{"title_page": "Yves Tumor", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Yves Tumor\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = no\n| birth_name       = Sean Bowie\n| alias            = {{hlist|Teams|Bekel\u00e9 Berhanu|Rajel Ali|Shanti|Yvesie Ray Vaughan}}\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Miami, Florida]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Electronic music|Electronic]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/sep/22/one-to-watch-yves-tumor-safe-in-hands-love |title=One to watch: Yves Tumor |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=September 22, 2018 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"P4K\">{{cite web |last=Frank |first=Alex |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/rising/10003-the-disgusting-beauty-of-enigmatic-experimentalist-yves-tumor |title=The Disgusting Beauty of Enigmatic Experimentalist Yves Tumor |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=January 11, 2017 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>|[[Experimental music|experimental]]<ref name=\"P4K\"/><ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Mykki Blanco]]|[[James Ferraro]]|[[Chino Amobi]]|[[Dev Hynes]]|[[Ecco2K]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|synthesizer|keyboards|guitar|bass|drums}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[PAN (record label)|PAN]]|[[Warp (record label)|Warp]]}}\n}}\n'''Sean Bowie''', best known by the recording alias '''Yves Tumor''', is an American [[record producer|producer]] of [[Experimental music|experimental]] [[electronic music]], born in [[Miami, Florida]] and currently based in [[Turin]], Italy.<ref>{{cite web |last=McDermott |first=Patrick D. |url=https://www.thefader.com/2016/10/05/fader-mix-yves-tumor |title=FADER Mix: Yves Tumor |work=[[The Fader]] |date=October 5, 2016 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://yves-tumor.bandcamp.com |title=Bandcamp: Yves Tumor |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nRaised in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], Tumor started making music at age 17 as an outlet away from \"dull, conservative surroundings.\" They taught themself to play drums, bass, guitar, and keyboards. Describing their experience growing up in Tennessee as unpleasant, they moved at age 20 to San Diego, and after college to Los Angeles, where they met [[Mykki Blanco]] in 2012, with whom they later toured for two and a half years throughout Europe and Asia.<ref name=\"Dazed\">{{cite web |last=Bulut |first=Selim |url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/32976/1/yves-tumor-serpent-music-album-stream-interview |title=Yves Tumor is making mood music in spiritual solitude |work=[[Dazed]] |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 2010s, Tumor recorded as Teams, and made music which [[AllMusic]] described as \"post-[[chillwave]]\". They debuted their Yves Tumor project in 2015 with an EP for Berlin's experimental club label Janus, and another one for Blanco's label, Dogfood MG.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ballard |first=Thea |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/yves-tumor-experiencing-the-deposit-of-faith |title=Yves Tumor: Experiencing the Deposit of Faith Album Review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=September 23, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |last=Simpson |first=Paul |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/yves-tumor-mn0003438593/biography |title=Yves Tumor {{!}} Biography & History |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Pearl |first=Max |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/36226 |title=RA News: PAN signs Yves Tumor for debut album, Serpent Music |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=September 1, 2016 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref> That same year, they self-released their first album, ''When Man Fails You'' (which would later be re-released by Apothecary Compositions on April 29, 2016).<ref>{{cite web |last=Clare Welsh |first=April |url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/09/01/mykki-blanco-affiliate-yves-tumor-to-release-serpent-music-on-pan |title=Mykki Blanco affiliate Yves Tumor to release Serpent Music on PAN |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |date=September 1, 2016 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AC\">{{cite web |url=https://apothecarycompositions.bandcamp.com/album/when-man-fails-you |title=When Man Fails You {{!}} Apothecary Compositions |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Tumor signed with PAN Records and released its label debut, ''Serpent Music''. They had worked on the album for three years after moving to [[Leipzig]], Germany. The album was recorded between Miami, Leipzig, Los Angeles and Berlin.<ref name=\"Dazed\"/> In ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''{{'}}s review of the album, critic Andy Beta compared Tumor's musical style to [[James Ferraro]] and [[Dean Blunt]], and noted their use of \"unsettling percussive loops and field recordings to create a mood as if lost in a strange urban landscape\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Beta |first=Andy |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22472-serpent-music |title=Yves Tumor: Serpent Music Album Review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=October 6, 2016 |accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Tumor released a compilation album titled ''Experiencing the Deposit of Faith'' for free. Later that week, it was revealed through a tour announcement that Tumor had signed to [[Warp (record label)|Warp Records]]. Following the announcement, they embarked on a tour with a new [[audiovisual]] show.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ryce |first=Andrew |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/40005 |title=RA News: Yves Tumor signs to Warp Records |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=September 15, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Bowe |first=Miles |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/09/15/yves-tumor-warp-records-album-stream-experiencing-deposit-faith |title=Yves Tumor signs to Warp, releases new album Experiencing The Deposit Of Faith |work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |date=September 15, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Tumor released their Warp debut, ''[[Safe in the Hands of Love]]'', with no prior announcement. It was preceded by the singles \"Noid\" on July 24, \"Licking an Orchid\" featuring James K on August 29, and \"Lifetime\" on September 3. The album received universal acclaim from music critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/safe-in-the-hands-of-love/yves-tumor |title=Safe in the Hands of Love by Yves Tumor Reviews and Tracks |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref> ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s Jayson Greene stated in their review that the album \"dwarfs everything the artist has released by several orders of magnitude. The leap is so audacious it's disorienting.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Greene |first=Jayson |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/yves-tumor-safe-in-the-hands-of-love |title=Yves Tumor: Safe in the Hands of Love Album Review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=September 7, 2018 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTumor's fourth album, ''Heaven to a Tortured Mind'', was released on April 3, 2020, preceded on March 3 by the single \"Kerosene\" featuring Diana Gordon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-yves-tumor-new-song-kerosene/|title=Listen to Yves Tumor\u2019s New Song \"Kerosene\"|website=Pitchfork|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> [[Alexis Petridis]], reviewing the album for ''[[The Guardian]]'', awarded it Album of the Week, describing it as \"extraordinary: experimental, capable of any genre, with an internal logic powering its shifts in mood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/02/yves-tumor-heaven-to-a-tortured-mind-album-review-warp|work=The Guardian|title=Yves Tumor: Heaven to a Tortured Mind review \u2013 strong, wrong songs of a rare genius|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nTumor has cited [[Throbbing Gristle]] as a major influence, saying: \"There's something about their music, like the hypnotic trance vibes, that really influenced me.\"<ref name=\"Dazed\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''When Man Fails You''\n|\n* Released: July 2, 2015<ref>{{cite web |last=Mashurova |first=Nina |url=http://www.imposemagazine.com/bytes/new-music/yves-tumor-when-man-fails-you |title=Yves Tumor, When Man Fails You |work=[[Impose (magazine)|Impose]] |date=July 2, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* Label: Self-released{{efn|Re-released by Apothecary Compositions on April 29, 2016, on cassette and digital download.<ref name=\"AC\"/>}}\n* Format: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Compact cassette|cassette]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Serpent Music''\n|\n* Released: September 22, 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yves-tumor.bandcamp.com/album/serpent-music |title=Serpent Music {{!}} Yves Tumor |work=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* Label: PAN\n* Format: [[Phonograph record|LP]], digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Safe in the Hands of Love]]''\n|\n* Released: September 5, 2018\n* Label: [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]\n* Format: LP, [[Compact disc|CD]], digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Heaven to a Tortured Mind''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/yves-tumor-announces-new-album-shares-video-for-new-song-watch/|title=Yves Tumor Announces New Album, Shares Video for New Song: Watch|first=Quinn|last=Moreland|date=Feb 18, 2020|accessdate=Feb 19, 2020|publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: April 3, 2020\n* Label: Warp\n* Format: LP, CD, digital download\n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Experiencing the Deposit of Faith''\n|\n* Released: September 13, 2017<ref>{{cite web |last=Durston |first=Tom |url=https://inverted-audio.com/yves-tumor-signs-warp-records-offers-free-compilation-experiencing-deposit-faith |title=Yves Tumor signs to Warp Records and offers free compilation \u2018Experiencing The Deposit Of Faith\u2019 |work=Inverted Audio |date=September 16, 2017 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* Label: Self-released\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Noid\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/noid-single/1413304542 |title=Noid - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Safe in the Hands of Love''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Licking an Orchid\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/licking-an-orchid-feat-james-k-single/1429974177 |title=Licking an Orchid (feat. James K) - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><br>{{small|(featuring James K)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lifetime\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/lifetime-single/1434725767 |title=Lifetime - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Gospel for a New Century\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/gospel-for-a-new-century/1494929769?i=1494929770 |title=Gospel For A New Century - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"|  2020\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Heaven to a Tortured Mind''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Kerosene\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Romanticist\" / \"Dream Palette\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4AVYBSDL7LAOhK6Y5Hq0M7?si=A6sQpuqGTom0HEoTwnT7Yg |title=Romanticist / Dream Palette by Yves Tumor |work=[[Spotify]] |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8em;\"| Artist\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Histrionic I\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Mykki Blanco]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Mykki Blanco Presents C-ORE''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mykkiblanco.bandcamp.com/album/mykki-blanco-presents-c-ore |title=Mykki Blanco Presents C-ORE {{!}} Mykki Blanco |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Childish\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Histrionic II\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Histrionic III / Skunk of the Earth\"\n|}\n\n===Remixes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Artist\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Zure\"<br>{{small|(Yves Tumor Obsession Edit)}}\n| 2017\n| [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]]\n| ''[[ASYNC \u2013 REMODELS|Async Remodels]]\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Altar\"<br>{{small|(Ruined by Yves Tumor)}}\n| 2018\n| [[Alice Glass]]\n| ''[[Alice Glass (EP)#Alice Glass (Remixes)|Alice Glass (Remixes)]]''\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tumor, Yves}}\n[[Category:Ambient musicians]]\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:American experimental musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Knoxville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Warp (record label) artists]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Yves Tumor\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = no\n| birth_name       = Sean Bowie\n| alias            = {{hlist|Teams|Bekel\u00e9 Berhanu|Rajel Ali|Shanti|Yvesie Ray Vaughan}}\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Miami, Florida]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Electronic music|Electronic]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/sep/22/one-to-watch-yves-tumor-safe-in-hands-love |title=One to watch: Yves Tumor |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=September 22, 2018 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"P4K\">{{cite web |last=Frank |first=Alex |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/rising/10003-the-disgusting-beauty-of-enigmatic-experimentalist-yves-tumor |title=The Disgusting Beauty of Enigmatic Experimentalist Yves Tumor |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=January 11, 2017 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>|[[Experimental music|experimental]]<ref name=\"P4K\"/><ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Mykki Blanco]]|[[James Ferraro]]|[[Chino Amobi]]|[[Dev Hynes]]|[[Ecco2K]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|synthesizer|keyboards|guitar|bass|drums}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[PAN (record label)|PAN]]|[[Warp (record label)|Warp]]}}\n}}\n'''Sean Bowie''', best known by the recording alias '''Yves Tumor''', is an American [[record producer|producer]] of [[Experimental music|experimental]] [[electronic music]], born in [[Miami, Florida]] and currently based in [[Turin]], Italy.<ref>{{cite web |last=McDermott |first=Patrick D. |url=https://www.thefader.com/2016/10/05/fader-mix-yves-tumor |title=FADER Mix: Yves Tumor |work=[[The Fader]] |date=October 5, 2016 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://yves-tumor.bandcamp.com |title=Bandcamp: Yves Tumor |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nRaised in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], Tumor started making music at age 17 as an outlet away from \"dull, conservative surroundings.\" They taught themself to play drums, bass, guitar, and keyboards. Describing their experience growing up in Tennessee as unpleasant, they moved at age 20 to San Diego, and after college to Los Angeles, where they met [[Mykki Blanco]] in 2012, whom they later toured with for two and a half years throughout Europe and Asia.<ref name=\"Dazed\">{{cite web |last=Bulut |first=Selim |url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/32976/1/yves-tumor-serpent-music-album-stream-interview |title=Yves Tumor is making mood music in spiritual solitude |work=[[Dazed]] |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 2010s, Tumor recorded as Teams, and made music which [[AllMusic]] described as \"post-[[chillwave]]\". They debuted their Yves Tumor project in 2015 with an EP for Berlin's experimental club label Janus, and another one for Blanco's label, Dogfood MG.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ballard |first=Thea |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/yves-tumor-experiencing-the-deposit-of-faith |title=Yves Tumor: Experiencing the Deposit of Faith Album Review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=September 23, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |last=Simpson |first=Paul |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/yves-tumor-mn0003438593/biography |title=Yves Tumor {{!}} Biography & History |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Pearl |first=Max |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/36226 |title=RA News: PAN signs Yves Tumor for debut album, Serpent Music |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=September 1, 2016 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref> That same year, they self-released their first album, ''When Man Fails You'' (which would later be re-released by Apothecary Compositions on April 29, 2016).<ref>{{cite web |last=Clare Welsh |first=April |url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/09/01/mykki-blanco-affiliate-yves-tumor-to-release-serpent-music-on-pan |title=Mykki Blanco affiliate Yves Tumor to release Serpent Music on PAN |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |date=September 1, 2016 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AC\">{{cite web |url=https://apothecarycompositions.bandcamp.com/album/when-man-fails-you |title=When Man Fails You {{!}} Apothecary Compositions |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Tumor signed with PAN Records and released its label debut, ''Serpent Music''. They had worked on the album for three years after moving to [[Leipzig]], Germany. The album was recorded between Miami, Leipzig, Los Angeles and Berlin.<ref name=\"Dazed\"/> In ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''{{'}}s review of the album, critic Andy Beta compared Tumor's musical style to [[James Ferraro]] and [[Dean Blunt]], and noted their use of \"unsettling percussive loops and field recordings to create a mood as if lost in a strange urban landscape\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Beta |first=Andy |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22472-serpent-music |title=Yves Tumor: Serpent Music Album Review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=October 6, 2016 |accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Tumor released a compilation album titled ''Experiencing the Deposit of Faith'' for free. Later that week, it was revealed through a tour announcement that Tumor had signed to [[Warp (record label)|Warp Records]]. Following the announcement, they embarked on a tour with a new [[audiovisual]] show.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ryce |first=Andrew |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/40005 |title=RA News: Yves Tumor signs to Warp Records |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=September 15, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Bowe |first=Miles |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/09/15/yves-tumor-warp-records-album-stream-experiencing-deposit-faith |title=Yves Tumor signs to Warp, releases new album Experiencing The Deposit Of Faith |work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |date=September 15, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Tumor released their Warp debut, ''[[Safe in the Hands of Love]]'', with no prior announcement. It was preceded by the singles \"Noid\" on July 24, \"Licking an Orchid\" featuring James K on August 29, and \"Lifetime\" on September 3. The album received universal acclaim from music critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/safe-in-the-hands-of-love/yves-tumor |title=Safe in the Hands of Love by Yves Tumor Reviews and Tracks |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref> ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s Jayson Greene stated in their review that the album \"dwarfs everything the artist has released by several orders of magnitude. The leap is so audacious it's disorienting.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Greene |first=Jayson |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/yves-tumor-safe-in-the-hands-of-love |title=Yves Tumor: Safe in the Hands of Love Album Review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=September 7, 2018 |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTumor's fourth album, ''Heaven to a Tortured Mind'', was released on April 3, 2020, preceded on March 3 by the single \"Kerosene\" featuring Diana Gordon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-yves-tumor-new-song-kerosene/|title=Listen to Yves Tumor\u2019s New Song \"Kerosene\"|website=Pitchfork|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> [[Alexis Petridis]], reviewing the album for ''[[The Guardian]]'', awarded it Album of the Week, describing it as \"extraordinary: experimental, capable of any genre, with an internal logic powering its shifts in mood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/02/yves-tumor-heaven-to-a-tortured-mind-album-review-warp|work=The Guardian|title=Yves Tumor: Heaven to a Tortured Mind review \u2013 strong, wrong songs of a rare genius|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nTumor has cited [[Throbbing Gristle]] as a major influence, saying: \"There's something about their music, like the hypnotic trance vibes, that really influenced me.\"<ref name=\"Dazed\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''When Man Fails You''\n|\n* Released: July 2, 2015<ref>{{cite web |last=Mashurova |first=Nina |url=http://www.imposemagazine.com/bytes/new-music/yves-tumor-when-man-fails-you |title=Yves Tumor, When Man Fails You |work=[[Impose (magazine)|Impose]] |date=July 2, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* Label: Self-released{{efn|Re-released by Apothecary Compositions on April 29, 2016, on cassette and digital download.<ref name=\"AC\"/>}}\n* Format: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Compact cassette|cassette]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Serpent Music''\n|\n* Released: September 22, 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yves-tumor.bandcamp.com/album/serpent-music |title=Serpent Music {{!}} Yves Tumor |work=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* Label: PAN\n* Format: [[Phonograph record|LP]], digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Safe in the Hands of Love]]''\n|\n* Released: September 5, 2018\n* Label: [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]\n* Format: LP, [[Compact disc|CD]], digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Heaven to a Tortured Mind''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/yves-tumor-announces-new-album-shares-video-for-new-song-watch/|title=Yves Tumor Announces New Album, Shares Video for New Song: Watch|first=Quinn|last=Moreland|date=Feb 18, 2020|accessdate=Feb 19, 2020|publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: April 3, 2020\n* Label: Warp\n* Format: LP, CD, digital download\n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Experiencing the Deposit of Faith''\n|\n* Released: September 13, 2017<ref>{{cite web |last=Durston |first=Tom |url=https://inverted-audio.com/yves-tumor-signs-warp-records-offers-free-compilation-experiencing-deposit-faith |title=Yves Tumor signs to Warp Records and offers free compilation \u2018Experiencing The Deposit Of Faith\u2019 |work=Inverted Audio |date=September 16, 2017 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* Label: Self-released\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Noid\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/noid-single/1413304542 |title=Noid - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Safe in the Hands of Love''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Licking an Orchid\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/licking-an-orchid-feat-james-k-single/1429974177 |title=Licking an Orchid (feat. James K) - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><br>{{small|(featuring James K)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lifetime\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/lifetime-single/1434725767 |title=Lifetime - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Gospel for a New Century\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/gospel-for-a-new-century/1494929769?i=1494929770 |title=Gospel For A New Century - Single by Yves Tumor on Apple Music |work=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"|  2020\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Heaven to a Tortured Mind''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Kerosene\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Romanticist\" / \"Dream Palette\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4AVYBSDL7LAOhK6Y5Hq0M7?si=A6sQpuqGTom0HEoTwnT7Yg |title=Romanticist / Dream Palette by Yves Tumor |work=[[Spotify]] |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8em;\"| Artist\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Histrionic I\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Mykki Blanco]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Mykki Blanco Presents C-ORE''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mykkiblanco.bandcamp.com/album/mykki-blanco-presents-c-ore |title=Mykki Blanco Presents C-ORE {{!}} Mykki Blanco |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Childish\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Histrionic II\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Histrionic III / Skunk of the Earth\"\n|}\n\n===Remixes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Artist\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Zure\"<br>{{small|(Yves Tumor Obsession Edit)}}\n| 2017\n| [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]]\n| ''[[ASYNC \u2013 REMODELS|Async Remodels]]\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Altar\"<br>{{small|(Ruined by Yves Tumor)}}\n| 2018\n| [[Alice Glass]]\n| ''[[Alice Glass (EP)#Alice Glass (Remixes)|Alice Glass (Remixes)]]''\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tumor, Yves}}\n[[Category:Ambient musicians]]\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:American experimental musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Knoxville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Warp (record label) artists]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Dom Kaos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career:syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yves_Tumor"}
{"title_page": "Charleston church shooting", "text_new": "{{redirect|2015 Charleston shooting|the shooting by a North Charleston police officer|Shooting of Walter Scott}}\n{{short description|Mass shooting in Charleston, South Carolina, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Charleston church shooting\n| partof      = [[Far-right terrorism in the United States]]\n| image       = Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal (AME) Church Corrected.jpg <!-- Better image that relates more to the shooting needed, examples: rescue response, aftermath picture -->\n| image_upright = \n| alt         = A white-painted church at sunset.\n| caption     = The [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in 2008\n| map = {{Location map many | South Carolina#United States\n| width = 250\n| label = Charleston\n| position = center\n| background = #FFFFDD\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|47|15|N|79|55|59|W}}\n}}\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     = Charleston, South Carolina\n| map_caption = \n| location    = [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]]<br />[[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina]], [[United States]]\n| target      = [[African American]] churchgoers\n| coordinates = {{Coord|32|47|15|N|79|55|59|W|display=inline,title}}  \n| date        = {{start date|2015|06|17}}\n| time        = {{circa}} 9:05 p.m. &ndash; c. 9:11 p.m.<ref name=\"ABC.Documents\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/police-documents-reveal-deadly-minutes-inside-south-carolina/story?id=34836336|title=New Police Documents Reveal Deadly Minutes Inside South Carolina Church|publisher=ABC News|date=October 29, 2015|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| timezone    = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| type        = [[Mass shooting]]<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-Shooting-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Bever|first1=Lindsey|last2=Costa|first2=Robert|title=9 dead in shooting at historic Charleston African American church. Police chief calls it \u2018hate crime.\u2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/17/white-gunman-sought-in-shooting-at-historic-charleston-african-ame-church/|accessdate=June 18, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref><br />[[Hate crime]]<br />\n| fatalities  = 9<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-Shooting-2015\" /><ref name=\"MyFox8-RoofConfesses-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://myfox8.com/2015/06/19/charleston-shooting-suspect-dylan-roof-confesses-to-killing-9-people/|title=Dylann Roof confesses to killing 9 people in Charleston church, wanting to start 'race war'|publisher=[[WGHP]]|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 1<ref name=\"DailyMirror-CharlestonChurch-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/charleston-church-shooting-first-picture-5904803|title=Charleston church shooting: First picture of 'gunman' on the run after nine people shot dead|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| perp     = [[Dylann Roof]]<ref name=\"Telegraph-RoofConfesses-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/11686370/Dylann-Roof-confesses-to-Charleston-shooting-as-governer-calls-for-death-penalty.html|title=Dylann Roof confesses to Charleston shooting as governor calls for death penalty|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Andrew|last=Marszal}}</ref>\n| weapons     = [[Glock 41]] [[.45 ACP|.45-caliber]] [[handgun]]\n| numparts    = <!-- or | numpart     = -->\n| dfens       = <!-- or | dfen        = -->\n| motive      = [[Right-wing terrorism|Far-right extremism]], [[white supremacy]]/[[white nationalism|nationalism]]\n| website     = <!-- URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n{{Terrorism}}\n\nThe '''Charleston church shooting''' (also known as the '''Charleston church massacre''')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html|title=Church Massacre Suspect Held as Charleston Grieves|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/dylann-roof-indicted-murder-church-massacre-n388066|title=Dylann Roof Indicted for Murder in Charleston Church Massacre|publisher=NBC News|date=July 7, 2015|access-date=November 12, 2015|first=Tracy|last=Connor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/charleston-police-church-shooting|title=Nine dead in Charleston church massacre|publisher=MSNBC|date=June 17, 2015|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> was a [[mass shooting]] on June 17, 2015, in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], in which nine [[African Americans]] were killed during a Bible study at the [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]]. Among those killed  was the senior pastor, [[South Carolina Senate|state senator]] [[Clementa C. Pinckney]]; three victims survived. This church is one of the oldest [[black church]]es in the United States, and it has long been a center for organizing related to [[civil rights]].\n\nThe morning after the attack, police arrested [[Dylann Roof]] in [[Shelby, North Carolina]]; the 21-year-old [[White supremacy|white supremacist]] had attended the Bible study before shooting. He was found to have targeted members of this church because of its history and stature. Roof was found [[competent to stand trial]] in [[United States federal court|federal court]]. \n\nIn December 2016 he was convicted of 33 [[Federal crime|federal]] [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crime]] and [[murder]] charges. On January 10, 2017, he was [[Capital punishment by the United States federal government|sentenced to death]] for these crimes.<ref name=\"jury-dylann-roof-death-penalty\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/11/us/dylann-roof-sentencing/|publisher=CNN|title=Victim's dad warns Dylann Roof: 'Your creator ... he's coming for you'|access-date=April 14, 2017|date=January 11, 2017}}</ref> Roof was separately charged with nine counts of murder in the [[South Carolina government and politics#Judicial branch|South Carolina]] [[State court (United States)|state court]]s. In April 2017, Roof pleaded guilty to all nine state charges in order to avoid a second death sentence, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for each. He will receive automatic appeals of his death sentence, but may eventually be executed by the federal justice system.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Harriet|last1=McLeod|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-south-carolina-shooting-roof-idUSKBN17C15W|title=Charleston church shooter pleads guilty to state murder counts|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=April 10, 2017|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Andrew|last1=Knapp|first2=Abigail|last2=Darlington|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/news/dylann-roof-s-life-sentences-on-state-murder-charges-surest/article_4a8b54ec-1df1-11e7-af4f-3f880fee388b.html|title=Dylann Roof's 9 life sentences on state murder charges 'surest' route to federal execution, prosecutor says|work=Post & Courier|date=April 10, 2017|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRoof espoused [[racial hatred]] in both a website [[manifesto]] published before the shooting, and a journal written from jail afterward. Roof posted photos on his website with emblems associated with [[white supremacy]] and with the [[Confederate battle flag]]. The shooting triggered debate on [[Modern display of the Confederate flag| modern display]] of the flag and other memorialization of the Confederacy. Following these murders, the [[South Carolina General Assembly]] voted to remove the flag from State Capitol grounds.\n\nAt the time, this was one of two of the deadliest mass shootings at an American [[place of worship]], alongside [[Waddell Buddhist temple shooting|a 1991 attack]] at a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] temple in [[Waddell, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah Pulliam|last=Bailey|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/06/18/the-charleston-shooting-is-the-largest-mass-shooting-in-a-house-of-worship-since-1991/|title=The Charleston shooting is the largest mass shooting in a house of worship since 1991|work=The Washington Post|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref> Fatalities at the 2017 [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]] and the 2018 [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]] have since exceeded it.\n\n==Background==\nFounded in 1816, the church has played an important role in the [[history of South Carolina]], including the [[Slavery in the United States|slavery era]] and Reconstruction, the [[civil rights movement]], and [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref name=\"NYTimes-DemandSimple-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/10/magazine/our-demand-is-simple-stop-killing-us.html|title=Our Demand Is Simple: Stop Killing Us|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 4, 2015|first=Jay Caspian|last=Kang}}</ref> Founded in 1816, this is the oldest [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in the [[Southern United States|South]], often referred to as \"Mother Emanuel\". The AME Church was founded in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] in 1814 as the first independent black denomination.<ref name=\"CNN-Shooting-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Payne|first1=Ed|title=Charleston church shooting: Multiple fatalities in South Carolina, source says|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/17/us/charleston-south-carolina-shooting/|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mullikin-CivilRightsRide-2013\">{{cite web|last1=Pinckney|first1=Reverend Honorable Clementa C.|title=Civil Rights Ride 2013 \u2013 Clementa C. Pinckney, SC Senate, Pastor Mother Emanuel AME|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XP35_JVnP6g|website=Mullikin Law Firm|access-date=June 18, 2015|date=February 20, 2015}}</ref> It is an [[Black church|historically black congregation]], one of the oldest south of [[Baltimore]]. \n\nWhen one of the church's co-founders, [[Denmark Vesey]], was suspected of planning a slave rebellion in Charleston in 1822, 35 people, including Vesey, were hanged and the church was burned down.<ref name=\"PostCourier-NineShot-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20150617/PC16/150619408|title=Nine shot, multiple fatalities reported in downtown church shooting|newspaper=[[The Post and Courier]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Zimmerman21June>{{ cite news|url= https://newrepublic.com/article/122102/was-emanuel-church-founder-denmark-vesey-victim-racist-paranoia | title=Was the Co-Founder of Charleston's Emanuel Church a Victim of Racist Paranoia, Too?|date=June 21, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|work=The New Republic|first=Jonathan|last=Zimmerman}}</ref> Charleston citizens accepted the claim that a slave rebellion was to begin at the stroke of midnight on June 16, 1822, and to erupt the following day; the shooting in 2015 occurred on the 193rd anniversary of the thwarted uprising.<ref name=\"Nation-WhiteSupremacy-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/210305/charleston-massacre-and-cunning-white-supremacy|title=The Charleston Massacre and the Cunning of White Supremacy|first=Greg|last=Grandin|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Nation]]}}</ref> As the rebuilt church was formally shuttered with other all-black congregations by the city in 1834, the congregation met in secret until 1865 when it was formally reorganized, and acquired the name Emanuel (\"God with us\").<ref name=\"AME-7thDistrict-MotherEmanual\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ame7.org/history/pages/sc_history.htm|title = Mother Emanuel, Charleston, SC|accessdate = June 19, 2015|website = 7th District AME Church, South Carolina|publisher = 7th District AME Office|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150618115132/http://www.ame7.org/history/pages/sc_history.htm|archivedate = June 18, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref> It rebuilt based on a design by Denmark Vesey's son.<ref name=\"Nation-WhiteSupremacy-2015\"/> That structure was badly damaged in the [[1886 Charleston earthquake]].<ref name=NPSEmanuel>{{cite web|work=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/charleston/ema.htm|title=Emanuel AME Church|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost-PainfulChapter-2015\"/> The current building dates from 1891.<ref name=\"Nation-WhiteSupremacy-2015\"/><ref name=\"AME-7thDistrict-MotherEmanual\"/>\n\nThe church's senior pastor, the Rev. [[Clementa C. Pinckney]], had held rallies after the [[shooting of Walter Scott]] by a white police officer two months earlier, in nearby [[North Charleston]]. As a [[South Carolina Senate|state senator]], Pinckney pushed for legislation requiring police to wear [[body worn video|body cameras]].<ref name=\"Heavy-Pinckney5Fact-2015\">{{cite news|last1 = Cleary|first1 = Tom|title = Clementa Pinckney Dead: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url = http://heavy.com/news/2015/06/clementa-pinckney-dead-charleston-church-shooting-victim-black-church-pastor-ame-shot-injury/|accessdate = June 17, 2015|publisher = [[Heavy.com]]|date = June 18, 2015}}</ref> \n\nSeveral commentators noted a similarity between the massacre at Emanuel AME and the 1963 [[16th Street Baptist Church bombing]] of a politically active African-American church in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], where the [[Ku Klux Klan]] (KKK) killed four black girls and injured fourteen others, during the civil rights movement. This attack created support for federal civil rights legislation.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-PainfulChapter-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/18/for-charlestons-emanuel-a-m-e-church-one-of-the-oldest-in-america-shooting-is-another-painful-chapter-in-long-history/|title=For Charleston's Emanuel AME Church, shooting is another painful chapter in rich history|first=Sarah|last=Kaplan|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CharlestonFunerals\"/>\n\nNumerous scholars, journalists, activists and politicians have emphasized placing the attack within the broader context of [[racism in the United States]] rather than seeing it as an isolated event. <!--Attacks on black churches were a common occurrence throughout the 19th and 20th centuries. In the late 1860s, following the [[American Civil War]], racial violence by [[white supremacists]] in the South was ubiquitous during the [[Reconstruction Era]], and a federal grand jury determined that the Klan was a \"terrorist organization\" in 1870.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://isbn.nu/toc/9780807119532 |title=White Terror: The Ku Klux Klan Conspiracy and Southern Reconstruction|last=Trelease|first=Allen W.|publisher=Louisiana State University Press: 1995}}</ref><ref name=\"Vox-ShootingTerrorism-2015\">{{cite web|first=Dara|last=Lind|url=http://www.vox.com/2015/6/18/8803721/charleston-terrorism-racism|title=Why calling the Charleston shooting terrorism is important to so many people|work=[[Vox (magazine)|Vox]]|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>--> In 1996, Congress had passed the Church Arson Prevention Act, making it a federal crime to damage religious property because of its \"racial or ethnic character\", in response to a spate of 154 [[church arson|suspicious church burnings]] since 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/churches/churches.htm|title=In Church Fires, a Pattern but No Conspiracy|work=The Washington Post|date=June 19, 1996|access-date=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost-MentallyIll-2015\">{{Cite news|first = Anthea|last = Butler|title = Shooters of color are called 'terrorists' and 'thugs.' Why are white shooters called 'mentally ill'?|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/06/18/call-the-charleston-church-shooting-what-it-is-terrorism/|newspaper = [[The Washington Post]]|date = June 18, 2015|access-date = June 18, 2015}}</ref> More recent arson attacks against black churches included a black church in [[Massachusetts]] that was burned down the day after the [[first inauguration of Barack Obama]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/15/us/15brfs-CONVICTIONIN_BRF.html|title=Massachusetts: Conviction in Racially Motivated Fire|work=The New York Times|date=April 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Atlantic-ThugsTerrorists-2015\">{{Cite web|title = Thugs and Terrorists Have Attacked Black Churches for Generations|url = https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/06/thugs-and-terrorists-have-plagued-black-churches-for-generations/396212/|date = June 18, 2015|access-date = June 18, 2015|work = [[The Atlantic]]|first = Connor|last = Friedersdorf}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJazeera-BLM-2015\">{{Cite web|title = Black lives \u2014 and churches \u2014 matter|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2015/06/black-lives-churches-matter-charleston-150618060102973.html|publisher = [[Al Jazeera]]|date = June 18, 2015|access-date = June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian-RevGreer-2015\">{{Cite web|title = Terrorism in Charleston demands the government act like black lives matter {{!}} The Rev Broderick Greer|url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jun/18/terrorism-charleston-government-black-lives-matter|website = [[The Guardian]]|date = June 18, 2015|accessdate = June 18, 2015|first = Reverend Broderick|last = Greer}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting==\nAt around 9:05&nbsp;p.m. EDT on Wednesday, June 17, 2015, the [[City of Charleston Police Department|Charleston Police Department]] began receiving calls of a shooting at Emanuel AME Church.<ref name=\"ABC.Documents\"/><ref name=\"PostCourier-NineShot-2015\"/> A man described as white, with sandy-blond hair, around 21 years old and {{convert|5|ft|9|in|cm}} in height, wearing a gray sweatshirt and jeans and opened fire with a [[Glock 41]] [[.45 ACP|.45-caliber]] [[handgun]]<ref>{{cite web | first=Ray |last=Sanchez |first2=Ed |last2=Payne |title=Charleston church shooting: Who is Dylann Roof? |date=June 23, 2015 |access-date=July 8, 2015 |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting-suspect/index.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701184533/http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting-suspect/index.html |archivedate=July 1, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> on a group of people inside the church at a [[Bible study (Christian)|Bible study]] attended by Pinckney. He had first attended the meeting as a participant that evening. The shooter then fled the scene.<ref name=\"Reuters-GunmanAtLarge-2015\">{{cite news | last1=McLeod| first1=Harriet| title=Gunman at large after killing nine at black South Carolina church| url=https://news.yahoo.com/shooting-erupts-church-charleston-south-carolina-021744448.html| accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher =[[Yahoo! News]]| agency=Reuters|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EverythingKnown\">{{cite web | url=http://time.com/3926112/charleston-shooting-latest/| title=Everything We Know About the Charleston Shooting| work=Time| date=June 18, 2015| accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ChillingCase\">{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/06/19/dylann-roof-charleston-police-charged--murder-black-church/28975573/| title=Affidavits spell out chilling case against Dylann Roof| work=USA Today| date=June 19, 2015| accessdate=June 19, 2015| first=Yamiche| last=Alcindor| first2=Doug| last2=Stanglin}}</ref> He had been carrying eight [[Magazine (firearms)|magazines]] holding [[hollow-point bullet]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-roof-hate-crimes-20150722-story.html| title=Dylann Roof indicted on federal hate-crime charges in Charleston church shooting| work=Los Angeles Times| date=July 22, 2015| accessdate=July 22, 2015| first=Timothy M.| last=Phelps}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dylann Roof entering Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, Charleston, South Carolina, 8 pm June 17, 2015.jpg|thumb|Dylann Roof entering Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church through a side door at 8:16 pm, as captured on CCTV]]\n\nDuring the hour preceding the attack, 13 people including the shooter participated in the Bible study.<ref name=\"ChurchShot\">{{cite web | url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/crime/pastor-8-others-fatally-shot-at-church-in-charleston-sc/ar-AAbLntz| title=Pastor, 8 others, fatally shot at church in Charleston, SC| publisher=MSN| date=June 18, 2015| accessdate=June 18, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618193308/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/crime/pastor-8-others-fatally-shot-at-church-in-charleston-sc/ar-AAbLntz| archive-date=June 18, 2015| url-status= dead}}</ref>  According to the accounts of people who talked to survivors, when the shooter walked into the historic African-American church, he immediately asked for Pinckney and sat down next to him, initially listening to others during the study.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/inside-charleston-bible-study-massacre/index.html| title=Inside the Bible Study Massacre: A mom 'laid in her son's blood'| last=Drash| first=Wayne| date=December 17, 2015| publisher=CNN| access-date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> He disagreed with some of the discussion of [[Religious text|Scripture]]. After other participants began praying,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.yahoo.com/charleston-church-shooting-survivor-describes-the-moment-suspected-gunman-dylann-roof-began-firing-221002383.html| title=Charleston church shooting survivor describes the moment suspected gunman Dylann Roof began firing| publisher=Yahoo! News| date=September 9, 2015| access-date=September 9, 2015| first=Jason| last=Sickles}}</ref> he stood up,<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/> and aimed a gun he pulled from a fanny pack at 87-year-old Susie Jackson. Jackson's nephew, 26-year-old Tywanza Sanders, tried to talk him down and asked him why he was attacking churchgoers. The shooter said, \"I have to do it. You rape our women and you're taking over our country. And you have to go.\" When he said he intended to shoot them all, Sanders dove in front of Jackson and was shot first. The shooter fired at the other victims, shouting [[racial epithets]]. He reportedly said, \"Y'all want something to pray about? I'll give you something to pray about.\"<ref name=Borden19June/> He reloaded his gun five times. Sanders' mother and his five-year-old niece, who also attended the study, survived the shooting by pretending to be dead on the floor.<ref name=\"RaceWar\">{{cite web | last1=Payne| first1=Ed| last2=Botelho| first2=Greg| url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting-main/| title=Charleston church shooting: Suspect confesses, says he sought race war| publisher=CNN|date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BroughtBack\">{{cite web | last1=Horowitz| first1=Jason| last2=Corasaniti| first2=Nick| last3=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a| first3=Richard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html| title=Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof Is Brought Back to Charleston| work=The New York Times| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost-SuspectCaptured-2015\"/>\n\nDot Scott, president of the local branch of the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]], said she had heard from victims' relatives that the shooter spared one woman (Polly Shepard),<ref>{{cite web | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/charleston-shooting-gunman-allegedly-survivor-inside-church/story?id=31872085| title=Charleston Shooting: What the Gunman Allegedly Told Churchgoers Before the Shooting| publisher=ABC News| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 18, 2015| first=Nikki| last=Battiste| first2=Emily| last2=Shapiro| first3=Matthew| last3=Stone}}</ref> saying that she could tell other people what happened.<ref name=\"ShootingSuspect\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/us/charleston-church-shooting-suspect/| title=Who is the Charleston church shooting suspect?| publisher=CNN| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> He asked, \"Did I shoot you?\" She replied, \"No.\" Then, he said, \"Good, 'cause we need someone to survive, because I'm gonna shoot myself, and you'll be the only survivor.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=Charleston Shooting: What the Gunman Allegedly Told Churchgoers Before the Shooting| url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/charleston-shooting-gunman-allegedly-survivor-inside-church/story?id=31872085| publisher=ABC News| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 22, 2015| first=Nikki| last=Battiste| first2=Emily| last2=Shapiro| first3=Matthew| last3=Stone}}</ref> According to the son of one victim, who spoke to that survivor, the shooter allegedly turned the gun to his own head and pulled the trigger, but discovered he was out of ammunition.<ref name=Phelps20June>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-dylann-roof-suicide-attempt-20150620-story.html| title=Dylann Roof tried to kill himself during attack, victim's son says| work=Los Angeles Times| date=June 20, 2015| access-date=June 22, 2015| first=Timothy M.| last=Phelps}}</ref> He left the church, reportedly after making another \"racially inflammatory statement\" over the victims' bodies.<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/> The entire shooting lasted for approximately six minutes.<ref name=\"ABC.Documents\"/>\n\nSeveral hours later, a [[bomb threat]] was called into the [[Courtyard by Marriott]] hotel on Calhoun Street. This complicated the police investigation of the shooting, as they needed to evacuate the immediate area.<ref name=\"PostCourier-NineShot-2015\"/><ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2015/jun/18/charleston-church-shooting-reports-fatalities-suspect-large-latest-updates| title= Charleston church shooting: police release image of suspect \u2013 latest updates| date=June 18, 2015| work=The Guardian| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Victims===\nThe victims, six women and three men, were all African-American members of the AME Church. Eight died at the scene; the ninth, Daniel Simmons, died at [[MUSC Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Former Mount Pleasant pastor among those slain| url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20150618/PC16/150619340/1177/daniel-l-simmons-74| work=The Post and Courier| date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 22, 2015| first=Tony| last=Bartelme}}</ref> They were all killed by multiple gunshots fired at close range.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-SuspectCaptured-2015\"/><ref name=\"RawEmotion\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/20/us/charleston-shooting-dylann-storm-roof.html| title=In Charleston, Raw Emotion at Hearing for Suspect in Church Shooting| work=The New York Times| date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 19, 2015| first=Nikita| last=Stewart| first2=Richard| last2=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref> Five persons survived the shooting unharmed, including Felicia Sanders, mother of slain victim Tywanza Sanders, and her five-year-old granddaughter, as well as Polly Sheppard, a Bible study member. Pinckney's wife and two daughters were inside the building during the shooting but were elsewhere.<ref name=\"DailyMirror-CharlestonChurch-2015\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20150619/PC16/150619306| title=In an hour, a church changes forever| work=Post and Courier| date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 20, 2015| first=Doug| last=Pardue| first2=Jennifer Berry| last2=Hawes}}</ref> Those killed were identified as:<ref>{{Cite web | title = Charleston Shooting Victims Identified| url = http://abcnews.go.com/US/charleston-shooting-victims-identified/story?id=31863489| publisher = ABC News| date = June 18, 2015| access-date = June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/us/charleston-church-shooting-victims/ | title=Charleston victims: 9 lives lost to family and community | publisher=CNN | date=June 19, 2015 | access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* [[Clementa C. Pinckney]] (41) \u2013 the church's pastor and a [[South Carolina Senate|South Carolina state senator]].\n* Cynthia Marie Graham Hurd (54) \u2013 a Bible study member and manager for the Charleston County Public Library system; sister of former state senator [[Malcolm Graham (politician)|Malcolm Graham]].\n* Susie Jackson (87) \u2013 a Bible study and church choir member. She was the oldest victim of the shooting.\n* Ethel Lee Lance (70) \u2013 the church's [[Sexton (office)|sexton]].\n* Depayne Middleton-Doctor (49) \u2013 a pastor who was also employed as a school administrator and admissions coordinator at [[Southern Wesleyan University]].\n* Tywanza Sanders (26) \u2013 a Bible study member; grandnephew of victim Susie Jackson. He was the youngest victim.\n* Daniel L. Simmons (74) \u2013 a pastor who also served at Greater Zion AME Church in [[Awendaw, South Carolina|Awendaw]].\n* Sharonda Coleman-Singleton (45) \u2013 a pastor; also a speech therapist and track coach at [[Goose Creek High School]]; mother of MLB prospect Chris Singleton.\n* Myra Thompson (59) \u2013 a Bible study teacher.\n{{Div col end}}\n\nThe victims were later collectively referred to as \"The Charleston Nine\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.laprogressive.com/charleston-nine/|title=Remembering The Charleston Nine| publisher=LA Progressive| date=June 17, 2016| access-date=June 21, 2016}}</ref> and \"The Emanuel Nine\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2017/01/10/the-emanuel-9-the-stories-of-dylann-roofs-victims.html| title=The Emanuel 9: The stories of Dylann Roof\u2019s victims| first=Meg| last=Kinnard| date=January 10, 2017| publisher=| via=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{Main|Dylann Roof}}\n\nDylann Storm Roof<ref name=CourtCaseOfficialName>{{Cite web|url=http://www5.rcgov.us/SCJDWEB/PublicIndex/PIError.aspx?County=40&CourtAgency=40216&Casenum=36973HB&CaseType=C&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=State of South Carolina vs Dylann Storm Roof}}</ref> was named by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) as the suspected killer after his father and uncle contacted police to positively identify him upon seeing security photos of him in the news.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/06/19/arrest-warrant-for-dylann-roof-for-charleston-shooting/28997521/|title=Dylann Roof's father, uncle called police to ID him in church shooting|work=USA Today|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Donna Leinwand|last=Leger}}</ref> Roof was born in [[Columbia, South Carolina]], and was living in largely African-American [[Eastover, South Carolina|Eastover]] at the time of the attack.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-SuspectCaptured-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/17/white-gunman-sought-in-shooting-at-historic-charleston-african-ame-church/|title=Church shooting suspect Dylann Roof captured amid hate crime investigation|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Roof had a prior police record consisting of two arrests, for trespassing and drug possession, both made in the months before the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kfor.com/2015/06/18/dylann-storm-roof-arrested-in-north-carolina-according-to-report/|title=Dylann Storm Roof arrested in North Carolina|publisher=[[KFOR-TV|KFOR]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Old|first1=Jason|title=Police: Dylann Roof arrested for trespassing, drug possession at Columbiana Centre|url=http://www.wistv.com/story/29353220/police-dylann-roof-arrested-for-trespassing-drug-possession-at-columbiana-centre|publisher=WISTV.com|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> According to then [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI Director]] [[James Comey]], a police report detailing Roof's admission to a narcotics offense should have prevented him from purchasing the weapon used in the shooting. An administrative error within the [[National Instant Criminal Background Check System]] (NICS) excluded Roof's admission (though not the arrest itself) from appearing on his mandatory background check.<ref name=Nakashima10July>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-accused-charleston-shooter-should-not-have-been-able-to-buy-gun/2015/07/10/0d09fda0-271f-11e5-b72c-2b7d516e1e0e_story.html?tid=HP_more?tid=HP_more|title=FBI: Breakdown in background check system allowed Dylann Roof to buy gun|work=The Washington Post|date=July 10, 2015|access-date=July 11, 2015|first=Ellen|last=Nakashima}}</ref><ref name=BBC10July>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-33487577|title=Charleston shooting: System failure 'allowed Roof to buy gun' - FBI|date=July 10, 2015|access-date=July 10, 2015|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHis [[Facebook]] page included an image of Roof wearing a jacket decorated with two [[emblem]]s popular among American [[white supremacist]]s: the [[Flag of Rhodesia|flag of the former]] [[Rhodesia]] (now known as [[Zimbabwe]]) and [[Flag of South Africa (1928\u20131994)|the flag of]] [[South Africa under apartheid|apartheid-era South Africa]].<ref name=\"nyt-ccs\">{{cite web|title=Charleston Church Shooting Suspect, Dylann Storm Roof, Is Captured|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/on-facebook-dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wears-symbols-of-white-supremacy.html|title=On Facebook, Dylann Roof, Charleston Suspect, Wears Symbols of White Supremacy|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dailybeast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2015/06/18/charleston-suspect-is-dylann-roof.html|title=Everything Known About Charleston Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof|work=The Daily Beast|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Roof reportedly told friends and neighbors he intended to kill people, including a plot to attack the [[College of Charleston]], but his claims were not taken seriously.<ref name=\"RoofFriend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/06/20/friend-dylann-roof-says-suspect-planned-attack-on-college-charleston/|title=Friend of Dylann Roof says suspect planned attack on College of Charleston|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RacialMotivation?\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/charleston-shooting-racial-motivation-dylann-storm-roof-told-black-neighbor-he-1974050|title=Charleston Shooting Racial Motivation? Dylann Storm Roof Told Black Neighbor He Planned On Killing|work=The International Business Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015|first=Clark|last=Mindock}}</ref> On June 20, bloggers discovered a website called \"The Last Rhodesian\" (www.lastrhodesian.com); it had been registered to a \"Dylann Roof\" on February 9, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Home \u2014 My website |url=http://lastrhodesian.com/ |date=June 20, 2015 |access-date=June 20, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620134455/http://lastrhodesian.com/ |archivedate=June 20, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Robles20June>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/us/dylann-storm-roof-photos-website-charleston-church-shooting.html|title=Dylann Storm Roof Photos Found on Website|last=Robles|first=Francis|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Gawker\">{{Cite web|title=Here Is What Appears to Be Dylann Roof's Racist Manifesto |url=http://gawker.com/here-is-what-appears-to-be-dylann-roofs-racist-manifest-1712767241 |work=Gawker |date=June 20, 2015 |access-date=June 20, 2015 |first=Brendan |last=O'Connor |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620195150/http://gawker.com/here-is-what-appears-to-be-dylann-roofs-racist-manifest-1712767241 |archivedate=June 20, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> The website included what appeared to be an unsigned manifesto containing Roof's opinions of \"Blacks\", \"Jews\", \"Hispanics\" and \"East Asians\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/210537/two-degrees-separation-between-dylann-roof-and-republican-party|title=The 2 Degrees of Separation Between Dylann Roof and the Republican Party|work=The Nation|date=June 22, 2015|access-date=June 23, 2015|first=Michelle|last=Goldberg}}</ref><ref name=Lewis21June>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/20/dylann-roof-fbi-website-manifesto-charleston-shooting|title=Dylann Roof: FBI probes manifesto and website linked to Charleston suspect|work=The Guardian|date=June 21, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|first1=Paul|last1=Lewis|first2=Amanda|last2=Holpuch|first3=Jessica|last3=Glenza}}</ref> as well a cache of photos, including an image of Roof posing with a handgun and a [[Confederate Battle Flag]].<ref name=Robles20June/> In this manifesto, Roof says he became \"racially aware\" as a result of the 2012 [[shooting of Trayvon Martin]], writing that when he learned about the incident, he read about it, concluding that [[George Zimmerman]] had been in the right. He didn't understand the controversy about it. He said he searched for \"black on White {{sic}} crime\"<!--Not a typo! The word \"White\" is capitalized in original--> on [[Google]] and found the website of the [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], where he read \"pages upon pages\" of cases involving black people murdering white people. Roof wrote that he had \"never been the same since that day\".<ref name = \"Gawker\"/>\n\nAccording to web server logs, Roof's website was last modified at 4:44&nbsp;p.m. on June 17, the day of the shooting, when Roof noted, \"[A]t the time of writing I am in a great hurry.\"<ref name=Robles20June/>\n\nAn unidentified source said interrogations with Roof after his arrest determined he had been planning the attack for around six months. He had researched Emanuel AME Church, and targeted it because of its role in [[African-American history]].<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/> A friend who briefly hid Roof's gun from him said, \"I don't think the church was his primary target because he told us he was going for the school. But I think he couldn't get into the school because of the security ... so I think he just settled for the church.\"<ref name=Weiss>{{cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/man-accused-of-church-killings-spoke-of-attacking-college/article_0329e2bf-5d5e-5a40-b8a0-f173160142d3.html|title=Man accused of church killings spoke of attacking college|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015|first=Mitch|last=Weiss|first2=Michael|last2=Biesecker}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Charlotte|last=Krol|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/11688181/Dylann-Roofs-friend-Charleston-church-wasnt-primary-target.html|title=Dylann Roof's friend: Charleston church 'wasn't primary target'|work=The Telegraph|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRoof's cellphone and computer were seized and subjected to FBI analysis. According to unnamed officials, he was in online communication with other white supremacists, who did not appear to have encouraged the massacre.<ref name=Schmidt3July>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/04/us/dylann-roof-was-in-contact-with-supremacists-officials-say.html|title=Charleston Suspect Was In Touch With Supremacists, Officials Say|date=July 3, 2015|access-date=July 3, 2015|first=Michael S.|last=Schmidt|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The investigation was said to have widened to include other persons of interest.<ref name=Monk2July>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestate.com/news/local/article26200726.html|first=John|last=Monk|date=July 2, 2015|access-date=July 3, 2015|title=EXCLUSIVE: Charges possible against church shooter\u2019s associates|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]}}</ref>\n\nFederal prosecutors said in August 2016 that Roof was \"self-radicalized\" online, instead of adopting his white supremacist ideology \"through his personal associations or experiences with white supremacist groups or individuals or others\".<ref name=\"WashPost.Self\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/08/22/prosecutors-say-accused-charleston-church-gunman-self-radicalized-online/|title=Prosecutors say Dylann Roof \u2018self-radicalized\u2019 online, wrote another manifesto in jail|work=The Washington Post|date=August 23, 2016|access-date=August 23, 2016|first=Mark|last=Berman}}</ref><ref name=\"Yahoo.Entrenched\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/feds-church-shooting-suspect-entrenched-beliefs-114157914.html|title=Feds: Church shooting suspect entrenched in his beliefs|publisher=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press|date=August 23, 2016|access-date=August 23, 2016|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref>\n\n==Criminal investigation==\n\n===Manhunt and capture===\nThe attack was treated as a [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crime]] by police. Officials from the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] were called in to assist in the investigation and manhunt.<ref name=\"EverythingKnown\"/>\n\nAt 10:44&nbsp;a.m., on the morning after the attack, Roof was captured in a traffic stop in [[Shelby, North Carolina]], approximately {{convert|245|mi|km}} from the shooting scene. A .45-caliber pistol was found in the car during the arrest.<ref name=\"WISTV-RoofCustody-2015\">{{cite news |title= Charleston church shooting suspect Dylann Roof in custody in NC |date= June 18, 2015 |work= [[WIS (TV)|WIS]] |publisher= WorldNow and WISTV |url= http://www.wistv.com/story/29351540/charleston-shooting-suspect-from-columbia-area |access-date= June 18, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170131150034/http://www.wistv.com/story/29351540/charleston-shooting-suspect-from-columbia-area |archive-date= January 31, 2017 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/us/charleston-south-carolina-shooting/index.html|title=Shooting suspect in custody after Charleston church massacre|publisher=CNN|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Police received a tip-off from a woman who recognized Roof and his car, a black [[Hyundai Elantra]] with South Carolina license plates and a three-flag [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|\"Confederate States of America\"]] bumper decoration,<ref name=Safi19June>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/19/charleston-shooting-florist-debbie-dills-hailed-a-hero-after-tailing-suspects-car|work=The Guardian|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Michael|last=Safi|title=Charleston shooting: florist Debbie Dills hailed a hero after tailing suspect's car}}</ref><ref name=Cush18June>{{cite news|url=http://gawker.com/dylann-roofs-car-like-s-c-statehouse-flies-a-confede-1712288717 |work=Gawker |title=Dylann Roof's car, like S.C. Statehouse, flies a Confederate Flag |first=Andy |last=Cush |date=June 18, 2015 |access-date=June 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619134327/http://gawker.com/dylann-roofs-car-like-s-c-statehouse-flies-a-confede-1712288717 |archivedate=June 19, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> on [[U.S. Route 74]], recalling security camera images taken at the church and distributed to the media. She later recalled, \"I got closer and saw that haircut. I was nervous. I had the worst feeling. Is that him or not him?\" She called her employer, who contacted local police, and then tailed the suspect's car for {{convert|35|mi|km}} until she was certain authorities were moving in for an arrest.<ref name=ShelbyStar>{{cite news|url=http://www.shelbystar.com/news/local/breaking-tip-from-kings-mountain-florists-led-to-charleston-shooting-suspect-s-arrest-1.492375|title=Tip from Kings Mountain florists led to Charleston shooting suspect's arrest|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015|work=[[Shelby Star]]}}</ref>\n\n===Legal proceedings===\n\nRoof waived his extradition rights and was flown to Sheriff Al Cannon Detention Center in [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]] on the evening of June 18.<ref name=\"BroughtBack\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxcarolina.com/story/29351540/shooting-suspect-dylann-roof-waives-extradition-headed-back-to-charleston|title=Charleston shooting suspect Dylann Roof due in court in Charleston Friday|work=WHNS Greenville|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RoofConfessed\"/> At the jail, his cell-block neighbor was Michael Slager, the former North Charleston police officer charged with murder after [[Shooting of Walter Scott|shooting Walter Scott]] following a traffic stop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/dylann-roof-and-michael-slager-are-cellblock-neighbors-in-charleston-county-jail-171133605.html|title=Dylann Roof and Michael Slager are cellblock neighbors in Charleston County jail|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Jason|last=Sickles}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Martinez |title=South Carolina cop shoots unarmed man: A timeline |date=April 8, 2015 |access-date=June 19, 2015 |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/04/08/us/south-carolina-cop-shoots-black-man-timeline/}}</ref> According to unconfirmed reports, Roof confessed to committing the attack and said he wanted to start a [[race war]].<ref name=\"RaceWar\"/> He reportedly told investigators he almost did not complete his plan because members of the church group had been so nice to him.<ref name=Borden19June>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/south-carolina-governor-urges-death-penalty-charges-in-church-slayings/2015/06/19/3c039722-1678-11e5-9ddc-e3353542100c_story.html|title=Officials: Suspect in church slayings unrepentant amid outcry over racial hatred|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|first1=Jeremy|last1=Borden|first2=Sari|last2=Horwitz|first3=Jerry|last3=Markon}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, Roof was charged with nine counts of murder and one count of possession of a firearm during the commission of a violent crime.<ref name=\"RoofConfessed\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/dylann-roof-confessed-killing-people-charleston-church-source/story?id=31884893|title=Dylann Roof Confessed to Killing 9 People at AME Church, Source Says|publisher=ABC News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Josh|last=Margolin|first2=Emily|last2=Shapiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/charleston-shooting-live-suspect-dylann-roof-in-custody-as-us-mourns-church-massacre--live-updates-10330694.html|title=Charleston shooting: Suspect Dylann Roof in custody as US mourns massacre \u2014 live updates|work=The Independent|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Lizzie|last=Dearden|first2=Payton|last2=Guion}}</ref> He first appeared in Charleston County court via [[Videoconferencing|videoconference]] at a bond hearing later that day. At the hearing, shooting survivors and relatives of five of the victims spoke to Roof directly, saying that they were \"praying for his soul\" and forgave him.<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/><ref name=\"ForgiveYou\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/familes-of-charleston-church-shooting-victims-to-dylann-roof--we--forgive-you-185833509.html|title=Families of Charleston shooting victims to Dylann Roof: We forgive you|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Dylan|last=Stableford}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/dylann-roof-almost-didnt-go-through-charleston-church-shooting-n378341|title=Dylann Roof 'Almost Didn't Go Through' With Charleston Church Shooting|publisher=NBC News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Daniel|last=Arkin}}</ref><ref name=\"VictimsAddress\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/06/19/i-forgive-you-relatives-of-charleston-church-victims-address-dylann-roof/|title='I forgive you.' Relatives of Charleston church shooting victims address Dylann Roof|work=The Washington Post|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Mark|last=Berman}}</ref>\n\nThe judge, Charleston County chief magistrate James \"Skip\" Gosnell, Jr., said at the [[Bail in the United States|bond hearing]] that, in addition to the dead victims and their families, \"there are victims on this young man's side of the family [...] Nobody would have ever thrown them into the whirlwind of events that they are being thrown into.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/s-judge-urges-support-dylann-roof-family-article-1.2264319 |title=S.C. judge urges support for accused murderer Dylann Roof's family in bizarre court speech|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|first=Barry|last=Paddock|first2=Rich|last2=Shapiro}}</ref> The judge was reported to have been reprimanded in 2005 by the [[South Carolina Supreme Court]] for using a racial slur while on the bench in 2003.<ref name=\"Reprimand\">{{cite web |url = http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/judge-who-presided-over-dylann-roof-bond-hearing-was-reprimanded-n379066|title=Judge Who Presided Over Dylann Roof Bond Hearing Was Reprimanded for Racial Slur|publisher=NBC News|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|first=Elizabeth|last=Chuck}}</ref> Gosnell set a $1 million bond for the weapons possession charge and no bail on the nine counts of murder.<ref>{{cite web|first=Scott|last=Neuman|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/06/19/415792559/-1-million-bond-for-church-shooting-suspect|title=$1 Million Bond For Charleston Church Shooting Suspect|publisher=NPR|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGovernor [[Nikki Haley]] called on prosecutors to seek [[Capital punishment in South Carolina|the death penalty]] against Roof.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2015/06/19/the-latest-church-shooting-haley-calls-for-death-penalty/Sd50001xUfcaWDV1XdZxHM/story.html|title=S.C. governor calls for death penalty in church shooting|work=Boston Globe|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> In June 2016 she warned against divisive rhetoric, saying that it could lead to tragedies such as the massacre at the church, and referred to the rhetoric of 2016 presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chasmar |first1=Jessica |title=Nikki Haley links Donald Trump to Charleston shooting: \u2018I know what that rhetoric can do\u2019 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/3/nikki-haley-links-donald-trump-to-charleston-shoot/ |access-date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 7, Roof was indicted on the nine murder charges and the weapons charge, as well three new charges of attempted murder, one for each person who survived the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/07/07/dylann-roof-indicted-in-charleston-shootings/29815457/|title=Dylann Roof indicted in deadly Charleston rampage|last=Bacon|first=John|date=July 8, 2015|work=USA Today|access-date=July 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/charges-charleston-church-shooting-attempted-murder-162002126.html|title=New charges in Charleston church shooting: Attempted murder|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 7, 2015|access-date=July 7, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref> He also faced federal [[hate crime]] charges,<ref name=nprindictment>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/07/22/425291216/charleston-shooting-suspect-roof-to-be-indicted-on-federal-hate-crime-charges|title=Charleston Shooting Suspect Roof To Be Indicted On Federal Hate Crime Charges|date=July 22, 2015|publisher=NPR|access-date=July 22, 2015}}</ref> including nine counts of using a firearm to commit murder and 24 [[Civil and political rights|civil rights]] violations (12 [[hate crime]] charges and 12 counts of violating a person's [[freedom of religion]]), with 18 of the charges carrying the federal death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20151213/PC16/151219888/1006/in-court-two-cases-against-dylann-roof-playing-out-at-different-pace|title=In court, two cases against Dylann Roof playing out at different pace|work=The Post and Courier|date=December 13, 2015|access-date=January 6, 2016|first=Andrew|last=Knapp}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, Roof pleaded not guilty to the federal charges, based on the advice of his lawyer [[David Bruck]]. Bruck earlier said Roof wanted to plead guilty, but he couldn't advise it without knowing the government's intentions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/suspect-charleston-church-shooting-due-federal-court-094257327.html|title=Not guilty plea in federal court for church shooting suspect|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 31, 2015|access-date=July 31, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard|first2=Bruce|last2=Smith}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Andrew|title=Meet Dylan Roof's Defender|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/07/29/meet-dylann-roof-s-defender|work=The Marshall Project|date=July 31, 2015|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 3, [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit]] solicitor (i.e., [[district attorney]]) Scarlett Wilson announced that she intended to seek the [[Capital punishment in the United States|death penalty]] against Roof in the state proceedings, based on more than two people being killed in the shooting and others' lives put at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/prosecutor-mulling-death-penalty-discuss-church-slayings-155225037.html|title=Prosecutor: Church shooting suspect to face death penalty|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 3, 2015|access-date=September 3, 2015|first=Meg |last= Kinnard| first2 =Jeffrey|last2=Collins}}</ref> On September 16, Roof said through his attorney that he was willing to plead guilty in exchange for a sentence of life in prison without parole.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/accused-gunman-charleston-church-shooting-proposes-guilty-plea-162700935.html|title=Accused gunman in Charleston church shooting proposes guilty plea|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 16, 2015|access-date=September 16, 2015|first=Harriet|last=McLeod}}</ref> \n\nOn October 1, the federal trial was pushed back to at least January 2016 to give prosecutors and Roof's attorneys more time to prepare.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/federal-trial-delayed-charleston-church-shooter-dylann-roof-n436996| title=Federal Trial Delayed for Charleston Church Shooter Dylann Roof| publisher=NBC News|date=October 1, 2015|access-date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> On December 1, the trial was postponed again to an unknown date.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/news-wrap-federal-trial-postponed-again-for-dylann-roof/|title=News Wrap: Federal trial postponed again for Dylann Roof|work=PBS NewsHour|date=December 1, 2015|access-date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> He and Joey Meek, accused of [[misprision of felony]] and lying to investigators about Roof's plans, were to reappear in federal court on February 11, 2016, while their lawyers held a bar meeting with prosecutors to discuss their cases.<ref name=FebruaryHearing>{{cite web| url= http://www.foxcarolina.com/story/30913936/court-hearing-scheduled-for-february-for-dylann-roof-friend|title=Court hearing scheduled for February for Dylann Roof, friend|work=FOX Carolina 21|date=January 7, 2016|access-date=January 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20160107/PC16/160109524/federal-hearing-for-church-shooter-dylann-roof-friend-set-for-feb-11|title=Federal hearing for church shooter Dylann Roof, friend set for Feb. 11|first=Andrew|last=Knapp|work=The Post and Courier|date=January 7, 2016| access-date=January 21, 2016}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=Did Dylann Roof and Joey Meek actually reappear in federal court on November 2, 2016?|date=November 2016}} On November 7, 2016, U.S. District Judge Richard Gergel postponed jury selection until November 9,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2016/11/07/jury-selection-charleston-9-trial-dylann-roof-postponed/93416182/|title=Jury selection in 'Charleston 9' trial of Dylann Roof postponed|first=Tonya|last=Maxwell|work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> later postponing the process again until November 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/11/07/us/dylann-roof-trial/|title=Dylann Roof case: Jury selection postponed over competency issue |work=CNN|date=November 8, 2016|access-date=November 9, 2016}}</ref> Gergel later postponed the jury selection to November 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/judge-orders-dylann-roof-competency-hearing-closed-to-media/2016/11/16/4051a064-ac20-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html|title=Judge orders Dylann Roof competency hearing closed to media|work=The Washington Post|date=November 16, 2016|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/judge-closes-dylann-roof-competency-hearing-public-205925881.html|title=Judge closes Dylann Roof competency hearing to the public|work=YAHOO! NEWS|date=November 16, 2016|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/11/16/us/ap-us-charleston-church-shooting.html |title=Judge Closes Dylann Roof Competency Hearing to the Public|work=The New York Times|date=November 16, 2016|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> On November 28, a federal judge granted a motion by Roof to represent himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/11/28/us/dylann-roof-to-represent-self-charleston-trial/|title=Dylann Roof represents self in Charleston murder trial|work=CNN|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-dylann-roof-charleston-church-shooting-trial-20161128-story.html|title=Judge grants Dylann Roof's 'unwise' request to represent himself in church shooting trial|work=Chicago Tribune|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38135604|title=Charleston massacre accused Dylann Roof to defend himself|work=BBC News|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/28/us/dylann-roof-charleston-massacre.html | title=Dylann Roof to Represent Himself at Trial in Charleston Church Shootings|work=New York Times|last=Sack |first=Kevin |date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref> On December 4, Roof made a handwritten request of Gergel, asking for his defense team for the guilt phase of his [[Capital punishment in the United States|federal death penalty]] trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/us/dylann-roof-charleston-trial.html?_r=0|title=Dylann Roof Wants His Lawyers Back to Begin Trial|work=New York Times| date= December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/dec/04/dylann-roof-charleston-church-shooting-trial-emanuel-ame |title = Dylann Roof: accused Charleston church gunman asks for defense team back|work=The Guardian|date=December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-dylann-roof-lawyers-20161204-story.html|title=Dylann Roof to judge: Let lawyers back on death penalty case|work=Los Angeles Times| date= December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-dylann-roof-church-shooting-trial-20161204-story.html|title=Dylann Roof to judge: Let lawyers back on S.C. church death penalty case |work=Chicago Tribune|date=December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref> On December 5, 2016, Gergel allowed Roof to hire back his lawyers for the guilt phase of his trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/dylann-roof-judge-let-defense-lawyers-back-charleston-church-massacre-n691761|title=Judge Allows Dylann Roof to Hire Back His Lawyers for Guilt Phase of Trial |work=NBC News|date=December 5, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-dylann-roof-attorneys-20161205-story.html|title=Accused Charleston church shooter Dylann Roof allowed to hire lawyers back, for now |work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 5, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref> On December 6, 2016, a federal judge denied a motion by Roof's defense team to delay Roof's trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/judge-denies-motion-delay-charleston-church-shooting-suspect-dylann-roof-n692776|title=Judge Denies Motion to Delay Charleston Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof's Trial Over Slager Outrage|work=NBC News|last=Johnson|first=Alex|date=December 6, 2016|access-date=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to seek the death penalty for Roof was a campaign topic in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic presidential primaries]], with [[Hillary Clinton]] supporting the Justice Department's decision and [[Bernie Sanders]] opposing it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/hillary-clinton-supports-death-penalty-for-dylann-roof_us_57507737e4b0c3752dccde7c|title=Hillary Clinton Supports Death Penalty For Dylann Roof|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 2, 2016|access-date=August 17, 2016| first = Sam | last=Stein}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Roof was declared competent to stand trial for the crimes.<ref name=\"Feig\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/judge-rules-charleston-shooter-dylann-roof-competent-to-stand-trial-news.25715.html? |title=Dylan Roof declared competent to stand trial |last=Feig |first=Zakk |date=November 25, 2016 |website=Hotnewhiphop |access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, following a second competency evaluation, Roof was again deemed competent.<ref>Alan Blinder, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/02/us/dylann-roof-charleston-church-killer-is-deemed-competent-for-sentencing.html Dylann Roof, Charleston Church Killer, Is Deemed Competent for Sentencing], ''New York Times'' (January 2, 2017).</ref>\n\nRoof's trial began on December 7, 2016; witnesses gave testimony describing the shooting in graphic detail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/us/dylann-roof-trial.html| title=Heart-Rending Testimony as Dylann Roof Trial Opens|work=New York Times|last2=Blinder|first2=Alan|last1=Sack|first1=Kevin|date=December 7, 2016|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>Alan Blinder and Kevin Sack, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/14/us/dylann-roof-trial-charleston.html Spared by Gunman in Charleston, Churchgoer Describes Night of Terror]\", ''New York Times'' (December 4, 2016).</ref> On December 15, 2016, Roof was found guilty of all 33 federal charges against him.<ref>Alan Blinder and Kevin Sack, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/15/us/dylann-roof-trial.html Dylann Roof Found Guilty in Charleston Church Massacre]\", ''New York Times'' (December 15, 2016).</ref> For the sentencing phase of the federal trial, Roof dismissed his attorneys and insisted on representing himself. In a statement to the court at his sentencing hearing on January 4, 2017, Roof offered no apology or explanation, saying \"There's nothing wrong with me psychologically.\"<ref name=\"NoApology\">Alan Blinder and Kevin Sack, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/04/us/dylann-roof-sentencing.html Dylann Roof, Addressing Court, Offers No Apology or Explanation for Massacre]\", ''New York Times'' (January 4, 2017).</ref> At the hearing, prosecutors introduced into evidence a two-page excerpt from journal written by Roof from jail six weeks after his arrest, in which Roof composed a white supremacist manifesto, writing: \"I would like to make it crystal clear, I do not regret what I did. I am not sorry. I have not shed a tear for the innocent people I killed.\"<ref name=\"NoApology\"/><ref>Matt Zapotosky, \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/charleston-church-shooter-i-would-like-to-make-it-crystal-clear-i-do-not-regret-what-i-did/2017/01/04/05b0061e-d1da-11e6-a783-cd3fa950f2fd_story.html Charleston church shooter: 'I would like to make it crystal clear, I do not regret what I did']\", ''Washington Post'' (January 4, 2016).</ref>\n\nRoof was sentenced to death on January 10, 2017, and to life in prison without parole on April 10, 2017.\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Charleston Shooting Memorial Service.jpg|thumb|right|A prayer vigil at Morris Brown African Methodist Episcopal Church]]\n\n===Context of racism===\nHeidi Beirich, the director of the Intelligence Project for the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]], a non-profit that seeks to [[List of organizations designated by the Southern Poverty Law Center as hate groups|identify American hate groups]] and confront their activities, said the gunman's reported motive has frequently appeared on white supremacist websites. They say that \"whites are being hugely victimized by blacks and no one is paying attention\". Referring to Roof's comments about rape, Beirich said, \"[Black men sexually assaulting white women] is probably the oldest racist trope we have in the U.S.\"<ref name = \"gulf\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/americas/usa/dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wore-symbols-of-white-supremacy-1.1537476 |title=Dylann Roof, Charleston suspect, wore symbols of white supremacy|work=Gulf News USA|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/on-facebook-dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wears-symbols-of-white-supremacy.html|title=Dylann Roof, Charleston Suspect, Wore Symbols of White Supremacy|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> According to Beirich, this trope related to a myth of Southern culture, as in fact African-American women had been much more frequently abused by white men. Lisa Lindquist-Dorr, associate professor at the [[University of Alabama]], said that the myth of black rapists had dominated imaginations of white, Southern men, who considered \"Sexual access to women is a trophy of power, white women embodied virtue and morality, they signified whiteness and white superiority, so sexual access to white women was possessing the ultimate privilege that white men held. It makes women trophies to be traded among men.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/18/white-female-sexuality-and-racist-violence-a-history_n_7613048.html |title=The History Of Using White Female Sexuality To Justify Racist Violence |work=The Huffington Post|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJamelle Bouie wrote in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', \"Make any list of anti-black terrorism in the United States, and you'll also have a list of attacks justified by the specter of black rape.\" He cited the [[Tulsa race riot]] of 1921, the [[Rosewood massacre]] of 1923, and the murder of 14-year-old [[Emmett Till]] in 1955 as examples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/history/2015/06/the_deadly_history_of_they_re_raping_our_women_racists_have_long_defended.html|title=The deadly history of \"They're raping our women\"|work=Salon|first=Jamelle|last=Bouie|access-date=June 25, 2015}}</ref> Beirich said it was unclear early in the investigation whether the suspect had any connection to [[hate group]]s. She noted that \"for several years South Carolina has been the place with the highest density of hate groups.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2015/0618/Charleston-mass-shooting-Reminder-of-past-racist-attacks-on-black-churches|title=Charleston mass shooting: Reminder of past racist attacks on black churches|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Memorials===\n[[File:Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, Charleston South Carolina.jpg|thumb|Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, Charleston South Carolina. 21 June 2015]]\n\nAt [[Morris Brown]] [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in Charleston, numerous people of different races and religions attended a ceremony commemorating the victims and they proclaimed that the attack would not divide the community.<ref name=\"BroughtBack\"/> Another such ceremony occurred at the [[TD Arena]] in the [[College of Charleston]].<ref name=\"RawEmotion\"/> On June 21, four days after the shooting, Emanuel AME Church reopened for its Sunday worship service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/shootings-emotional-burden-looms-over-sunday-sermons-064421413.html|title=Shootings' emotional burden looms over Sunday sermons|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 21, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015|first=Phillip|last=Lucas}}</ref> The Rev. Dr. Norvel Goff Sr., Presiding Elder of Emanuel AME Church, delivered the sermon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://northdallasgazette.com/2015/06/24/charleston-church-filled-with-signs-of-good-and-evil/|title=Charleston Church filled with signs of good and evil|work=North Dallas Gazette|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015|first=Clemon|last=Richardson}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2015, at Emanuel AME Church, funerals were held for victims Ethel Lance and Sharonda Coleman-Singleton and they were attended by several political figures and [[civil rights]] leaders.<ref name=\"CharlestonFunerals\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/26/us/charleston-south-carolina-shooting-funerals.html|title=In Charleston Funerals, Remembering Victims of Hate as Symbols of Love|work=The New York Times|date=June 25, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015 |first = Lizette | last= Alvarez| first2 = Nikita| last2 = Stewart | first3 =Richard| last3=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref> Clementa Pinckney's funeral was held in the basketball arena of the [[College of Charleston]] on June 26, 2015, with President [[Barack Obama]] delivering the eulogy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/06/26/417840372/president-obama-delivers-eulogy-at-funeral-for-rev-clementa-pinckney|title=President Obama Delivers Eulogy At Funeral For Rev. Clementa Pinckney|last=Goodwyn|first=Wade|author-link=Wade Goodwyn|date=June 26, 2015 |publisher=NPR|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Earlier, Pinckney's body lay in state in the [[South Carolina State House]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-83855240/|title=Hundreds line up in South Carolina's capital to honor slain pastor Clementa Pinckney |last =Jarvie|first=Jenny|date=June 24, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> This was followed by the funerals of Tywanza Sanders, Susie Jackson, and Cynthia Graham Hurd the next day.<ref>{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Chuck|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/funerals-held-three-more-charleston-church-victims-n383066|title='They Will Not Have Died in Vain': Funerals Held for Three Charleston Victims|publisher=NBC News|date=June 27, 2015|accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref> Hurd's family announced that they are establishing the Cynthia Graham Hurd Fund for Reading and Literacy organization in her memory; it is expected to give children easier access to books.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.wcnc.com/story/news/local/regional/2015/06/26/foundation-established-for-cause-close-to-charleston-shooting-victims-heart/29377815/|title=Foundation established for cause close to Charleston shooting victim's heart|publisher=WCNC|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627194743/http://www.wcnc.com/story/news/local/regional/2015/06/26/foundation-established-for-cause-close-to-charleston-shooting-victims-heart/29377815/|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> By July 2, the last of the victims, Daniel Simmons, was buried.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/funeral-victim-charleston-shooting-columbia-32177450 |title=Last Funeral for Victim of Charleston Shooting in Columbia|publisher=ABC News|date=July 2, 2015 |accessdate=July 2, 2015|first=Susanne M.|last=Schafer}}</ref>\n\n===Community response===\nThere has been some criticism aimed towards the community's forgiveness of Roof.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/02/419405863/charlestons-black-leaders-want-justice-as-much-as-forgiveness|title=Charleston's Black Leaders Want To See Justice As Much As Forgiveness|publisher=NPR|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Black Lives Matter]] movement has protested the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Black Lives Matter: Charleston Shooting Was an Act of Terror|url=http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Black-Lives-Matter-Charleston-Shooting-Was-an-Act-of-Terror-20150620-0010.html|work=[[TeleSUR]]|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=y|November 2019}}\n\nQuestions were raised about the security of black churches (as well as the security of churches in general) and their long-standing practice of welcoming anyone who is willing to pray (as most Christian churches are, regardless of the race of the majority of its parishioners). Roof, a stranger to churchgoers, was easily able to enter Emanuel AME Church with no questions asked. In the weeks after the shooting, [[African Methodist Episcopal Church|AME Church]] leaders distributed a document titled \"12 Considerations for Congregational Security\", which recommended creating security plans and teams for black churches, improving communications, developing relationships with local law enforcement, and securing and monitoring all entrances and exits to churches. Some churches considered hiring armed security guards and installing metal detectors, but conversations in support of these steps have currently not gained traction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/15/black-churches-straddle-security-openness/31527859/|title=After Charleston, black churches straddle fine line between security, openness|work=USA Today|date=August 16, 2015|accessdate=August 16, 2015|first=Tyler|last=Pager}}</ref>\n\nNine artists from across the United States created portraits of the victims as a tribute. The portraits were put on display at Principle Gallery for one month, and were given to the victims' families afterwards.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weismann|first1=Lisa|title=Artists donate talent for Emanuel AME victim portraits| url= http://www.live5news.com/story/32098215/artists-donate-talent-for-emanuel-ame-victim-portraits |accessdate=June 2, 2016|agency=Live5News|publisher=Frankly Media and Raycom Media|date=May 30, 2016}}</ref> Artists involved in the memorial included Ricky Mujica, Mario Andres Robinson, Lauren Tilden, Paul McCormack, Gregory Mortenson, Catherine Prescott, Terry Strickland, [[Judy Tak\u00e1cs]], and [[Stephanie Deshpande]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Charleston portrait project pays tribute to Emanuel 9|url=http://counton2.com/2016/05/28/principle-gallery-charleston-to-unveil-emanuel-9-portrait-project/|accessdate=June 2, 2016|agency=WCBD News 2|publisher=Media General Communications Holdings, LLC|date=May 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2016, survivors of the shooting sued the FBI for inadvertently enabling Roof to purchase the gun used in the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/charleston-church-shooting-victims-sue-fbi-over-gun-145126439.html|title=Charleston church shooting victims sue FBI over gun buy|publisher=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press|date=July 1, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref>\n\n===Other investigations===\nThe FBI is investigating possible [[church arson]] after several black churches burned down in one week's time following the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/officials-firefighters-battling-blaze-black-church-sc-024633155.html|title=Another black church in South Carolina burns; cause unknown|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2015|first=Jeffrey|last=Collins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/church-fires-common-usually-not-result-arson-083959655.html|title=Church fires not usually arson; weather found as cause in SC|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2015|first=Bruce|last=Smith|first2=Ray|last2=Henry}}</ref> On July 3, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported that the investigation concluded that the fires were unrelated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3945382/arson-black-churches-charleston-church-shooting-fire-lightning-south-carolina/|title=The Black-Church Fires in Southern States Are Not Connected, Authorities Say|work=Time|date=July 3, 2015|accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe FBI underwent a 30-day review to examine the lapses in the background-check system that allowed the suspected shooter to legally purchase the gun used in the shooting.<ref name=Nakashima10July/> According to [[James Comey]], Roof had been arrested in March on a felony drug charge, which would have required an inquiry into the charge during the background check examination. However, he was actually arrested on a misdemeanor drug charge, which was incorrectly written as a felony at first due to a data entry error made by a jail clerk. The mistake was noticed by the jail two days after the arrest, but the change was not made. The FBI agent conducting the background check examination then called the wrong agency while making the inquiry into the drug charge, due to having limited information on law enforcement agencies in [[Lexington County, South Carolina|Lexington County]]. This subsequently allowed Roof to make the purchase. However, despite the misdemeanor charge, he still would not have been able to purchase the gun under a law that barred anyone who is an \"unlawful user of or addicted to any controlled substance\" from owning firearms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2015/07/11/dylann-roof-apparently-had-not-been-arrested-for-a-felony-a-month-before-he-went-through-a-gun-purchase-background-check/|title=Dylann Roof apparently had not been arrested for a felony a month before he went through a gun purchase background check|work=The Washington Post|date=July 11, 2015|accessdate=July 12, 2015|first=Eugene|last=Volokh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/jail-clerical-error-acknowledged-church-shooting-gun-buy-190536334.html|title=Jail clerical error acknowledged in church shooting gun buy|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 13, 2015|accessdate=July 13, 2015|first=Jeffrey|last=Collins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jail-error-led-to-charleston-shooting-suspect-dylann-roofs-gun-buy/|title=Jail error led to Charleston shooting suspect's gun purchase|publisher=CBS News|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Several bills aiming to fix this loophole were proposed, and South Carolina legislation planned to discuss the loophole in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestate.com/news/local/article50646270.html|title=SC bills aim to close loophole that allowed Dylann Roof to buy a gun|work=The State|date=December 19, 2015|accessdate=January 6, 2016|first=Seanna|last=Adcox}}</ref> On August 30, 2019, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals]] ruled that the survivors and families of the deceased can sue the Federal government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ca4.uscourts.gov/opinions/181931.P.pdf|title=No. 18\u20131931|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, one of the friends who briefly hid Roof's gun away from him was arrested, reportedly for lying to federal authorities during their investigation and failing to report a crime. The next day, he pleaded not guilty to one count of making false statements to federal investigators and one count of concealing knowledge about a crime. He faces a maximum of nine years in prison and a $500,000 fine. According to legal experts, prosecutors possibly intend to use the prospect of federal charges against him as leverage for testifying against Roof.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/feds-investigate-friend-charleston-shooting-suspect-083706466.html|title=Official: Friend of Charleston church shooter arrested|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 17, 2015|accessdate=September 17, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/friend-alleged-church-shooter-appear-court-081354454.html|title=Indictment: Church shooter's friend knew about attack plans|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 18, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/09/18/joey-meek-friend-of-dylann-roof-charged-in-connection-with-church-shooting/|title=Joey Meek, friend of Dylann Roof, pleads not guilty to federal charges|work=The Washington Post|date=September 18, 2015|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> He was to reappear in federal court alongside Roof on February 11, 2016.<ref name=FebruaryHearing/>{{clarify|reason=Did the friend actually reappear in federal court alongside Roof on November 2, 2016?|date=November 2016}} Joey Meek pleaded guilty in federal court April 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thestate.com/news/local/crime/article74651222.html|title=Joey Meek knew what Dylann Roof was going to do, told others not to talk to FBI|last=Monk|first=John|work=The State (newspaper)|date=April 29, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> He was sentenced to 27 months in prison in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/03/21/us/joey-meek-sentencing-dylann-roof-charleston/|title=Dylann Roof friend sentenced to 27 months in prison|work=CNN|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n\n===Officials===\n[[List of mayors of Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston Mayor]] [[Joseph P. Riley, Jr.]] denounced the attack and said, \"Of all cities, in Charleston, to have a horrible hateful person go into the church and kill people there to pray and worship with each other is something that is beyond any comprehension and is not explained. We are going to put our arms around that church and that church family.\"\n\n[[Governor of South Carolina|South Carolina Governor]] [[Nikki Haley]] said, \"While we do not yet know all of the details, we do know that we'll never understand what motivates anyone to enter one of our places of worship and take the life of another. Please join us in lifting up the victims and their families with our love and prayers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/9-people-killed-in-shooting-at-black-church-in-charleston-s-c-1.3118057|title=9 people killed in shooting at black church in Charleston, S.C.|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] said in Charleston on June 18, \"Once again, innocent people were killed in part because someone who wanted to inflict harm had no trouble getting their hands on a gun...We as a country will have to reckon with the fact that this type of mass violence does not happen in other advanced countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/7613074|title=Obama On Charleston Shooting: 'This Type Of Mass Violence Does Not Happen In Other Advanced Countries'|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> At a Washington press conference later that day, he said, \"Michelle and I know several members of Emanuel AME Church. We knew their pastor, Reverend Clementa Pinckney, who, along with eight others, gathered in prayer and fellowship and was murdered last night. And to say our thoughts and prayers are with them and their families, and their community, doesn\u2019t say enough to convey the heartache and the sadness and the anger that we feel.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3926839/president-obama-charleston-transcript/|title=Read President Obama\u2019s Speech on the Charleston Church Shooting|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, the [[United States Department of Justice]] fast-tracked a [[Victims of Crime Act of 1984|Crime Victim Assistance Formula Grant]] of $29 million to the South Carolina government. Some of the money will be allocated to the survivors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-charleston-assistance-idUSKBN0OZ2CN20150619|title=U.S. to fast track $29 million to help Charleston shooting victims' families|agency=Reuters|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Families===\nAfter Roof's appearance at his bond hearing, his family issued a statement, expressing their shock and grief at his actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3929115/roof-family-statement-church-shootings/|title=Dylann Roof's Family Breaks Silence on Shooting|work=Time|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Dan|last=Kedmey}}</ref> Following the funerals of several of the victims in the shooting, they issued a second statement, expressing their condolences to the victims' families and announcing the temporary postponement of comments out of respect for them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/dylann-roofs-family-releases-new-statement-charleston-church-shooting-offers-1984222|title=Dylann Roof's Family Releases New Statement On Charleston Church Shooting, Offers Condolences To Victims' Families|work=The International Business Times|date=June 25, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|first=Thomas|last=Barrabi}}</ref> During the bond hearing, several family members of the victims told Roof that they forgave him.<ref name=\"ForgiveYou\"/>\n\n===Local community===\nThe local community surrounding Charleston held prayer vigils and fundraisers. A mass unity rally was also held on the [[Arthur Ravenel Bridge]] on the evening of June 21. Organizers of the rally claimed there were up to 20,000 supporters in the rally. Tens of thousands of individuals crossed from the [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|Mount Pleasant]] side of the bridge to the downtown Charleston side, carrying supportive signs and flags. Dozens of boats joined in the procession as well <ref>{{cite news|title=Organizers says 20,000 joined Bridge to Peace march on Ravenel Bridge|url=http://abcnews4.com/archive/watch-bridge-to-peace-event-live-on-abcnews-4-or-stream-it-live|accessdate=March 3, 2016|work=ABC News 4|date=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Religious community===\nThe [[World Methodist Council]], an association of worldwide churches in the [[Methodism|Methodist]] tradition, of which the AME Church is a part, said it \"urges prayer and support for the victims' families and those members of Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church who have been so gravely affected by this crime motivated by hate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldmethodistcouncil.org/response-to-deadly-shootings-at-church-in-charleston-sc/|title=Response to Deadly Shootings at Church in Charleston, SC|year=2015|work=World Methodist Council|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> The President and Vice-President of the British Methodist Conference, also a member of the World Methodist Council, sent a letter of solidarity to the [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]], saying, \"The hearts of the members of the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain]] go out to the families and friends of those killed; to the Church; and to the wider communities in Charleston.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/news-and-events/news-releases/message-of-solidarity-sent-to-african-methodist-episcopal-church|title=Message of solidarity sent to African Methodist Episcopal Church|work=The Methodist Church in Britain|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Methodist Council of Bishops|Council of Bishops]] of [[The United Methodist Church]], also a member of the World Methodist Council and in [[full communion]] with the African Methodist Episcopal Church, called on its members \"to support the victims of this and all acts of violence, to work to end racism and hatred, to seek peace with justice, and to live the [[Lord's Prayer|prayer that our Lord gave us]], that God's 'kingdom come, [and] will be done, on earth as it is in heaven'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/united-methodists-stand-with-ame-after-church-shooting2|title=United Methodists stand with AME after church shooting|last=Hahn|first=Heather|last2=Brodie|first2=Matt|date=June 18, 2015|publisher=The United Methodist Church|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Christian Methodist Episcopal Church]], also a member of the World Methodist Council and in full communion with the African Methodist Episcopal Church, shared its support with the presiding bishop, stating, \"let us join with the AMEs in prayer for the healing of the families touched by this tragedy&nbsp;\u2013 the families of the victims and the family of the perpetrator\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecmechurch.org/news.htm|title=News & Announcements for the Christian Methodist Episcopal Church|last=Reddick|first=Lawrence|date=June 18, 2015|work=Christian Methodist Episcopal Church|accessdate=June 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625010002/http://www.thecmechurch.org/news.htm|archivedate=June 25, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Rev. [[Olav Fykse Tveit]], general secretary of the [[World Council of Churches]], said, \"We offer our prayers for healing to the wounded and traumatized, and solidarity and accompaniment to our sisters and brothers in the African Methodist Episcopal Church\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Kenny|url=http://www.ecumenicalnews.com/article/worldwide-churches-condemn-us-race-hate-killing-in-charleston-30680|title=Worldwide churches condemn US 'race-hate' killing in Charleston|work=Ecumenical News|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Archbishop [[Joseph Edward Kurtz]], the president of [[U.S. Conference of Catholic Bishops]], made similar remarks.<ref>{{cite web|first=Carol|last=Kuruvilla|first2=Antonia|last2=Blumberg|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/18/religious-leaders-react-charleston-shooting_n_7613324.html|title=Faith Community Rallies Around Charleston Church After Shooting|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVarious national [[Judaism|Jewish]] organizations, including the [[American Jewish Committee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=7oJILSPwFfJSG&b=8451793&ct=14736637&notoc=1|title=AJC Deplores Fatal Attack on Black Charleston Church|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|work=AJC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624021204/http://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=7oJILSPwFfJSG&b=8451793&ct=14736637&notoc=1|archivedate=June 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Union for Reform Judaism]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rj.org/blog/2015/06/18/reform-movement-mourns-victims-of-charleston-ame-tragedy/|title=Reform Movement Mourns Victims of Charleston AME Tragedy|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|publisher=RJ.org}}</ref> [[Jewish Federations of North America]], [[Anti-Defamation League]], and [[Orthodox Union]] issued statements deploring the attack and expressing deep grief and horror. The [[Rabbinical Assembly]], in its own statement, quoted [[Leviticus]], saying, \"'Do not stand idly by the blood of your neighbor.' Hateful, violent acts such as this have no place in our society, in a country known for its diversity and blending of various cultures.\"<ref name=\"Wilner\">{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Wilner|url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Suspect-arrested-for-South-Carolina-church-shooting-406502|title=Jewish groups express 'heartbreak' over Charleston church shooting|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMany national [[Muslim]] organizations and individual [[imam]]s,<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeSarro|first1=Nina|title=Muslim leader prays for peace in wake of Charleston shooting|url=http://www.myfoxlubbock.com/news/local/story/islamic-center/J9sDgyXzqUqhkcAB5J1GEw.cspx|publisher=myfoxlubbock.com|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our Community Responds to the Charleston Tragedy|url=http://detroitinterfaithcouncil.com/2015/06/20/our-community-responds-to-the-charleston-tragedy/|website=detroitinterfaithcouncil.com/|publisher=DETROIT INTERFAITH COUNCIL|accessdate=June 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621070303/http://detroitinterfaithcouncil.com/2015/06/20/our-community-responds-to-the-charleston-tragedy/|archive-date=June 21, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> such as [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations]],<ref>{{cite web|title=CAIR Stands with African-American Community After Terror Attack on Charleston Church|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cair-stands-with-african-american-community-after-terror-attack-on-charleston-church-300101476.html|agency=PR Newswire|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> [[Islamic Society of North America]] (ISNA),<ref>{{cite web|title=ISNA Statement on Charleston Church Shooting|url=http://www.isna.net/isnas-statement-on-charleston-church-shooting.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113312/http://www.isna.net/isnas-statement-on-charleston-church-shooting.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 4, 2016|publisher=isna.net|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> and [[Islamic Circle of North America]] issued statements condemning the attack and offering sympathy for the victims.<ref name=\"onislam.net\">{{cite web|title=US Muslims Call for Charleston 'Day of Prayer'|url=http://www.onislam.net/english/news/americas/487835-us-muslims-call-for-charleston-day-of-prayer.html|publisher=onislam.net|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> In a joint statement, CAIR and Muslim leaders in [[Baltimore]] quoted the [[Quran]], saying, \"The Qur'an, the Muslim holy book, says: 'He who takes one life, it is as if he has slain all of mankind. And he who saves one life, it is as if he has saved all of mankind.'\"<ref name=\"onislam.net\"/>\n\nMuslim and Jewish religious organizations have raised several hundred thousand dollars to help rebuild black churches that were burned down in the weeks after the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/10/muslim-jewish-groups-fundraising-rebuild-black-churches|title=Muslim and Jewish groups at forefront of efforts to rebuild black churches|last=Blau|first=Max|date=July 10, 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nAt least eighteen candidates and prospective candidates for the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election]] expressed reactions through various media and addresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/u-presidential-candidates-reaction-south-carolina-church-shootings-123405886.html|title=U.S. presidential candidates react to South Carolina church shootings|agency=Reuters|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> According to [[National Public Radio|NPR]], Democratic and Republican candidates found different ways to address the incident, with Democrats seeing race and gun control as central issues, while Republicans pointing to mental illness and referring to it as tragic but random act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Predictably, Democrats, Republicans Don't Agree on Charleston Causes, Solutions|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/06/19/415747034/predictably-democrats-republicans-dont-agree-on-charleston-causes-solutions|publisher=NPR|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|first=Don|last=Gonyea|first2=Domenico|last2=Montanaro}}</ref> Most Republican candidates eventually acknowledged that race was a motivating factor for the shooting. According to the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', the shooting became a precarious subject for Republican presidential contenders, in particular in regard of the racial motivations behind it, as South Carolina holds primaries and the state's political importance have resulted in some candidates \"skirting around the clear racial motivations behind the attack\".<ref>{{cite web|title=How presidential candidates are responding to Charleston, S.C., shooting|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/USA-Update/2015/0622/How-presidential-candidates-are-responding-to-Charleston-S.C.-shooting|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015|first=Henry|last=Gass}}</ref>\n\nThe night following the attack, [[Jon Stewart]] delivered a monologue on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' discussing the tragic nature of the news, condemning the attacks as well as the media's response to it.   Stewart argued that in response to [[Islamic terrorism]], politicians declare they will do \"whatever we can\" to make America safe, even justifying [[Torture and the United States#Torture, interrogation and prisons in the War on Terror|torture]], but respond to this mass shooting with \"what are you gonna do, crazy is as crazy does\".<ref name=\"RollingStone-JonStewart-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/watch-jon-stewarts-heartbreaking-charleston-shooting-monologue-20150619|title=Watch Jon Stewart's Heartbreaking Charleston Shooting Monologue|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Daniel|last=Kreps}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], whose website Roof cited as a source for his radicalization, issued a statement on its website \"unequivocally condemn[ing]\" the attack, but that Roof has some \"legitimate grievances\" against black people. An additional statement from the group's president, Earl Holt III, disavowed responsibility for the crime and said the group's website \"accurately and honestly report[s] black-on-white violent crime\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/ccc-dylann-roof-legitimate-grievances|work=Talking Points Memo|last=Thompson|first=Catherine|title=Group That May Have Influenced Charleston Killer: He Had Some 'Legitimate Grievances'|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an online forum, Charles Cotton, a lawyer in [[Houston]] and a national board member of the [[National Rifle Association]], placed blame for the shooting on Pinckney for not allowing the churchgoers to hold [[concealed carry]] weapons inside the church. In 2011, Pinckney had voted against legislation that would allow concealed handguns to be carried into public places. Cotton also criticized the effectiveness of gun-free zones, stating, \"If we look at mass shootings that occur, most happen in gun-free zones.\" Cotton's comment has since been deleted from the online forum.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lisa Maria|last=Garza|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nra-executive-suggests-slain-charleston-pastor-blame-gun-043458974.html|title=NRA executive suggests slain Charleston pastor to blame for gun deaths|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"TimesPicayune-AP-NRABlamesPinckney-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Associated Press|title=Charleston shooting the fault of slain pastor Clementa Pinckney, NRA board member writes|url=http://www.nola.com/crime/index.ssf/2015/06/charleston_shooting_the_fault.html|accessdate=June 21, 2015|work=[[The Times-Picayune]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the shooting, [[Rhodesians Worldwide]], an online magazine catering to the Rhodesian expatriate community, issued a brief statement condemning Roof's actions in response to his use of the [[Flag of Rhodesia|Rhodesian flag]]. It said 80% of the [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] were black and that the [[Rhodesian Bush War]] was a struggle against [[communism]] rather than a racial conflict.<ref name=\"RhodesiansWorldwide-Condemning-2015\">{{cite web|title=Rhodesians Worldwide homepage|url=http://rhodesians-worldwide.com/|work=Rhodesians Worldwide|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Richardson]], the owner of the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[Carolina Panthers]], donated $100,000 to the Mother Emanuel Hope Fund set up by Mayor Riley, specifically calling for $10,000 to each of the families of the nine victims to cover their funeral expenses, and the remaining $10,000 to be delivered to the Emanuel AME Church itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000498123/article/panthers-owner-donates-100000-to-charleston-victims|title=Panthers owner donates $100,000 to Charleston victims|publisher=National Football League|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcnc.com/story/sports/nfl/panthers/2015/06/20/panthers-make-generous-donation-for-church-shooting-victims/29031349/|title=Panthers make generous donation for church shooting victims|publisher=WCNC.com|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621211649/http://www.wcnc.com/story/sports/nfl/panthers/2015/06/20/panthers-make-generous-donation-for-church-shooting-victims/29031349/|archive-date=June 21, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nArtist [[Carrie Mae Weems]] has created a theater piece in response to the murders, called ''Grace Notes''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/this-artist-is-taking-on-americas-history-of-violence|title=This artist is taking on America\u2019s history of violence|last=Brown|first=Jeffrey|date=January 8, 2018|website=PBS NewsHour|access-date=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCivil rights advocates said the Charleston attack not only fit the dictionary definition of terrorism but reflected a history of attempts by the [[Ku Klux Klan]] and other white supremacist groups to terrorize African-Americans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-shooting-terrorism-or-hate-crime.html |title=Many Ask, Why Not Call Church Shooting Terrorism |work=New York Times|date=18 June 2015|accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged retaliatory attack===\n{{main|Burnette Chapel shooting}}\n\nAccording to the State of Tennessee, a 2017 church shooting that killed a woman and wounded seven others was retaliation for the Charleston shooting. The suspect, who is black, reportedly said that he wanted to \"kill 10 white people\" and referenced Roof and the [[Pan-African flag]] in a note he left in his car.<ref>https://jg-tc.com/news/national/state-suspect-aimed-to-kill-at-least-white-churchgoers/article_7313a262-6692-5f9b-be25-448bdae251b8.html</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-nashville-church-shooter-motive-20190521-ub3jfebrujifbdpvfcp46bbhh5m.html|title=Nashville-area shooter wanted to kill 10 white congregants to avenge Charleston church victims|last=Ganz|first=Jami|work=New York Daily News|access-date=June 16, 2019|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/antioch-church-shooting-more-testimony-expected-on-day-2-of-trial|title=Gunman's note: \"Dylann Roof is less than nothing\", says shooting was \"vengeance\" for Charleston|last=Bowles|first=Laken|work=News Channel 5 (Nashville)|access-date=June 14, 2019|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\n\n===Confederate flag===\n{{main|Modern display of the Confederate flag#Reactions to 2015 Charleston church shooting}}\n[[File:Battle flag of the Confederate States of America.svg|thumb|upright=0.7|The battle flag of the [[Confederate States of America]].]]\n\nOn June 18, 2015, the day after the shooting, many flags, including those at the [[South Carolina State House]], were flown at [[half-staff]]. The [[Confederate battle flag]] flying over the South Carolina Confederate Monument<ref>{{cite web|title=South Carolina Confederate Monument|url=http://www.hmdb.org/Marker.asp?Marker=17048|publisher=The Historical Marker Database|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> near the state house was not lowered, as South Carolina law prohibited alteration of the flag without the consent of two-thirds of the state legislature.<ref name=\"wp0619\">{{cite news|last1=Moyer|first1=Justin Wm.|title=Why South Carolina's Confederate flag isn't at half-staff after church shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/19/why-south-carolinas-confederate-flag-isnt-at-half-mast-after-church-shooting/|accessdate=June 19, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> Also, the flagpole lacked a pulley system, meaning the flag could not be flown at half-staff, only removed.<ref name=\"wp0619\"/>\n\n====Flag removal from statehouse grounds====\n[[File:South Carolina State House.JPG|thumb|right|[[South Carolina State House]] with the Confederate Monument in front, flag at rest|alt=View of the South Carolina State House with the Confederate Monument in front]]\n\nCalls to remove the Confederate flag from statehouse grounds, as well as debates over the context of its symbolic nature, were renewed after the attack<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/06/19/dylann-roof-charleston-police-charged-with-murder-black-church/28975573/|title=Dylann Roof charged with 9 counts of murder in Charleston attack|work=USA Today|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Yamiche|last=Alcindor|first2=Doug|last2=Stanglin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/20/us/charleston-shooting-reignites-debate-about-confederate-flag.html|title=Charleston Shooting Reignites Debate About Confederate Flag|work=The New York Times|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|first=Katie|last=Rogers}}</ref> by several prominent figures, including President [[Barack Obama]], [[Mitt Romney]], and [[Jeb Bush]].<ref name=\"NYT.Flag\">{{cite web|title=Mitt Romney, Jeb Bush and Ted Cruz Weigh In on Confederate Flag at South Carolina Capitol|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/06/20/mitt-romney-calls-for-removal-of-confederate-flag-at-south-carolina-capitol/|work=The New York Times|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015|first=Michael|last=Barbaro}}</ref> On June 20, 2015 several thousand people gathered in front of the South Carolina State House in protest. An online petition at [[MoveOn.org]] encouraging the flag's removal had received over 370,000 signatures by that time.<ref name=FlagProtest>{{cite news|last1=Macpherson|first1=Robert|title=Protesters target Confederate flag after Charleston killings|url=https://news.yahoo.com/protesters-target-confederate-flag-charleston-killings-015001853.html|accessdate=June 21, 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt a statehouse press conference on June 22, Governor [[Nikki Haley]], flanked by elected officials of both parties, including U.S. Republican senators [[Lindsey Graham]] and [[Tim Scott]], and former Republican Governor [[Mark Sanford]], called for the flag to be removed by the state legislature, saying that while the flag was \"an integral part of our past, it does not represent the future\" of South Carolina.<ref name=Niquette22June>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-06-22/south-carolina-officials-call-for-confederate-flag-to-come-down|title=South Carolina Governor Backs Removal of Confederate Flag|first=Mark|last=Niquette|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=Bloomberg News}}</ref> Eulogizing the Rev. Clementa Pinckney on June 26, 2015, before 5,000 congregants at the [[College of Charleston]], President [[Barack Obama]] acknowledged that the shooting had catalyzed a broad movement, backed by Republicans and Democrats, to remove the flag from official public display. \"Blinded by hatred, [the gunman] failed to comprehend what Reverend Pinckney so well understood: the power of God's grace,\" Obama said. \"By taking down that flag we express God's grace. But I don't think God wants us to stop there.\"<ref name=Sack26June>{{cite news|first1=Kevin|last1=Sack|first2=Lizette|last2=Alvarez|work=The New York Times|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/27/us/thousands-gather-for-funeral-of-clementa-pinckney-in-charleston.html|title=President Obama Eulogizes Charleston Pastor as One Who Understood Grace}}</ref><ref name=Hathaway26June>{{cite news|url=http://gawker.com/obama-leads-mourners-in-amazing-grace-at-pinckney-fun-1714240326 |title=In Breathtaking Moment, Obama Leads Charleston Mourners in 'Amazing Grace' |first=Jay |last=Hathaway |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=June 26, 2015 |work=Gawker |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627094419/http://gawker.com/obama-leads-mourners-in-amazing-grace-at-pinckney-fun-1714240326 |archivedate=June 27, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2015, the [[South Carolina Senate]] voted to remove the Confederate flag from display outside the South Carolina State House. Following 13 hours of debate, the vote in the House to remove it was passed by a two-thirds majority (94\u201320) on July 9. Governor Nikki Haley signed the bill on July 9.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/07/09/south-carolina-rep-jenny-horne-on-her-historic-and-surprisingly-personal-speech-it-needed-to-be-done/?hpid=z2 ''Washington Post'', Jenny Horne: How a descendant of the president of the Confederacy helped vanquish his flag] accessdate=2015-07-09</ref>  On July 10, the Confederate flag was taken down for the last time; it will be stored until it can later be shown in a museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/confederate-flag-fans-critics-gather-s-statehouse-article-1.2287700|title=Confederate flag fans, critics gather at S.C. statehouse|work=The New York Daily News|date=July 10, 2015|accessdate=July 10, 2015|first=Meg|last=Wagner|first2=Corky|last2=Siemaszko}}</ref>\n\n====Retailers end sales of the flag====\n\nOn June 23, 2015, retailers [[Wal-Mart]], [[Amazon.com]], [[Sears Holding Corporation]] (which owns [[Sears]] and [[Kmart]]), and [[eBay]] all announced plans to stop selling merchandise with the Confederate flag.<ref>{{cite web|first=MJ|last=Lee|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/22/politics/confederate-flag-walmart-south-carolina/|title=Walmart, Amazon.com, Sears, eBay to stop selling Confederate flag merchandise|publisher=CNN|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Similarly, [[Warner Bros.]] announced they were halting production of \"[[General Lee (car)|General Lee]]\" car toys, which prominently feature a Confederate flag on the roof.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rich|first1=McCormik|title=Warner Bros. scraps Dukes of Hazzard car toys over Confederate flag controversy|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/6/23/8836571/dukes-of-hazzard-car-toys-confederate-flag|work=The Verge|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> Many major flag manufacturers also decided to stop profiting from the flag.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-shooting-south-carolina-flag-fact-idUSKBN0P421P20150624|title=At rural South Carolina flag factory, sadness and pride|date=June 24, 2015|first=Edward|last=McAllister|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3932924/flag-manufacturer-confederate/|title=Prominent Flag Manufacturer Will Stop Producing Confederate Flags|date=June 23, 2015|first=Katy|last=Osborn|work=Time|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chapa|first1=Sergio|title=Dixie Flag will no longer sell confederate flags|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/news/2015/06/23/dixie-flag-will-no-longer-sell-the-confederate.html|work=San Antonio Business Journal|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Removal of monuments and memorials related to the Confederacy===\n{{see also|Removal of Confederate monuments and memorials}}\n\nThe city of [[New Orleans]] has announced plans to remove four memorials related to the Confederacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/vigil-vs-removal-of-statue-of-confederate-president-jefferson-davis-in-new-orleans/|title=New Orleans tears down Confederate monument|publisher=}}</ref> Two of them, the [[Battle of Liberty Place Monument]] and the [[Jefferson Davis Monument]], have been removed as of May 11, 2017.\n\n===Other===\nIn addition to the controversy regarding the Confederate flag's modern display, there have been considerations by institutions across the U.S. to remove the names of historic Confederate figures from schools, colleges, and streets. Campaigns to change the names were started in several cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2015/07/institutions_reconsider_confed.html|title=Institutions reconsider Confederate memorials after Charleston, S.C., church shooting|work=Mass Live|date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=July 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a national survey conducted in 2015, 57% of Americans opined that the Confederate flag represented Southern pride rather than racism. A previous poll in 2000 had a nearly identical result of 59%. However, poll results from only citizens living in the South yielded different results: 75% of whites described the flag as a symbol of pride, while 75% of blacks said the flag represented racism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/02/politics/confederate-flag-poll-racism-southern-pride/|title=Poll: Majority sees Confederate flag as Southern pride symbol, not racist|publisher=CNN|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Earl Holt political donations===\n\nEarl Holt, the leader of the [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], whose website Roof credited in his manifesto for shaping his views, gave more than $74,000<ref name=Swaine22June>{{cite news|title=Four Republican hopefuls return money after 'Dylann Roof manifesto's revelation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/22/scott-walker-republican-dylann-roof-manifesto|first1=Jon|last1=Swaine|first2=Jessica|last2=Glenza|work=The Guardian|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates and committees in recent years, including campaign donations to 2016 presidential candidates [[Ted Cruz]], [[Rick Santorum]], and [[Rand Paul]], who have all condemned Roof's racially based motives.<ref name=Alexander22June>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/republicans/11690736/Republican-presidential-candidates-received-donations-from-man-who-inspired-Charleston-shooter.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|first=Harriet|last=Alexander|title=Republican candidates accepted donations from man whose organisation inspired Dylann Roof}}</ref><ref name=Lichtblau22June>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/22/us/campaign-donations-linked-to-white-supremacist.html|title=White Supremacist Donated to 2016 G.O.P. Campaigns|date=June 22, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 22, 2015|first=Eric|last=Lichtblau}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-holt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/21/dylann-roof-manifesto-charlston-shootings-republicans|title=Leader of group cited in 'Dylann Roof manifesto' donated to top Republicans|work=The Guardian|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> Following the shooting, and after a journalist contacted the campaigns with details about the donor's background, a spokesman for the [[Ted Cruz 2016 presidential campaign|Ted Cruz campaign]] said he would return an $8,500 donation to Holt;<ref name=\"guardian-holt\"/> the campaign later said it would be donating $11,000 to the Mother Emanuel Hope Fund, to assist the victims' families.<ref name=Swaine22June/> The Rand Paul campaign said Holt's $2,250 donation would be given to the Fund,<ref name=Lichtblau22June/> and Rick Santorum said his $1,500 donation from Holt would be donated to the same charity.<ref name=Thompson22June>{{ cite news|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/rick-santorum-earl-holt-ccc|title=Santorum To Give Away Money Donated To Him By White Supremacist|first=Catherine|last=Thompson|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=Talking Points Memo}}</ref> Twelve other Republican office-holders also announced they would be returning or donating Holt's contributions.<ref name=Swaine22June/>\n\n===\"Terrorism\" terminology===\n{{See also|Definitions of terrorism}}\n\nWhile some media professionals, politicians and law enforcement officials referred to the attack as [[Homegrown terrorism|domestic terrorism]], others did not. This renewed a debate about the proper terminology to use when describing the shooting and other attacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/charleston-shooting-renews-debate-over-labelling-incidents-as-terrorism/article25045158/|title=Questions surround reluctance to label Charleston shooting as 'terrorism'|first=Affan|last=Chowdhry|work=The Globe and Mail|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, professor and [[terrorism]] expert Brian Phillips offered his definition of terrorism and said, the shooting was \"clearly a terrorist act\". He based this conclusion on a racist political motivation that \"seems likely\" and his \"intimidation of a wider audience\" criterion was met when \"...{{nbsp}}the shooter reportedly left one person alive to spread the message\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/monkey-cage/wp/2015/06/18/was-what-happened-in-charleston-terrorism/|title=Was what happened in Charleston terrorism?|first=Brian J.|last=Phillips|work=The Washington Post|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> An article by CNN National Security Analyst [[Peter Bergen]] and David Sterman on June 19 says, \"By any reasonable standard, this is terrorism, which is generally defined as an act of violence against civilians by individuals or organizations for political purposes. ... [D]eadly acts of terrorism by virulent racists and anti-government extremists have been more common in the United States than deadly acts of jihadist terrorism since [[September 11 attacks|9/11]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/opinions/bergen-charleston-attack-terrorism/index.html|title=Call it terrorism in Charleston|first=Peter|last=Bergen|first2=David|last2=Sterman|publisher=CNN|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome publications and their analyses of the event said these naming discrepancies reflect either forms of denial or outright [[racism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/06/18/was-the-charleston-massacre-an-act-of-terrorism/|title=Was the Charleston Massacre an Act of Terrorism?|first=Elias|last=Groll|work=Foreign Policy|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/06/29/terrorism-in-charleston|title=Terrorism in Charleston|first=Jelani|last=Cobb|work=The New Yorker|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/hate-crime-or-terrorism-debate-grows-about-terminology|title=Civil-rights experts have one word for church attack: It was terrorism|first=Rick|last=Gladstone|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> The journalist [[Glenn Greenwald]] wrote that {{quote|Almost immediately, news reports indicated there was 'no sign of terrorism'{{snd}}by which they meant: {{em|it does not appear that the shooter is Muslim}} ... other than the perpetrator\u2019s non-Muslim identity, the Charleston attack from the start had the indicia of what is commonly understood to be 'terrorism'. (emphasis in original)<ref>{{cite web |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |title=Refusal to Call Charleston Shootings 'Terrorism' Again Shows It\u2019s a Meaningless Propaganda Term |url=https://theintercept.com/2015/06/19/refusal-call-charleston-shootings-terrorism-shows-meaningless-propaganda-term/ |website=The Intercept |date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nSpeaking on June 19 at a press conference in [[Baltimore]], [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI Director]] [[James Comey]] said, while his agency was investigating the shooting as a \"hate crime\", he did not consider it an \"act of terrorism\", citing the lack of political motivation for the suspect's actions.<ref name=Comey>{{cite web|url=http://www.13wham.com/news/features/nation-news/stories/fbi-director-charleston-shooting-not-terrorism-3408.shtml|title=FBI Director: Charleston shooting not terrorism|publisher=WHAM-TV|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150628135934/http://13wham.com/news/features/nation-news/stories/fbi-director-charleston-shooting-not-terrorism-3408.shtml|archivedate=June 28, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/06/22/white-house-won-t-back-fbi-chief-on-charleston-terror.html|title=White House Won't Back FBI Chief on Charleston 'Terror'|work=The Daily Beast|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015|first=Shane|last=Harris}}</ref> He said, \"Terrorism is act of violence done or threatened in order to try to influence a public body or citizenry, so it's more of a political act, and again, based on what I know, I don't see this as a political act. Doesn't make it any less horrific, but terrorism has a definition under federal law.\"<ref name=Comey/>\n\nHeidi Beirich, who leads the Intelligence Project of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), pointed to the discovery of a website attributed to Roof, which featured a manifesto and sixty photos as an example of why federal agents \"don't have themselves together on this issue\". The website began circulating on the Internet on June 20. Beirich said, \"The way they found the website was that someone ran a domain tool reverse search on this guy's name... It wasn't rocket science, but where were the feds?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/25/dylann-roof-domestic-extremists-terrorism-law-enforcement|title=Beyond Dylann Roof: inside the hunt for domestic extremists in the digital age|work=The Guardian|date=June 25, 2015|accessdate=July 4, 2015|first=Andrew|last=Gumbel}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, FBI spokesman Paul Bresson left open the possibility of terrorism charges, saying, \"Any eventual federal charges will be determined by the facts at the conclusion of the investigation, and are not influenced by how the investigation is initially opened.\" Ultimately, it is up to [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] prosecutors to decide what federal charges to bring. A spokesperson for Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] said the Department of Justice was investigating the shooting as both \"a hate crime and as an act of domestic terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/fbi-terrorism-charges-not-ruled-out-charleston-shooting|publisher=MSNBC|title=FBI: Terrorism charges not ruled out in Charleston shooting|last=Melber|first=Ari|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Imitators and subculture===\nThe infamy of Roof and the shooting has inspired imitators to plot similar attacks. Benjamin Thomas Samuel McDowell was arrested for unlawful firearm possession; he had been planning to shoot up the Temple Emanu-El synagogue in [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]], while Elizabeth Lecron and Vincent Armstrong were arrested for plotting to use explosives for \"upscale mass murder\"{{Clarification needed|reason=|date=July 2019}} in [[Toledo, Ohio]], having previously corresponded with Roof himself.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/06/us/south-carolina-arrest-benjamin-mcdowell-dylann-roof.html|title=Man in South Carolina Wanted to Copy Dylann Roof, Officials Say|last=Bidgood|first=Jess|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 22, 2019|date=February 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ndoh/pr/toledo-couple-indicted-conspiracy-use-explosives-and-firearms-kill-and-injure-others|title=Toledo couple indicted for conspiracy to use explosives and firearms to kill and injure others|work=United States Department of Justice|access-date=February 21, 2019|date=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heavy.com/news/2018/12/elizabeth-lecron|title=Elizabeth LeCron: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Santiago|first=Elyn|work=Heavy.com|access-date=June 16, 2019|date=December 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/monroe-area-man-with-arsenal-fantasized-about-killing-jews|title=Man with arsenal allegedly fantasized about killing Jews|last=Hutton|first=Caleb|work=HeraldNet.com|access-date=June 16, 2019|date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA violent [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] subculture has also emerged, known as the \"Bowl Gang\" or \"Bowl Patrol\", glorifying Roof and other far-right mass murderers.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Zack|last1=Beauchamp|accessdate=2019-08-17|title=An online subculture celebrating the Charleston church shooter appears to be inspiring copycat plots|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/2/7/18215634/dylann-roof-charleston-church-shooter-bowl-gang|date=7 February 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Paul|last1=Blumenthal|first2=Jessica|last2=Schulberg|first3=Luke|last3=O'Brien|accessdate=2019-08-17|title=Mass Shooters Have Been Exploiting The Internet For Years. New Zealand Took It To A New Level.|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/new-zealand-shooting-columbine-breivik-rodgers-roof-bowers_n_5c8c4b79e4b0d7f6b0f38e58|date=16 March 2019|website=HuffPost}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-08-17|title=Hardcore White Supremacists Elevate Dylann Roof to Cult Hero Status|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/hardcore-white-supremacists-elevate-dylann-roof-to-cult-hero-status|website=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Post\u2013civil rights era in African-American history|Post-civil rights era African-American history]]\n* [[Jeffersontown Kroger shooting]]\n* [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150620134455/http://lastrhodesian.com/ The Last Rhodesian] via [[Archive.org]] \u2013 Dylann Roof website\n* {{cite web|title=South Carolina State Senate Debate on the Confederate Flag|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?326742-1/south-carolina-state-senate-debate-confederate-flag|publisher=[[C-SPAN]]|date=June 23, 2015}}\n* [http://www.aaihs.org/resources/charlestonsyllabus/ #Charlestonsyllabus, a list of academic sources related to the shooting]\n* [http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1907500-un-ano-de-la-masacre-de-charleston-el-debate-que-no-fue Marcelo Pisarro, \"Un a\u00f1o de la masacre de Charleston: el debate que no fue\", La Naci\u00f3n, June 12, 2016.] (Spanish)\n{{Charleston, South Carolina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charleston, South Carolina shooting}}\n[[Category:2015 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:2015 in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:2015 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American history in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2015]]\n[[Category:Charleston church shooting| ]]\n[[Category:Crimes in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Massacres of Christians]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:History of Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:June 2015 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2015]]\n[[Category:Massacres in religious buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder trials]]\n[[Category:Murdered African-American people]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Civil Rights Era African-American history]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against African Americans]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in the United States in 2015]]\n[[Category:White supremacy in the United States]]\n[[Category:White nationalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Attacks on African-American churches]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|2015 Charleston shooting|the shooting by a North Charleston police officer|Shooting of Walter Scott}}\n{{short description|Mass shooting in Charleston, South Carolina, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Charleston church shooting\n| partof      = [[Far-right terrorism in the United States]]\n| image       = Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal (AME) Church Corrected.jpg <!-- Better image that relates more to the shooting needed, examples: rescue response, aftermath picture -->\n| image_upright = \n| alt         = A white-painted church at sunset.\n| caption     = The [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in 2008\n| map = {{Location map many | South Carolina#United States\n| width = 250\n| label = Charleston\n| position = center\n| background = #FFFFDD\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|47|15|N|79|55|59|W}}\n}}\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     = Charleston, South Carolina\n| map_caption = \n| location    = [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]]<br />[[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina]], [[United States]]\n| target      = [[African American]] churchgoers\n| coordinates = {{Coord|32|47|15|N|79|55|59|W|display=inline,title}}  \n| date        = {{start date|2015|06|17}}\n| time        = {{circa}} 9:05 p.m. &ndash; c. 9:11 p.m.<ref name=\"ABC.Documents\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/police-documents-reveal-deadly-minutes-inside-south-carolina/story?id=34836336|title=New Police Documents Reveal Deadly Minutes Inside South Carolina Church|publisher=ABC News|date=October 29, 2015|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| timezone    = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| type        = [[Mass shooting]]<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-Shooting-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Bever|first1=Lindsey|last2=Costa|first2=Robert|title=9 dead in shooting at historic Charleston African American church. Police chief calls it \u2018hate crime.\u2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/17/white-gunman-sought-in-shooting-at-historic-charleston-african-ame-church/|accessdate=June 18, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref><br />[[Hate crime]]<br />\n| fatalities  = 9<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-Shooting-2015\" /><ref name=\"MyFox8-RoofConfesses-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://myfox8.com/2015/06/19/charleston-shooting-suspect-dylan-roof-confesses-to-killing-9-people/|title=Dylann Roof confesses to killing 9 people in Charleston church, wanting to start 'race war'|publisher=[[WGHP]]|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 1<ref name=\"DailyMirror-CharlestonChurch-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/charleston-church-shooting-first-picture-5904803|title=Charleston church shooting: First picture of 'gunman' on the run after nine people shot dead|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| perp     = [[Dylann Roof]]<ref name=\"Telegraph-RoofConfesses-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/11686370/Dylann-Roof-confesses-to-Charleston-shooting-as-governer-calls-for-death-penalty.html|title=Dylann Roof confesses to Charleston shooting as governor calls for death penalty|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Andrew|last=Marszal}}</ref>\n| weapons     = [[Glock 41]] [[.45 ACP|.45-caliber]] [[handgun]]\n| numparts    = <!-- or | numpart     = -->\n| dfens       = <!-- or | dfen        = -->\n| motive      = [[Right-wing terrorism|Far-right extremism]], [[white supremacy]]/[[white nationalism|nationalism]]\n| website     = <!-- URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n{{Terrorism}}\n\nThe '''Charleston church shooting''' (also known as the '''Charleston church massacre''')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html|title=Church Massacre Suspect Held as Charleston Grieves|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/dylann-roof-indicted-murder-church-massacre-n388066|title=Dylann Roof Indicted for Murder in Charleston Church Massacre|publisher=NBC News|date=July 7, 2015|access-date=November 12, 2015|first=Tracy|last=Connor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/charleston-police-church-shooting|title=Nine dead in Charleston church massacre|publisher=MSNBC|date=June 17, 2015|access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> was a [[mass shooting]] on June 17, 2015, in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], in which nine [[African Americans]] were killed during a Bible study at the [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]]. Among those killed  was the senior pastor, [[South Carolina Senate|state senator]] [[Clementa C. Pinckney]]; three victims survived. This church is one of the oldest [[black church]]es in the United States, and it has long been a center for organizing related to [[civil rights]].\n\nThe morning after the attack, police arrested [[Dylann Roof]] in [[Shelby, North Carolina]]; the 21-year-old [[White supremacy|white supremacist]] had attended the Bible study before shooting. He was found to have targeted members of this church because of its history and stature. Roof was found [[competent to stand trial]] in [[United States federal court|federal court]]. \n\nIn December 2016 he was convicted of 33 [[Federal crime|federal]] [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crime]] and [[murder]] charges. On January 10, 2017, he was [[Capital punishment by the United States federal government|sentenced to death]] for these crimes.<ref name=\"jury-dylann-roof-death-penalty\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/11/us/dylann-roof-sentencing/|publisher=CNN|title=Victim's dad warns Dylann Roof: 'Your creator ... he's coming for you'|access-date=April 14, 2017|date=January 11, 2017}}</ref> Roof was separately charged with nine counts of murder in the [[South Carolina government and politics#Judicial branch|South Carolina]] [[State court (United States)|state court]]s. In April 2017, Roof pleaded guilty to all nine state charges in order to avoid a second death sentence, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for each. He will receive automatic appeals of his death sentence, but may eventually be executed by the federal justice system.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Harriet|last1=McLeod|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-south-carolina-shooting-roof-idUSKBN17C15W|title=Charleston church shooter pleads guilty to state murder counts|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=April 10, 2017|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Andrew|last1=Knapp|first2=Abigail|last2=Darlington|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/news/dylann-roof-s-life-sentences-on-state-murder-charges-surest/article_4a8b54ec-1df1-11e7-af4f-3f880fee388b.html|title=Dylann Roof's 9 life sentences on state murder charges 'surest' route to federal execution, prosecutor says|work=Post & Courier|date=April 10, 2017|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRoof espoused [[racial hatred]] in both a website [[manifesto]] published before the shooting, and a journal written from jail afterward. Roof posted photos on his website with emblems associated with [[white supremacy]] and with the [[Confederate battle flag]]. The shooting triggered debate on [[Modern display of the Confederate flag| modern display]] of the flag and other memorialization of the Confederacy. Following these murders, the [[South Carolina General Assembly]] voted to remove the flag from State Capitol grounds.\n\nAt the time, this was one of two of the deadliest mass shootings at an American [[place of worship]], alongside [[Waddell Buddhist temple shooting|a 1991 attack]] at a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] temple in [[Waddell, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah Pulliam|last=Bailey|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/06/18/the-charleston-shooting-is-the-largest-mass-shooting-in-a-house-of-worship-since-1991/|title=The Charleston shooting is the largest mass shooting in a house of worship since 1991|work=The Washington Post|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref> Fatalities at the 2017 [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]] and the 2018 [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]] have since exceeded it.\n\n==Background==\nFounded in 1816, the church has played an important role in the [[history of South Carolina]], including the [[Slavery in the United States|slavery era]] and Reconstruction, the [[civil rights movement]], and [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref name=\"NYTimes-DemandSimple-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/10/magazine/our-demand-is-simple-stop-killing-us.html|title=Our Demand Is Simple: Stop Killing Us|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 4, 2015|first=Jay Caspian|last=Kang}}</ref> Founded in 1816, this is the oldest [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in the [[Southern United States|South]], often referred to as \"Mother Emanuel\". The AME Church was founded in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] in 1814 as the first independent black denomination.<ref name=\"CNN-Shooting-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Payne|first1=Ed|title=Charleston church shooting: Multiple fatalities in South Carolina, source says|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/17/us/charleston-south-carolina-shooting/|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mullikin-CivilRightsRide-2013\">{{cite web|last1=Pinckney|first1=Reverend Honorable Clementa C.|title=Civil Rights Ride 2013 \u2013 Clementa C. Pinckney, SC Senate, Pastor Mother Emanuel AME|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XP35_JVnP6g|website=Mullikin Law Firm|access-date=June 18, 2015|date=February 20, 2015}}</ref> It is an [[Black church|historically black congregation]], one of the oldest south of [[Baltimore]]. \n\nWhen one of the church's co-founders, [[Denmark Vesey]], was suspected of planning a slave rebellion in Charleston in 1822, 35 people, including Vesey, were hanged and the church was burned down.<ref name=\"PostCourier-NineShot-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20150617/PC16/150619408|title=Nine shot, multiple fatalities reported in downtown church shooting|newspaper=[[The Post and Courier]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Zimmerman21June>{{ cite news|url= https://newrepublic.com/article/122102/was-emanuel-church-founder-denmark-vesey-victim-racist-paranoia | title=Was the Co-Founder of Charleston's Emanuel Church a Victim of Racist Paranoia, Too?|date=June 21, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|work=The New Republic|first=Jonathan|last=Zimmerman}}</ref> Charleston citizens accepted the claim that a slave rebellion was to begin at the stroke of midnight on June 16, 1822, and to erupt the following day; the shooting in 2015 occurred on the 193rd anniversary of the thwarted uprising.<ref name=\"Nation-WhiteSupremacy-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/210305/charleston-massacre-and-cunning-white-supremacy|title=The Charleston Massacre and the Cunning of White Supremacy|first=Greg|last=Grandin|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Nation]]}}</ref> As the rebuilt church was formally shuttered with other all-black congregations by the city in 1834, the congregation met in secret until 1865 when it was formally reorganized, and acquired the name Emanuel (\"God with us\").<ref name=\"AME-7thDistrict-MotherEmanual\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ame7.org/history/pages/sc_history.htm|title = Mother Emanuel, Charleston, SC|accessdate = June 19, 2015|website = 7th District AME Church, South Carolina|publisher = 7th District AME Office|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150618115132/http://www.ame7.org/history/pages/sc_history.htm|archivedate = June 18, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref> It rebuilt based on a design by Denmark Vesey's son.<ref name=\"Nation-WhiteSupremacy-2015\"/> That structure was badly damaged in the [[1886 Charleston earthquake]].<ref name=NPSEmanuel>{{cite web|work=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/charleston/ema.htm|title=Emanuel AME Church|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost-PainfulChapter-2015\"/> The current building dates from 1891.<ref name=\"Nation-WhiteSupremacy-2015\"/><ref name=\"AME-7thDistrict-MotherEmanual\"/>\n\nThe church's senior pastor, the Rev. [[Clementa C. Pinckney]], had held rallies after the [[shooting of Walter Scott]] by a white police officer two months earlier, in nearby [[North Charleston]]. As a [[South Carolina Senate|state senator]], Pinckney pushed for legislation requiring police to wear [[body worn video|body cameras]].<ref name=\"Heavy-Pinckney5Fact-2015\">{{cite news|last1 = Cleary|first1 = Tom|title = Clementa Pinckney Dead: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url = http://heavy.com/news/2015/06/clementa-pinckney-dead-charleston-church-shooting-victim-black-church-pastor-ame-shot-injury/|accessdate = June 17, 2015|publisher = [[Heavy.com]]|date = June 18, 2015}}</ref> \n\nSeveral commentators noted a similarity between the massacre at Emanuel AME and the 1963 [[16th Street Baptist Church bombing]] of a politically active African-American church in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], where the [[Ku Klux Klan]] (KKK) killed four black girls and injured fourteen others, during the civil rights movement. This attack created support for federal civil rights legislation.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-PainfulChapter-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/18/for-charlestons-emanuel-a-m-e-church-one-of-the-oldest-in-america-shooting-is-another-painful-chapter-in-long-history/|title=For Charleston's Emanuel AME Church, shooting is another painful chapter in rich history|first=Sarah|last=Kaplan|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CharlestonFunerals\"/>\n\nNumerous scholars, journalists, activists and politicians have emphasized placing the attack within the broader context of [[racism in the United States]] rather than seeing it as an isolated event. <!--Attacks on black churches were a common occurrence throughout the 19th and 20th centuries. In the late 1860s, following the [[American Civil War]], racial violence by [[white supremacists]] in the South was ubiquitous during the [[Reconstruction Era]], and a federal grand jury determined that the Klan was a \"terrorist organization\" in 1870.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://isbn.nu/toc/9780807119532 |title=White Terror: The Ku Klux Klan Conspiracy and Southern Reconstruction|last=Trelease|first=Allen W.|publisher=Louisiana State University Press: 1995}}</ref><ref name=\"Vox-ShootingTerrorism-2015\">{{cite web|first=Dara|last=Lind|url=http://www.vox.com/2015/6/18/8803721/charleston-terrorism-racism|title=Why calling the Charleston shooting terrorism is important to so many people|work=[[Vox (magazine)|Vox]]|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>--> In 1996, Congress had passed the Church Arson Prevention Act, making it a federal crime to damage religious property because of its \"racial or ethnic character\", in response to a spate of 154 [[church arson|suspicious church burnings]] since 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/churches/churches.htm|title=In Church Fires, a Pattern but No Conspiracy|work=The Washington Post|date=June 19, 1996|access-date=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost-MentallyIll-2015\">{{Cite news|first = Anthea|last = Butler|title = Shooters of color are called 'terrorists' and 'thugs.' Why are white shooters called 'mentally ill'?|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/06/18/call-the-charleston-church-shooting-what-it-is-terrorism/|newspaper = [[The Washington Post]]|date = June 18, 2015|access-date = June 18, 2015}}</ref> More recent arson attacks against black churches included a black church in [[Massachusetts]] that was burned down the day after the [[first inauguration of Barack Obama]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/15/us/15brfs-CONVICTIONIN_BRF.html|title=Massachusetts: Conviction in Racially Motivated Fire|work=The New York Times|date=April 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Atlantic-ThugsTerrorists-2015\">{{Cite web|title = Thugs and Terrorists Have Attacked Black Churches for Generations|url = https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/06/thugs-and-terrorists-have-plagued-black-churches-for-generations/396212/|date = June 18, 2015|access-date = June 18, 2015|work = [[The Atlantic]]|first = Connor|last = Friedersdorf}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJazeera-BLM-2015\">{{Cite web|title = Black lives \u2014 and churches \u2014 matter|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2015/06/black-lives-churches-matter-charleston-150618060102973.html|publisher = [[Al Jazeera]]|date = June 18, 2015|access-date = June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian-RevGreer-2015\">{{Cite web|title = Terrorism in Charleston demands the government act like black lives matter {{!}} The Rev Broderick Greer|url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jun/18/terrorism-charleston-government-black-lives-matter|website = [[The Guardian]]|date = June 18, 2015|accessdate = June 18, 2015|first = Reverend Broderick|last = Greer}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting==\nAt around 9:05&nbsp;p.m. EDT on Wednesday, June 17, 2015, the [[City of Charleston Police Department|Charleston Police Department]] began receiving calls of a shooting at Emanuel AME Church.<ref name=\"ABC.Documents\"/><ref name=\"PostCourier-NineShot-2015\"/> A man described as white, with sandy-blond hair, around 21 years old and {{convert|5|ft|9|in|cm}} in height, wearing a gray sweatshirt and jeans and opened fire with a [[Glock 41]] [[.45 ACP|.45-caliber]] [[handgun]]<ref>{{cite web | first=Ray |last=Sanchez |first2=Ed |last2=Payne |title=Charleston church shooting: Who is Dylann Roof? |date=June 23, 2015 |access-date=July 8, 2015 |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting-suspect/index.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701184533/http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting-suspect/index.html |archivedate=July 1, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> on a group of people inside the church at a [[Bible study (Christian)|Bible study]] attended by Pinckney. He had first attended the meeting as a participant that evening. The shooter then fled the scene.<ref name=\"Reuters-GunmanAtLarge-2015\">{{cite news | last1=McLeod| first1=Harriet| title=Gunman at large after killing nine at black South Carolina church| url=https://news.yahoo.com/shooting-erupts-church-charleston-south-carolina-021744448.html| accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher =[[Yahoo! News]]| agency=Reuters|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EverythingKnown\">{{cite web | url=http://time.com/3926112/charleston-shooting-latest/| title=Everything We Know About the Charleston Shooting| work=Time| date=June 18, 2015| accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ChillingCase\">{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/06/19/dylann-roof-charleston-police-charged--murder-black-church/28975573/| title=Affidavits spell out chilling case against Dylann Roof| work=USA Today| date=June 19, 2015| accessdate=June 19, 2015| first=Yamiche| last=Alcindor| first2=Doug| last2=Stanglin}}</ref> He had been carrying eight [[Magazine (firearms)|magazines]] holding [[hollow-point bullet]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-roof-hate-crimes-20150722-story.html| title=Dylann Roof indicted on federal hate-crime charges in Charleston church shooting| work=Los Angeles Times| date=July 22, 2015| accessdate=July 22, 2015| first=Timothy M.| last=Phelps}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dylann Roof entering Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, Charleston, South Carolina, 8 pm June 17, 2015.jpg|thumb|Dylann Roof entering Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church through a side door at 8:16 pm, as captured on CCTV]]\n\nDuring the hour preceding the attack, 13 people including the shooter participated in the Bible study.<ref name=\"ChurchShot\">{{cite web | url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/crime/pastor-8-others-fatally-shot-at-church-in-charleston-sc/ar-AAbLntz| title=Pastor, 8 others, fatally shot at church in Charleston, SC| publisher=MSN| date=June 18, 2015| accessdate=June 18, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618193308/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/crime/pastor-8-others-fatally-shot-at-church-in-charleston-sc/ar-AAbLntz| archive-date=June 18, 2015| url-status= dead}}</ref>  According to the accounts of people who talked to survivors, when the shooter walked into the historic African-American church, he immediately asked for Pinckney and sat down next to him, initially listening to others during the study.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/inside-charleston-bible-study-massacre/index.html| title=Inside the Bible Study Massacre: A mom 'laid in her son's blood'| last=Drash| first=Wayne| date=December 17, 2015| publisher=CNN| access-date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> He disagreed with some of the discussion of [[Religious text|Scripture]]. After other participants began praying,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.yahoo.com/charleston-church-shooting-survivor-describes-the-moment-suspected-gunman-dylann-roof-began-firing-221002383.html| title=Charleston church shooting survivor describes the moment suspected gunman Dylann Roof began firing| publisher=Yahoo! News| date=September 9, 2015| access-date=September 9, 2015| first=Jason| last=Sickles}}</ref> he stood up,<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/> and aimed a gun he pulled from a fanny pack at 87-year-old Susie Jackson. Jackson's nephew, 26-year-old Tywanza Sanders, tried to talk him down and asked him why he was attacking churchgoers. The shooter said, \"I have to do it. You rape our women and you're taking over our country. And you have to go.\" When he said he intended to shoot them all, Sanders dove in front of Jackson and was shot first. The shooter fired at the other victims, shouting [[racial epithets]]. He reportedly said, \"Y'all want something to pray about? I'll give you something to pray about.\"<ref name=Borden19June/> He reloaded his gun five times. Sanders' mother and his five-year-old niece, who also attended the study, survived the shooting by pretending to be dead on the floor.<ref name=\"RaceWar\">{{cite web | last1=Payne| first1=Ed| last2=Botelho| first2=Greg| url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting-main/| title=Charleston church shooting: Suspect confesses, says he sought race war| publisher=CNN|date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BroughtBack\">{{cite web | last1=Horowitz| first1=Jason| last2=Corasaniti| first2=Nick| last3=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a| first3=Richard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html| title=Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof Is Brought Back to Charleston| work=The New York Times| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost-SuspectCaptured-2015\"/>\n\nDot Scott, president of the local branch of the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]], said she had heard from victims' relatives that the shooter spared one woman (Polly Shepard),<ref>{{cite web | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/charleston-shooting-gunman-allegedly-survivor-inside-church/story?id=31872085| title=Charleston Shooting: What the Gunman Allegedly Told Churchgoers Before the Shooting| publisher=ABC News| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 18, 2015| first=Nikki| last=Battiste| first2=Emily| last2=Shapiro| first3=Matthew| last3=Stone}}</ref> saying that she could tell other people what happened.<ref name=\"ShootingSuspect\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/us/charleston-church-shooting-suspect/| title=Who is the Charleston church shooting suspect?| publisher=CNN| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> He asked, \"Did I shoot you?\" She replied, \"No.\" Then, he said, \"Good, 'cause we need someone to survive, because I'm gonna shoot myself, and you'll be the only survivor.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=Charleston Shooting: What the Gunman Allegedly Told Churchgoers Before the Shooting| url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/charleston-shooting-gunman-allegedly-survivor-inside-church/story?id=31872085| publisher=ABC News| date=June 18, 2015| access-date=June 22, 2015| first=Nikki| last=Battiste| first2=Emily| last2=Shapiro| first3=Matthew| last3=Stone}}</ref> According to the son of one victim, who spoke to that survivor, the shooter allegedly turned the gun to his own head and pulled the trigger, but discovered he was out of ammunition.<ref name=Phelps20June>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-dylann-roof-suicide-attempt-20150620-story.html| title=Dylann Roof tried to kill himself during attack, victim's son says| work=Los Angeles Times| date=June 20, 2015| access-date=June 22, 2015| first=Timothy M.| last=Phelps}}</ref> He left the church, reportedly after making another \"racially inflammatory statement\" over the victims' bodies.<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/> The entire shooting lasted for approximately six minutes.<ref name=\"ABC.Documents\"/>\n\nSeveral hours later, a [[bomb threat]] was called into the [[Courtyard by Marriott]] hotel on Calhoun Street. This complicated the police investigation of the shooting, as they needed to evacuate the immediate area.<ref name=\"PostCourier-NineShot-2015\"/><ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2015/jun/18/charleston-church-shooting-reports-fatalities-suspect-large-latest-updates| title= Charleston church shooting: police release image of suspect \u2013 latest updates| date=June 18, 2015| work=The Guardian| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Victims===\nThe victims, six women and three men, were all African-American members of the AME Church. Eight died at the scene; the ninth, Daniel Simmons, died at [[MUSC Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Former Mount Pleasant pastor among those slain| url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20150618/PC16/150619340/1177/daniel-l-simmons-74| work=The Post and Courier| date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 22, 2015| first=Tony| last=Bartelme}}</ref> They were all killed by multiple gunshots fired at close range.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-SuspectCaptured-2015\"/><ref name=\"RawEmotion\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/20/us/charleston-shooting-dylann-storm-roof.html| title=In Charleston, Raw Emotion at Hearing for Suspect in Church Shooting| work=The New York Times| date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 19, 2015| first=Nikita| last=Stewart| first2=Richard| last2=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref> Five persons survived the shooting unharmed, including Felicia Sanders, mother of slain victim Tywanza Sanders, and her five-year-old granddaughter, as well as Polly Sheppard, a Bible study member. Pinckney's wife and two daughters were inside the building during the shooting but were elsewhere.<ref name=\"DailyMirror-CharlestonChurch-2015\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20150619/PC16/150619306| title=In an hour, a church changes forever| work=Post and Courier| date=June 19, 2015| access-date=June 20, 2015| first=Doug| last=Pardue| first2=Jennifer Berry| last2=Hawes}}</ref> Those killed were identified as:<ref>{{Cite web | title = Charleston Shooting Victims Identified| url = http://abcnews.go.com/US/charleston-shooting-victims-identified/story?id=31863489| publisher = ABC News| date = June 18, 2015| access-date = June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/us/charleston-church-shooting-victims/ | title=Charleston victims: 9 lives lost to family and community | publisher=CNN | date=June 19, 2015 | access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* [[Clementa C. Pinckney]] (41) \u2013 the church's pastor and a [[South Carolina Senate|South Carolina state senator]].\n* Cynthia Marie Graham Hurd (54) \u2013 a Bible study member and manager for the Charleston County Public Library system; sister of former state senator [[Malcolm Graham (politician)|Malcolm Graham]].\n* Susie Jackson (87) \u2013 a Bible study and church choir member. She was the oldest victim of the shooting.\n* Ethel Lee Lance (70) \u2013 the church's [[Sexton (office)|sexton]].\n* Depayne Middleton-Doctor (49) \u2013 a pastor who was also employed as a school administrator and admissions coordinator at [[Southern Wesleyan University]].\n* Tywanza Sanders (26) \u2013 a Bible study member; grandnephew of victim Susie Jackson. He was the youngest victim.\n* Daniel L. Simmons (74) \u2013 a pastor who also served at Greater Zion AME Church in [[Awendaw, South Carolina|Awendaw]].\n* Sharonda Coleman-Singleton (45) \u2013 a pastor; also a speech therapist and track coach at [[Goose Creek High School]]; mother of MLB prospect Chris Singleton.\n* Myra Thompson (59) \u2013 a Bible study teacher.\n{{Div col end}}\n\nThe victims were later collectively referred to as \"The Charleston Nine\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.laprogressive.com/charleston-nine/|title=Remembering The Charleston Nine| publisher=LA Progressive| date=June 17, 2016| access-date=June 21, 2016}}</ref> and \"The Emanuel Nine\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2017/01/10/the-emanuel-9-the-stories-of-dylann-roofs-victims.html| title=The Emanuel 9: The stories of Dylann Roof\u2019s victims| first=Meg| last=Kinnard| date=January 10, 2017| publisher=| via=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{Main|Dylann Roof}}\n\nDylann Storm Roof<ref name=CourtCaseOfficialName>{{Cite web|url=http://www5.rcgov.us/SCJDWEB/PublicIndex/PIError.aspx?County=40&CourtAgency=40216&Casenum=36973HB&CaseType=C&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=State of South Carolina vs Dylann Storm Roof}}</ref> was named by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) as the suspected killer after his father and uncle contacted police to positively identify him upon seeing security photos of him in the news.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/06/19/arrest-warrant-for-dylann-roof-for-charleston-shooting/28997521/|title=Dylann Roof's father, uncle called police to ID him in church shooting|work=USA Today|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Donna Leinwand|last=Leger}}</ref> Roof was born in [[Columbia, South Carolina]], and was living in largely African-American [[Eastover, South Carolina|Eastover]] at the time of the attack.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost-SuspectCaptured-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/17/white-gunman-sought-in-shooting-at-historic-charleston-african-ame-church/|title=Church shooting suspect Dylann Roof captured amid hate crime investigation|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Roof had a prior police record consisting of two arrests, for trespassing and drug possession, both made in the months before the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kfor.com/2015/06/18/dylann-storm-roof-arrested-in-north-carolina-according-to-report/|title=Dylann Storm Roof arrested in North Carolina|publisher=[[KFOR-TV|KFOR]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Old|first1=Jason|title=Police: Dylann Roof arrested for trespassing, drug possession at Columbiana Centre|url=http://www.wistv.com/story/29353220/police-dylann-roof-arrested-for-trespassing-drug-possession-at-columbiana-centre|publisher=WISTV.com|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> According to then [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI Director]] [[James Comey]], a police report detailing Roof's admission to a narcotics offense should have prevented him from purchasing the weapon used in the shooting. An administrative error within the [[National Instant Criminal Background Check System]] (NICS) excluded Roof's admission (though not the arrest itself) from appearing on his mandatory background check.<ref name=Nakashima10July>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-accused-charleston-shooter-should-not-have-been-able-to-buy-gun/2015/07/10/0d09fda0-271f-11e5-b72c-2b7d516e1e0e_story.html?tid=HP_more?tid=HP_more|title=FBI: Breakdown in background check system allowed Dylann Roof to buy gun|work=The Washington Post|date=July 10, 2015|access-date=July 11, 2015|first=Ellen|last=Nakashima}}</ref><ref name=BBC10July>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-33487577|title=Charleston shooting: System failure 'allowed Roof to buy gun' - FBI|date=July 10, 2015|access-date=July 10, 2015|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHis [[Facebook]] page included an image of Roof wearing a jacket decorated with two [[emblem]]s popular among American [[white supremacist]]s: the [[Flag of Rhodesia|flag of the former]] [[Rhodesia]] (now known as [[Zimbabwe]]) and [[Flag of South Africa (1928\u20131994)|the flag of]] [[South Africa under apartheid|apartheid-era South Africa]].<ref name=\"nyt-ccs\">{{cite web|title=Charleston Church Shooting Suspect, Dylann Storm Roof, Is Captured|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/on-facebook-dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wears-symbols-of-white-supremacy.html|title=On Facebook, Dylann Roof, Charleston Suspect, Wears Symbols of White Supremacy|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dailybeast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2015/06/18/charleston-suspect-is-dylann-roof.html|title=Everything Known About Charleston Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof|work=The Daily Beast|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Roof reportedly told friends and neighbors he intended to kill people, including a plot to attack the [[College of Charleston]], but his claims were not taken seriously.<ref name=\"RoofFriend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/06/20/friend-dylann-roof-says-suspect-planned-attack-on-college-charleston/|title=Friend of Dylann Roof says suspect planned attack on College of Charleston|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RacialMotivation?\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/charleston-shooting-racial-motivation-dylann-storm-roof-told-black-neighbor-he-1974050|title=Charleston Shooting Racial Motivation? Dylann Storm Roof Told Black Neighbor He Planned On Killing|work=The International Business Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015|first=Clark|last=Mindock}}</ref> On June 20, bloggers discovered a website called \"The Last Rhodesian\" (www.lastrhodesian.com); it had been registered to a \"Dylann Roof\" on February 9, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Home \u2014 My website |url=http://lastrhodesian.com/ |date=June 20, 2015 |access-date=June 20, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620134455/http://lastrhodesian.com/ |archivedate=June 20, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Robles20June>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/us/dylann-storm-roof-photos-website-charleston-church-shooting.html|title=Dylann Storm Roof Photos Found on Website|last=Robles|first=Francis|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Gawker\">{{Cite web|title=Here Is What Appears to Be Dylann Roof's Racist Manifesto |url=http://gawker.com/here-is-what-appears-to-be-dylann-roofs-racist-manifest-1712767241 |work=Gawker |date=June 20, 2015 |access-date=June 20, 2015 |first=Brendan |last=O'Connor |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620195150/http://gawker.com/here-is-what-appears-to-be-dylann-roofs-racist-manifest-1712767241 |archivedate=June 20, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> The website included what appeared to be an unsigned manifesto containing Roof's opinions of \"Blacks\", \"Jews\", \"Hispanics\" and \"East Asians\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/210537/two-degrees-separation-between-dylann-roof-and-republican-party|title=The 2 Degrees of Separation Between Dylann Roof and the Republican Party|work=The Nation|date=June 22, 2015|access-date=June 23, 2015|first=Michelle|last=Goldberg}}</ref><ref name=Lewis21June>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/20/dylann-roof-fbi-website-manifesto-charleston-shooting|title=Dylann Roof: FBI probes manifesto and website linked to Charleston suspect|work=The Guardian|date=June 21, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|first1=Paul|last1=Lewis|first2=Amanda|last2=Holpuch|first3=Jessica|last3=Glenza}}</ref> as well a cache of photos, including an image of Roof posing with a handgun and a [[Confederate Battle Flag]].<ref name=Robles20June/> In this manifesto, Roof says he became \"racially aware\" as a result of the 2012 [[shooting of Trayvon Martin]], writing that when he learned about the incident, he read about it, concluding that [[George Zimmerman]] had been in the right. He didn't understand the controversy about it. He said he searched for \"black on White {{sic}} crime\"<!--Not a typo! The word \"White\" is capitalized in original--> on [[Google]] and found the website of the [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], where he read \"pages upon pages\" of cases involving black people murdering white people. Roof wrote that he was \"never been the same since that day\".<ref name = \"Gawker\"/>\n\nAccording to web server logs, Roof's website was last modified at 4:44&nbsp;p.m. on June 17, the day of the shooting, when Roof noted, \"[A]t the time of writing I am in a great hurry.\"<ref name=Robles20June/>\n\nAn unidentified source said interrogations with Roof after his arrest determined he had been planning the attack for around six months. He had researched Emanuel AME Church, and targeted it because of its role in [[African-American history]].<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/> A friend who briefly hid Roof's gun from him said, \"I don't think the church was his primary target because he told us he was going for the school. But I think he couldn't get into the school because of the security ... so I think he just settled for the church.\"<ref name=Weiss>{{cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/man-accused-of-church-killings-spoke-of-attacking-college/article_0329e2bf-5d5e-5a40-b8a0-f173160142d3.html|title=Man accused of church killings spoke of attacking college|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015|first=Mitch|last=Weiss|first2=Michael|last2=Biesecker}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Charlotte|last=Krol|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/11688181/Dylann-Roofs-friend-Charleston-church-wasnt-primary-target.html|title=Dylann Roof's friend: Charleston church 'wasn't primary target'|work=The Telegraph|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRoof's cellphone and computer were seized and subjected to FBI analysis. According to unnamed officials, he was in online communication with other white supremacists, who did not appear to have encouraged the massacre.<ref name=Schmidt3July>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/04/us/dylann-roof-was-in-contact-with-supremacists-officials-say.html|title=Charleston Suspect Was In Touch With Supremacists, Officials Say|date=July 3, 2015|access-date=July 3, 2015|first=Michael S.|last=Schmidt|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The investigation was said to have widened to include other persons of interest.<ref name=Monk2July>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestate.com/news/local/article26200726.html|first=John|last=Monk|date=July 2, 2015|access-date=July 3, 2015|title=EXCLUSIVE: Charges possible against church shooter\u2019s associates|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]}}</ref>\n\nFederal prosecutors said in August 2016 that Roof was \"self-radicalized\" online, instead of adopting his white supremacist ideology \"through his personal associations or experiences with white supremacist groups or individuals or others\".<ref name=\"WashPost.Self\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/08/22/prosecutors-say-accused-charleston-church-gunman-self-radicalized-online/|title=Prosecutors say Dylann Roof \u2018self-radicalized\u2019 online, wrote another manifesto in jail|work=The Washington Post|date=August 23, 2016|access-date=August 23, 2016|first=Mark|last=Berman}}</ref><ref name=\"Yahoo.Entrenched\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/feds-church-shooting-suspect-entrenched-beliefs-114157914.html|title=Feds: Church shooting suspect entrenched in his beliefs|publisher=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press|date=August 23, 2016|access-date=August 23, 2016|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref>\n\n==Criminal investigation==\n\n===Manhunt and capture===\nThe attack was treated as a [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crime]] by police. Officials from the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] were called in to assist in the investigation and manhunt.<ref name=\"EverythingKnown\"/>\n\nAt 10:44&nbsp;a.m., on the morning after the attack, Roof was captured in a traffic stop in [[Shelby, North Carolina]], approximately {{convert|245|mi|km}} from the shooting scene. A .45-caliber pistol was found in the car during the arrest.<ref name=\"WISTV-RoofCustody-2015\">{{cite news |title= Charleston church shooting suspect Dylann Roof in custody in NC |date= June 18, 2015 |work= [[WIS (TV)|WIS]] |publisher= WorldNow and WISTV |url= http://www.wistv.com/story/29351540/charleston-shooting-suspect-from-columbia-area |access-date= June 18, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170131150034/http://www.wistv.com/story/29351540/charleston-shooting-suspect-from-columbia-area |archive-date= January 31, 2017 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/us/charleston-south-carolina-shooting/index.html|title=Shooting suspect in custody after Charleston church massacre|publisher=CNN|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Police received a tip-off from a woman who recognized Roof and his car, a black [[Hyundai Elantra]] with South Carolina license plates and a three-flag [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|\"Confederate States of America\"]] bumper decoration,<ref name=Safi19June>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/19/charleston-shooting-florist-debbie-dills-hailed-a-hero-after-tailing-suspects-car|work=The Guardian|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Michael|last=Safi|title=Charleston shooting: florist Debbie Dills hailed a hero after tailing suspect's car}}</ref><ref name=Cush18June>{{cite news|url=http://gawker.com/dylann-roofs-car-like-s-c-statehouse-flies-a-confede-1712288717 |work=Gawker |title=Dylann Roof's car, like S.C. Statehouse, flies a Confederate Flag |first=Andy |last=Cush |date=June 18, 2015 |access-date=June 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619134327/http://gawker.com/dylann-roofs-car-like-s-c-statehouse-flies-a-confede-1712288717 |archivedate=June 19, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> on [[U.S. Route 74]], recalling security camera images taken at the church and distributed to the media. She later recalled, \"I got closer and saw that haircut. I was nervous. I had the worst feeling. Is that him or not him?\" She called her employer, who contacted local police, and then tailed the suspect's car for {{convert|35|mi|km}} until she was certain authorities were moving in for an arrest.<ref name=ShelbyStar>{{cite news|url=http://www.shelbystar.com/news/local/breaking-tip-from-kings-mountain-florists-led-to-charleston-shooting-suspect-s-arrest-1.492375|title=Tip from Kings Mountain florists led to Charleston shooting suspect's arrest|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015|work=[[Shelby Star]]}}</ref>\n\n===Legal proceedings===\n\nRoof waived his extradition rights and was flown to Sheriff Al Cannon Detention Center in [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]] on the evening of June 18.<ref name=\"BroughtBack\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxcarolina.com/story/29351540/shooting-suspect-dylann-roof-waives-extradition-headed-back-to-charleston|title=Charleston shooting suspect Dylann Roof due in court in Charleston Friday|work=WHNS Greenville|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RoofConfessed\"/> At the jail, his cell-block neighbor was Michael Slager, the former North Charleston police officer charged with murder after [[Shooting of Walter Scott|shooting Walter Scott]] following a traffic stop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/dylann-roof-and-michael-slager-are-cellblock-neighbors-in-charleston-county-jail-171133605.html|title=Dylann Roof and Michael Slager are cellblock neighbors in Charleston County jail|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Jason|last=Sickles}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Martinez |title=South Carolina cop shoots unarmed man: A timeline |date=April 8, 2015 |access-date=June 19, 2015 |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/04/08/us/south-carolina-cop-shoots-black-man-timeline/}}</ref> According to unconfirmed reports, Roof confessed to committing the attack and said he wanted to start a [[race war]].<ref name=\"RaceWar\"/> He reportedly told investigators he almost did not complete his plan because members of the church group had been so nice to him.<ref name=Borden19June>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/south-carolina-governor-urges-death-penalty-charges-in-church-slayings/2015/06/19/3c039722-1678-11e5-9ddc-e3353542100c_story.html|title=Officials: Suspect in church slayings unrepentant amid outcry over racial hatred|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|first1=Jeremy|last1=Borden|first2=Sari|last2=Horwitz|first3=Jerry|last3=Markon}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, Roof was charged with nine counts of murder and one count of possession of a firearm during the commission of a violent crime.<ref name=\"RoofConfessed\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/dylann-roof-confessed-killing-people-charleston-church-source/story?id=31884893|title=Dylann Roof Confessed to Killing 9 People at AME Church, Source Says|publisher=ABC News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Josh|last=Margolin|first2=Emily|last2=Shapiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/charleston-shooting-live-suspect-dylann-roof-in-custody-as-us-mourns-church-massacre--live-updates-10330694.html|title=Charleston shooting: Suspect Dylann Roof in custody as US mourns massacre \u2014 live updates|work=The Independent|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Lizzie|last=Dearden|first2=Payton|last2=Guion}}</ref> He first appeared in Charleston County court via [[Videoconferencing|videoconference]] at a bond hearing later that day. At the hearing, shooting survivors and relatives of five of the victims spoke to Roof directly, saying that they were \"praying for his soul\" and forgave him.<ref name=\"ChillingCase\"/><ref name=\"ForgiveYou\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/familes-of-charleston-church-shooting-victims-to-dylann-roof--we--forgive-you-185833509.html|title=Families of Charleston shooting victims to Dylann Roof: We forgive you|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Dylan|last=Stableford}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/dylann-roof-almost-didnt-go-through-charleston-church-shooting-n378341|title=Dylann Roof 'Almost Didn't Go Through' With Charleston Church Shooting|publisher=NBC News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Daniel|last=Arkin}}</ref><ref name=\"VictimsAddress\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/06/19/i-forgive-you-relatives-of-charleston-church-victims-address-dylann-roof/|title='I forgive you.' Relatives of Charleston church shooting victims address Dylann Roof|work=The Washington Post|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015|first=Mark|last=Berman}}</ref>\n\nThe judge, Charleston County chief magistrate James \"Skip\" Gosnell, Jr., said at the [[Bail in the United States|bond hearing]] that, in addition to the dead victims and their families, \"there are victims on this young man's side of the family [...] Nobody would have ever thrown them into the whirlwind of events that they are being thrown into.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/s-judge-urges-support-dylann-roof-family-article-1.2264319 |title=S.C. judge urges support for accused murderer Dylann Roof's family in bizarre court speech|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|first=Barry|last=Paddock|first2=Rich|last2=Shapiro}}</ref> The judge was reported to have been reprimanded in 2005 by the [[South Carolina Supreme Court]] for using a racial slur while on the bench in 2003.<ref name=\"Reprimand\">{{cite web |url = http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/judge-who-presided-over-dylann-roof-bond-hearing-was-reprimanded-n379066|title=Judge Who Presided Over Dylann Roof Bond Hearing Was Reprimanded for Racial Slur|publisher=NBC News|date=June 20, 2015|access-date=June 21, 2015|first=Elizabeth|last=Chuck}}</ref> Gosnell set a $1 million bond for the weapons possession charge and no bail on the nine counts of murder.<ref>{{cite web|first=Scott|last=Neuman|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/06/19/415792559/-1-million-bond-for-church-shooting-suspect|title=$1 Million Bond For Charleston Church Shooting Suspect|publisher=NPR|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGovernor [[Nikki Haley]] called on prosecutors to seek [[Capital punishment in South Carolina|the death penalty]] against Roof.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2015/06/19/the-latest-church-shooting-haley-calls-for-death-penalty/Sd50001xUfcaWDV1XdZxHM/story.html|title=S.C. governor calls for death penalty in church shooting|work=Boston Globe|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> In June 2016 she warned against divisive rhetoric, saying that it could lead to tragedies such as the massacre at the church, and referred to the rhetoric of 2016 presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chasmar |first1=Jessica |title=Nikki Haley links Donald Trump to Charleston shooting: \u2018I know what that rhetoric can do\u2019 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/3/nikki-haley-links-donald-trump-to-charleston-shoot/ |access-date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 7, Roof was indicted on the nine murder charges and the weapons charge, as well three new charges of attempted murder, one for each person who survived the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/07/07/dylann-roof-indicted-in-charleston-shootings/29815457/|title=Dylann Roof indicted in deadly Charleston rampage|last=Bacon|first=John|date=July 8, 2015|work=USA Today|access-date=July 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/charges-charleston-church-shooting-attempted-murder-162002126.html|title=New charges in Charleston church shooting: Attempted murder|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 7, 2015|access-date=July 7, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref> He also faced federal [[hate crime]] charges,<ref name=nprindictment>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/07/22/425291216/charleston-shooting-suspect-roof-to-be-indicted-on-federal-hate-crime-charges|title=Charleston Shooting Suspect Roof To Be Indicted On Federal Hate Crime Charges|date=July 22, 2015|publisher=NPR|access-date=July 22, 2015}}</ref> including nine counts of using a firearm to commit murder and 24 [[Civil and political rights|civil rights]] violations (12 [[hate crime]] charges and 12 counts of violating a person's [[freedom of religion]]), with 18 of the charges carrying the federal death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20151213/PC16/151219888/1006/in-court-two-cases-against-dylann-roof-playing-out-at-different-pace|title=In court, two cases against Dylann Roof playing out at different pace|work=The Post and Courier|date=December 13, 2015|access-date=January 6, 2016|first=Andrew|last=Knapp}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, Roof pleaded not guilty to the federal charges, based on the advice of his lawyer [[David Bruck]]. Bruck earlier said Roof wanted to plead guilty, but he couldn't advise it without knowing the government's intentions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/suspect-charleston-church-shooting-due-federal-court-094257327.html|title=Not guilty plea in federal court for church shooting suspect|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 31, 2015|access-date=July 31, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard|first2=Bruce|last2=Smith}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Andrew|title=Meet Dylan Roof's Defender|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/07/29/meet-dylann-roof-s-defender|work=The Marshall Project|date=July 31, 2015|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 3, [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit]] solicitor (i.e., [[district attorney]]) Scarlett Wilson announced that she intended to seek the [[Capital punishment in the United States|death penalty]] against Roof in the state proceedings, based on more than two people being killed in the shooting and others' lives put at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/prosecutor-mulling-death-penalty-discuss-church-slayings-155225037.html|title=Prosecutor: Church shooting suspect to face death penalty|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 3, 2015|access-date=September 3, 2015|first=Meg |last= Kinnard| first2 =Jeffrey|last2=Collins}}</ref> On September 16, Roof said through his attorney that he was willing to plead guilty in exchange for a sentence of life in prison without parole.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/accused-gunman-charleston-church-shooting-proposes-guilty-plea-162700935.html|title=Accused gunman in Charleston church shooting proposes guilty plea|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 16, 2015|access-date=September 16, 2015|first=Harriet|last=McLeod}}</ref> \n\nOn October 1, the federal trial was pushed back to at least January 2016 to give prosecutors and Roof's attorneys more time to prepare.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/federal-trial-delayed-charleston-church-shooter-dylann-roof-n436996| title=Federal Trial Delayed for Charleston Church Shooter Dylann Roof| publisher=NBC News|date=October 1, 2015|access-date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> On December 1, the trial was postponed again to an unknown date.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/news-wrap-federal-trial-postponed-again-for-dylann-roof/|title=News Wrap: Federal trial postponed again for Dylann Roof|work=PBS NewsHour|date=December 1, 2015|access-date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> He and Joey Meek, accused of [[misprision of felony]] and lying to investigators about Roof's plans, were to reappear in federal court on February 11, 2016, while their lawyers held a bar meeting with prosecutors to discuss their cases.<ref name=FebruaryHearing>{{cite web| url= http://www.foxcarolina.com/story/30913936/court-hearing-scheduled-for-february-for-dylann-roof-friend|title=Court hearing scheduled for February for Dylann Roof, friend|work=FOX Carolina 21|date=January 7, 2016|access-date=January 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20160107/PC16/160109524/federal-hearing-for-church-shooter-dylann-roof-friend-set-for-feb-11|title=Federal hearing for church shooter Dylann Roof, friend set for Feb. 11|first=Andrew|last=Knapp|work=The Post and Courier|date=January 7, 2016| access-date=January 21, 2016}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=Did Dylann Roof and Joey Meek actually reappear in federal court on November 2, 2016?|date=November 2016}} On November 7, 2016, U.S. District Judge Richard Gergel postponed jury selection until November 9,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2016/11/07/jury-selection-charleston-9-trial-dylann-roof-postponed/93416182/|title=Jury selection in 'Charleston 9' trial of Dylann Roof postponed|first=Tonya|last=Maxwell|work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> later postponing the process again until November 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/11/07/us/dylann-roof-trial/|title=Dylann Roof case: Jury selection postponed over competency issue |work=CNN|date=November 8, 2016|access-date=November 9, 2016}}</ref> Gergel later postponed the jury selection to November 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/judge-orders-dylann-roof-competency-hearing-closed-to-media/2016/11/16/4051a064-ac20-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html|title=Judge orders Dylann Roof competency hearing closed to media|work=The Washington Post|date=November 16, 2016|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/judge-closes-dylann-roof-competency-hearing-public-205925881.html|title=Judge closes Dylann Roof competency hearing to the public|work=YAHOO! NEWS|date=November 16, 2016|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/11/16/us/ap-us-charleston-church-shooting.html |title=Judge Closes Dylann Roof Competency Hearing to the Public|work=The New York Times|date=November 16, 2016|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> On November 28, a federal judge granted a motion by Roof to represent himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/11/28/us/dylann-roof-to-represent-self-charleston-trial/|title=Dylann Roof represents self in Charleston murder trial|work=CNN|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-dylann-roof-charleston-church-shooting-trial-20161128-story.html|title=Judge grants Dylann Roof's 'unwise' request to represent himself in church shooting trial|work=Chicago Tribune|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38135604|title=Charleston massacre accused Dylann Roof to defend himself|work=BBC News|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/28/us/dylann-roof-charleston-massacre.html | title=Dylann Roof to Represent Himself at Trial in Charleston Church Shootings|work=New York Times|last=Sack |first=Kevin |date=November 28, 2016|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref> On December 4, Roof made a handwritten request of Gergel, asking for his defense team for the guilt phase of his [[Capital punishment in the United States|federal death penalty]] trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/us/dylann-roof-charleston-trial.html?_r=0|title=Dylann Roof Wants His Lawyers Back to Begin Trial|work=New York Times| date= December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/dec/04/dylann-roof-charleston-church-shooting-trial-emanuel-ame |title = Dylann Roof: accused Charleston church gunman asks for defense team back|work=The Guardian|date=December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-dylann-roof-lawyers-20161204-story.html|title=Dylann Roof to judge: Let lawyers back on death penalty case|work=Los Angeles Times| date= December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-dylann-roof-church-shooting-trial-20161204-story.html|title=Dylann Roof to judge: Let lawyers back on S.C. church death penalty case |work=Chicago Tribune|date=December 4, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref> On December 5, 2016, Gergel allowed Roof to hire back his lawyers for the guilt phase of his trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/dylann-roof-judge-let-defense-lawyers-back-charleston-church-massacre-n691761|title=Judge Allows Dylann Roof to Hire Back His Lawyers for Guilt Phase of Trial |work=NBC News|date=December 5, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-dylann-roof-attorneys-20161205-story.html|title=Accused Charleston church shooter Dylann Roof allowed to hire lawyers back, for now |work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 5, 2016|access-date=December 5, 2016}}</ref> On December 6, 2016, a federal judge denied a motion by Roof's defense team to delay Roof's trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/judge-denies-motion-delay-charleston-church-shooting-suspect-dylann-roof-n692776|title=Judge Denies Motion to Delay Charleston Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof's Trial Over Slager Outrage|work=NBC News|last=Johnson|first=Alex|date=December 6, 2016|access-date=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to seek the death penalty for Roof was a campaign topic in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic presidential primaries]], with [[Hillary Clinton]] supporting the Justice Department's decision and [[Bernie Sanders]] opposing it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/hillary-clinton-supports-death-penalty-for-dylann-roof_us_57507737e4b0c3752dccde7c|title=Hillary Clinton Supports Death Penalty For Dylann Roof|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 2, 2016|access-date=August 17, 2016| first = Sam | last=Stein}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Roof was declared competent to stand trial for the crimes.<ref name=\"Feig\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/judge-rules-charleston-shooter-dylann-roof-competent-to-stand-trial-news.25715.html? |title=Dylan Roof declared competent to stand trial |last=Feig |first=Zakk |date=November 25, 2016 |website=Hotnewhiphop |access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, following a second competency evaluation, Roof was again deemed competent.<ref>Alan Blinder, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/02/us/dylann-roof-charleston-church-killer-is-deemed-competent-for-sentencing.html Dylann Roof, Charleston Church Killer, Is Deemed Competent for Sentencing], ''New York Times'' (January 2, 2017).</ref>\n\nRoof's trial began on December 7, 2016; witnesses gave testimony describing the shooting in graphic detail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/us/dylann-roof-trial.html| title=Heart-Rending Testimony as Dylann Roof Trial Opens|work=New York Times|last2=Blinder|first2=Alan|last1=Sack|first1=Kevin|date=December 7, 2016|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>Alan Blinder and Kevin Sack, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/14/us/dylann-roof-trial-charleston.html Spared by Gunman in Charleston, Churchgoer Describes Night of Terror]\", ''New York Times'' (December 4, 2016).</ref> On December 15, 2016, Roof was found guilty of all 33 federal charges against him.<ref>Alan Blinder and Kevin Sack, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/15/us/dylann-roof-trial.html Dylann Roof Found Guilty in Charleston Church Massacre]\", ''New York Times'' (December 15, 2016).</ref> For the sentencing phase of the federal trial, Roof dismissed his attorneys and insisted on representing himself. In a statement to the court at his sentencing hearing on January 4, 2017, Roof offered no apology or explanation, saying \"There's nothing wrong with me psychologically.\"<ref name=\"NoApology\">Alan Blinder and Kevin Sack, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/04/us/dylann-roof-sentencing.html Dylann Roof, Addressing Court, Offers No Apology or Explanation for Massacre]\", ''New York Times'' (January 4, 2017).</ref> At the hearing, prosecutors introduced into evidence a two-page excerpt from journal written by Roof from jail six weeks after his arrest, in which Roof composed a white supremacist manifesto, writing: \"I would like to make it crystal clear, I do not regret what I did. I am not sorry. I have not shed a tear for the innocent people I killed.\"<ref name=\"NoApology\"/><ref>Matt Zapotosky, \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/charleston-church-shooter-i-would-like-to-make-it-crystal-clear-i-do-not-regret-what-i-did/2017/01/04/05b0061e-d1da-11e6-a783-cd3fa950f2fd_story.html Charleston church shooter: 'I would like to make it crystal clear, I do not regret what I did']\", ''Washington Post'' (January 4, 2016).</ref>\n\nRoof was sentenced to death on January 10, 2017, and to life in prison without parole on April 10, 2017.\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Charleston Shooting Memorial Service.jpg|thumb|right|A prayer vigil at Morris Brown African Methodist Episcopal Church]]\n\n===Context of racism===\nHeidi Beirich, the director of the Intelligence Project for the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]], a non-profit that seeks to [[List of organizations designated by the Southern Poverty Law Center as hate groups|identify American hate groups]] and confront their activities, said the gunman's reported motive has frequently appeared on white supremacist websites. They say that \"whites are being hugely victimized by blacks and no one is paying attention\". Referring to Roof's comments about rape, Beirich said, \"[Black men sexually assaulting white women] is probably the oldest racist trope we have in the U.S.\"<ref name = \"gulf\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/americas/usa/dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wore-symbols-of-white-supremacy-1.1537476 |title=Dylann Roof, Charleston suspect, wore symbols of white supremacy|work=Gulf News USA|date=June 19, 2015|access-date=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/on-facebook-dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wears-symbols-of-white-supremacy.html|title=Dylann Roof, Charleston Suspect, Wore Symbols of White Supremacy|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> According to Beirich, this trope related to a myth of Southern culture, as in fact African-American women had been much more frequently abused by white men. Lisa Lindquist-Dorr, associate professor at the [[University of Alabama]], said that the myth of black rapists had dominated imaginations of white, Southern men, who considered \"Sexual access to women is a trophy of power, white women embodied virtue and morality, they signified whiteness and white superiority, so sexual access to white women was possessing the ultimate privilege that white men held. It makes women trophies to be traded among men.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/18/white-female-sexuality-and-racist-violence-a-history_n_7613048.html |title=The History Of Using White Female Sexuality To Justify Racist Violence |work=The Huffington Post|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJamelle Bouie wrote in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', \"Make any list of anti-black terrorism in the United States, and you'll also have a list of attacks justified by the specter of black rape.\" He cited the [[Tulsa race riot]] of 1921, the [[Rosewood massacre]] of 1923, and the murder of 14-year-old [[Emmett Till]] in 1955 as examples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/history/2015/06/the_deadly_history_of_they_re_raping_our_women_racists_have_long_defended.html|title=The deadly history of \"They're raping our women\"|work=Salon|first=Jamelle|last=Bouie|access-date=June 25, 2015}}</ref> Beirich said it was unclear early in the investigation whether the suspect had any connection to [[hate group]]s. She noted that \"for several years South Carolina has been the place with the highest density of hate groups.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2015/0618/Charleston-mass-shooting-Reminder-of-past-racist-attacks-on-black-churches|title=Charleston mass shooting: Reminder of past racist attacks on black churches|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Memorials===\n[[File:Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, Charleston South Carolina.jpg|thumb|Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, Charleston South Carolina. 21 June 2015]]\n\nAt [[Morris Brown]] [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in Charleston, numerous people of different races and religions attended a ceremony commemorating the victims and they proclaimed that the attack would not divide the community.<ref name=\"BroughtBack\"/> Another such ceremony occurred at the [[TD Arena]] in the [[College of Charleston]].<ref name=\"RawEmotion\"/> On June 21, four days after the shooting, Emanuel AME Church reopened for its Sunday worship service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/shootings-emotional-burden-looms-over-sunday-sermons-064421413.html|title=Shootings' emotional burden looms over Sunday sermons|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 21, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015|first=Phillip|last=Lucas}}</ref> The Rev. Dr. Norvel Goff Sr., Presiding Elder of Emanuel AME Church, delivered the sermon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://northdallasgazette.com/2015/06/24/charleston-church-filled-with-signs-of-good-and-evil/|title=Charleston Church filled with signs of good and evil|work=North Dallas Gazette|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015|first=Clemon|last=Richardson}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2015, at Emanuel AME Church, funerals were held for victims Ethel Lance and Sharonda Coleman-Singleton and they were attended by several political figures and [[civil rights]] leaders.<ref name=\"CharlestonFunerals\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/26/us/charleston-south-carolina-shooting-funerals.html|title=In Charleston Funerals, Remembering Victims of Hate as Symbols of Love|work=The New York Times|date=June 25, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015 |first = Lizette | last= Alvarez| first2 = Nikita| last2 = Stewart | first3 =Richard| last3=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref> Clementa Pinckney's funeral was held in the basketball arena of the [[College of Charleston]] on June 26, 2015, with President [[Barack Obama]] delivering the eulogy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/06/26/417840372/president-obama-delivers-eulogy-at-funeral-for-rev-clementa-pinckney|title=President Obama Delivers Eulogy At Funeral For Rev. Clementa Pinckney|last=Goodwyn|first=Wade|author-link=Wade Goodwyn|date=June 26, 2015 |publisher=NPR|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Earlier, Pinckney's body lay in state in the [[South Carolina State House]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-83855240/|title=Hundreds line up in South Carolina's capital to honor slain pastor Clementa Pinckney |last =Jarvie|first=Jenny|date=June 24, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> This was followed by the funerals of Tywanza Sanders, Susie Jackson, and Cynthia Graham Hurd the next day.<ref>{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Chuck|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/charleston-church-shooting/funerals-held-three-more-charleston-church-victims-n383066|title='They Will Not Have Died in Vain': Funerals Held for Three Charleston Victims|publisher=NBC News|date=June 27, 2015|accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref> Hurd's family announced that they are establishing the Cynthia Graham Hurd Fund for Reading and Literacy organization in her memory; it is expected to give children easier access to books.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.wcnc.com/story/news/local/regional/2015/06/26/foundation-established-for-cause-close-to-charleston-shooting-victims-heart/29377815/|title=Foundation established for cause close to Charleston shooting victim's heart|publisher=WCNC|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627194743/http://www.wcnc.com/story/news/local/regional/2015/06/26/foundation-established-for-cause-close-to-charleston-shooting-victims-heart/29377815/|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> By July 2, the last of the victims, Daniel Simmons, was buried.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/funeral-victim-charleston-shooting-columbia-32177450 |title=Last Funeral for Victim of Charleston Shooting in Columbia|publisher=ABC News|date=July 2, 2015 |accessdate=July 2, 2015|first=Susanne M.|last=Schafer}}</ref>\n\n===Community response===\nThere has been some criticism aimed towards the community's forgiveness of Roof.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/02/419405863/charlestons-black-leaders-want-justice-as-much-as-forgiveness|title=Charleston's Black Leaders Want To See Justice As Much As Forgiveness|publisher=NPR|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Black Lives Matter]] movement has protested the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Black Lives Matter: Charleston Shooting Was an Act of Terror|url=http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Black-Lives-Matter-Charleston-Shooting-Was-an-Act-of-Terror-20150620-0010.html|work=[[TeleSUR]]|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=y|November 2019}}\n\nQuestions were raised about the security of black churches (as well as the security of churches in general) and their long-standing practice of welcoming anyone who is willing to pray (as most Christian churches are, regardless of the race of the majority of its parishioners). Roof, a stranger to churchgoers, was easily able to enter Emanuel AME Church with no questions asked. In the weeks after the shooting, [[African Methodist Episcopal Church|AME Church]] leaders distributed a document titled \"12 Considerations for Congregational Security\", which recommended creating security plans and teams for black churches, improving communications, developing relationships with local law enforcement, and securing and monitoring all entrances and exits to churches. Some churches considered hiring armed security guards and installing metal detectors, but conversations in support of these steps have currently not gained traction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/15/black-churches-straddle-security-openness/31527859/|title=After Charleston, black churches straddle fine line between security, openness|work=USA Today|date=August 16, 2015|accessdate=August 16, 2015|first=Tyler|last=Pager}}</ref>\n\nNine artists from across the United States created portraits of the victims as a tribute. The portraits were put on display at Principle Gallery for one month, and were given to the victims' families afterwards.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weismann|first1=Lisa|title=Artists donate talent for Emanuel AME victim portraits| url= http://www.live5news.com/story/32098215/artists-donate-talent-for-emanuel-ame-victim-portraits |accessdate=June 2, 2016|agency=Live5News|publisher=Frankly Media and Raycom Media|date=May 30, 2016}}</ref> Artists involved in the memorial included Ricky Mujica, Mario Andres Robinson, Lauren Tilden, Paul McCormack, Gregory Mortenson, Catherine Prescott, Terry Strickland, [[Judy Tak\u00e1cs]], and [[Stephanie Deshpande]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Charleston portrait project pays tribute to Emanuel 9|url=http://counton2.com/2016/05/28/principle-gallery-charleston-to-unveil-emanuel-9-portrait-project/|accessdate=June 2, 2016|agency=WCBD News 2|publisher=Media General Communications Holdings, LLC|date=May 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2016, survivors of the shooting sued the FBI for inadvertently enabling Roof to purchase the gun used in the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/charleston-church-shooting-victims-sue-fbi-over-gun-145126439.html|title=Charleston church shooting victims sue FBI over gun buy|publisher=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press|date=July 1, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref>\n\n===Other investigations===\nThe FBI is investigating possible [[church arson]] after several black churches burned down in one week's time following the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/officials-firefighters-battling-blaze-black-church-sc-024633155.html|title=Another black church in South Carolina burns; cause unknown|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2015|first=Jeffrey|last=Collins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/church-fires-common-usually-not-result-arson-083959655.html|title=Church fires not usually arson; weather found as cause in SC|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2015|first=Bruce|last=Smith|first2=Ray|last2=Henry}}</ref> On July 3, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported that the investigation concluded that the fires were unrelated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3945382/arson-black-churches-charleston-church-shooting-fire-lightning-south-carolina/|title=The Black-Church Fires in Southern States Are Not Connected, Authorities Say|work=Time|date=July 3, 2015|accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe FBI underwent a 30-day review to examine the lapses in the background-check system that allowed the suspected shooter to legally purchase the gun used in the shooting.<ref name=Nakashima10July/> According to [[James Comey]], Roof had been arrested in March on a felony drug charge, which would have required an inquiry into the charge during the background check examination. However, he was actually arrested on a misdemeanor drug charge, which was incorrectly written as a felony at first due to a data entry error made by a jail clerk. The mistake was noticed by the jail two days after the arrest, but the change was not made. The FBI agent conducting the background check examination then called the wrong agency while making the inquiry into the drug charge, due to having limited information on law enforcement agencies in [[Lexington County, South Carolina|Lexington County]]. This subsequently allowed Roof to make the purchase. However, despite the misdemeanor charge, he still would not have been able to purchase the gun under a law that barred anyone who is an \"unlawful user of or addicted to any controlled substance\" from owning firearms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2015/07/11/dylann-roof-apparently-had-not-been-arrested-for-a-felony-a-month-before-he-went-through-a-gun-purchase-background-check/|title=Dylann Roof apparently had not been arrested for a felony a month before he went through a gun purchase background check|work=The Washington Post|date=July 11, 2015|accessdate=July 12, 2015|first=Eugene|last=Volokh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/jail-clerical-error-acknowledged-church-shooting-gun-buy-190536334.html|title=Jail clerical error acknowledged in church shooting gun buy|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=July 13, 2015|accessdate=July 13, 2015|first=Jeffrey|last=Collins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jail-error-led-to-charleston-shooting-suspect-dylann-roofs-gun-buy/|title=Jail error led to Charleston shooting suspect's gun purchase|publisher=CBS News|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Several bills aiming to fix this loophole were proposed, and South Carolina legislation planned to discuss the loophole in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestate.com/news/local/article50646270.html|title=SC bills aim to close loophole that allowed Dylann Roof to buy a gun|work=The State|date=December 19, 2015|accessdate=January 6, 2016|first=Seanna|last=Adcox}}</ref> On August 30, 2019, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals]] ruled that the survivors and families of the deceased can sue the Federal government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ca4.uscourts.gov/opinions/181931.P.pdf|title=No. 18\u20131931|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, one of the friends who briefly hid Roof's gun away from him was arrested, reportedly for lying to federal authorities during their investigation and failing to report a crime. The next day, he pleaded not guilty to one count of making false statements to federal investigators and one count of concealing knowledge about a crime. He faces a maximum of nine years in prison and a $500,000 fine. According to legal experts, prosecutors possibly intend to use the prospect of federal charges against him as leverage for testifying against Roof.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/feds-investigate-friend-charleston-shooting-suspect-083706466.html|title=Official: Friend of Charleston church shooter arrested|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 17, 2015|accessdate=September 17, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/friend-alleged-church-shooter-appear-court-081354454.html|title=Indictment: Church shooter's friend knew about attack plans|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=September 18, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2015|first=Meg|last=Kinnard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/09/18/joey-meek-friend-of-dylann-roof-charged-in-connection-with-church-shooting/|title=Joey Meek, friend of Dylann Roof, pleads not guilty to federal charges|work=The Washington Post|date=September 18, 2015|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> He was to reappear in federal court alongside Roof on February 11, 2016.<ref name=FebruaryHearing/>{{clarify|reason=Did the friend actually reappear in federal court alongside Roof on November 2, 2016?|date=November 2016}} Joey Meek pleaded guilty in federal court April 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thestate.com/news/local/crime/article74651222.html|title=Joey Meek knew what Dylann Roof was going to do, told others not to talk to FBI|last=Monk|first=John|work=The State (newspaper)|date=April 29, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> He was sentenced to 27 months in prison in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/03/21/us/joey-meek-sentencing-dylann-roof-charleston/|title=Dylann Roof friend sentenced to 27 months in prison|work=CNN|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n\n===Officials===\n[[List of mayors of Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston Mayor]] [[Joseph P. Riley, Jr.]] denounced the attack and said, \"Of all cities, in Charleston, to have a horrible hateful person go into the church and kill people there to pray and worship with each other is something that is beyond any comprehension and is not explained. We are going to put our arms around that church and that church family.\"\n\n[[Governor of South Carolina|South Carolina Governor]] [[Nikki Haley]] said, \"While we do not yet know all of the details, we do know that we'll never understand what motivates anyone to enter one of our places of worship and take the life of another. Please join us in lifting up the victims and their families with our love and prayers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/9-people-killed-in-shooting-at-black-church-in-charleston-s-c-1.3118057|title=9 people killed in shooting at black church in Charleston, S.C.|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] said in Charleston on June 18, \"Once again, innocent people were killed in part because someone who wanted to inflict harm had no trouble getting their hands on a gun...We as a country will have to reckon with the fact that this type of mass violence does not happen in other advanced countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/7613074|title=Obama On Charleston Shooting: 'This Type Of Mass Violence Does Not Happen In Other Advanced Countries'|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> At a Washington press conference later that day, he said, \"Michelle and I know several members of Emanuel AME Church. We knew their pastor, Reverend Clementa Pinckney, who, along with eight others, gathered in prayer and fellowship and was murdered last night. And to say our thoughts and prayers are with them and their families, and their community, doesn\u2019t say enough to convey the heartache and the sadness and the anger that we feel.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3926839/president-obama-charleston-transcript/|title=Read President Obama\u2019s Speech on the Charleston Church Shooting|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, the [[United States Department of Justice]] fast-tracked a [[Victims of Crime Act of 1984|Crime Victim Assistance Formula Grant]] of $29 million to the South Carolina government. Some of the money will be allocated to the survivors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-charleston-assistance-idUSKBN0OZ2CN20150619|title=U.S. to fast track $29 million to help Charleston shooting victims' families|agency=Reuters|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Families===\nAfter Roof's appearance at his bond hearing, his family issued a statement, expressing their shock and grief at his actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3929115/roof-family-statement-church-shootings/|title=Dylann Roof's Family Breaks Silence on Shooting|work=Time|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Dan|last=Kedmey}}</ref> Following the funerals of several of the victims in the shooting, they issued a second statement, expressing their condolences to the victims' families and announcing the temporary postponement of comments out of respect for them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/dylann-roofs-family-releases-new-statement-charleston-church-shooting-offers-1984222|title=Dylann Roof's Family Releases New Statement On Charleston Church Shooting, Offers Condolences To Victims' Families|work=The International Business Times|date=June 25, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|first=Thomas|last=Barrabi}}</ref> During the bond hearing, several family members of the victims told Roof that they forgave him.<ref name=\"ForgiveYou\"/>\n\n===Local community===\nThe local community surrounding Charleston held prayer vigils and fundraisers. A mass unity rally was also held on the [[Arthur Ravenel Bridge]] on the evening of June 21. Organizers of the rally claimed there were up to 20,000 supporters in the rally. Tens of thousands of individuals crossed from the [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|Mount Pleasant]] side of the bridge to the downtown Charleston side, carrying supportive signs and flags. Dozens of boats joined in the procession as well <ref>{{cite news|title=Organizers says 20,000 joined Bridge to Peace march on Ravenel Bridge|url=http://abcnews4.com/archive/watch-bridge-to-peace-event-live-on-abcnews-4-or-stream-it-live|accessdate=March 3, 2016|work=ABC News 4|date=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Religious community===\nThe [[World Methodist Council]], an association of worldwide churches in the [[Methodism|Methodist]] tradition, of which the AME Church is a part, said it \"urges prayer and support for the victims' families and those members of Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church who have been so gravely affected by this crime motivated by hate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldmethodistcouncil.org/response-to-deadly-shootings-at-church-in-charleston-sc/|title=Response to Deadly Shootings at Church in Charleston, SC|year=2015|work=World Methodist Council|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> The President and Vice-President of the British Methodist Conference, also a member of the World Methodist Council, sent a letter of solidarity to the [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]], saying, \"The hearts of the members of the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain]] go out to the families and friends of those killed; to the Church; and to the wider communities in Charleston.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/news-and-events/news-releases/message-of-solidarity-sent-to-african-methodist-episcopal-church|title=Message of solidarity sent to African Methodist Episcopal Church|work=The Methodist Church in Britain|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Methodist Council of Bishops|Council of Bishops]] of [[The United Methodist Church]], also a member of the World Methodist Council and in [[full communion]] with the African Methodist Episcopal Church, called on its members \"to support the victims of this and all acts of violence, to work to end racism and hatred, to seek peace with justice, and to live the [[Lord's Prayer|prayer that our Lord gave us]], that God's 'kingdom come, [and] will be done, on earth as it is in heaven'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/united-methodists-stand-with-ame-after-church-shooting2|title=United Methodists stand with AME after church shooting|last=Hahn|first=Heather|last2=Brodie|first2=Matt|date=June 18, 2015|publisher=The United Methodist Church|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Christian Methodist Episcopal Church]], also a member of the World Methodist Council and in full communion with the African Methodist Episcopal Church, shared its support with the presiding bishop, stating, \"let us join with the AMEs in prayer for the healing of the families touched by this tragedy&nbsp;\u2013 the families of the victims and the family of the perpetrator\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecmechurch.org/news.htm|title=News & Announcements for the Christian Methodist Episcopal Church|last=Reddick|first=Lawrence|date=June 18, 2015|work=Christian Methodist Episcopal Church|accessdate=June 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625010002/http://www.thecmechurch.org/news.htm|archivedate=June 25, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Rev. [[Olav Fykse Tveit]], general secretary of the [[World Council of Churches]], said, \"We offer our prayers for healing to the wounded and traumatized, and solidarity and accompaniment to our sisters and brothers in the African Methodist Episcopal Church\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Kenny|url=http://www.ecumenicalnews.com/article/worldwide-churches-condemn-us-race-hate-killing-in-charleston-30680|title=Worldwide churches condemn US 'race-hate' killing in Charleston|work=Ecumenical News|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Archbishop [[Joseph Edward Kurtz]], the president of [[U.S. Conference of Catholic Bishops]], made similar remarks.<ref>{{cite web|first=Carol|last=Kuruvilla|first2=Antonia|last2=Blumberg|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/18/religious-leaders-react-charleston-shooting_n_7613324.html|title=Faith Community Rallies Around Charleston Church After Shooting|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVarious national [[Judaism|Jewish]] organizations, including the [[American Jewish Committee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=7oJILSPwFfJSG&b=8451793&ct=14736637&notoc=1|title=AJC Deplores Fatal Attack on Black Charleston Church|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|work=AJC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624021204/http://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=7oJILSPwFfJSG&b=8451793&ct=14736637&notoc=1|archivedate=June 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Union for Reform Judaism]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rj.org/blog/2015/06/18/reform-movement-mourns-victims-of-charleston-ame-tragedy/|title=Reform Movement Mourns Victims of Charleston AME Tragedy|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|publisher=RJ.org}}</ref> [[Jewish Federations of North America]], [[Anti-Defamation League]], and [[Orthodox Union]] issued statements deploring the attack and expressing deep grief and horror. The [[Rabbinical Assembly]], in its own statement, quoted [[Leviticus]], saying, \"'Do not stand idly by the blood of your neighbor.' Hateful, violent acts such as this have no place in our society, in a country known for its diversity and blending of various cultures.\"<ref name=\"Wilner\">{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Wilner|url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Suspect-arrested-for-South-Carolina-church-shooting-406502|title=Jewish groups express 'heartbreak' over Charleston church shooting|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMany national [[Muslim]] organizations and individual [[imam]]s,<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeSarro|first1=Nina|title=Muslim leader prays for peace in wake of Charleston shooting|url=http://www.myfoxlubbock.com/news/local/story/islamic-center/J9sDgyXzqUqhkcAB5J1GEw.cspx|publisher=myfoxlubbock.com|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our Community Responds to the Charleston Tragedy|url=http://detroitinterfaithcouncil.com/2015/06/20/our-community-responds-to-the-charleston-tragedy/|website=detroitinterfaithcouncil.com/|publisher=DETROIT INTERFAITH COUNCIL|accessdate=June 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621070303/http://detroitinterfaithcouncil.com/2015/06/20/our-community-responds-to-the-charleston-tragedy/|archive-date=June 21, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> such as [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations]],<ref>{{cite web|title=CAIR Stands with African-American Community After Terror Attack on Charleston Church|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cair-stands-with-african-american-community-after-terror-attack-on-charleston-church-300101476.html|agency=PR Newswire|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> [[Islamic Society of North America]] (ISNA),<ref>{{cite web|title=ISNA Statement on Charleston Church Shooting|url=http://www.isna.net/isnas-statement-on-charleston-church-shooting.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113312/http://www.isna.net/isnas-statement-on-charleston-church-shooting.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 4, 2016|publisher=isna.net|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> and [[Islamic Circle of North America]] issued statements condemning the attack and offering sympathy for the victims.<ref name=\"onislam.net\">{{cite web|title=US Muslims Call for Charleston 'Day of Prayer'|url=http://www.onislam.net/english/news/americas/487835-us-muslims-call-for-charleston-day-of-prayer.html|publisher=onislam.net|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> In a joint statement, CAIR and Muslim leaders in [[Baltimore]] quoted the [[Quran]], saying, \"The Qur'an, the Muslim holy book, says: 'He who takes one life, it is as if he has slain all of mankind. And he who saves one life, it is as if he has saved all of mankind.'\"<ref name=\"onislam.net\"/>\n\nMuslim and Jewish religious organizations have raised several hundred thousand dollars to help rebuild black churches that were burned down in the weeks after the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/10/muslim-jewish-groups-fundraising-rebuild-black-churches|title=Muslim and Jewish groups at forefront of efforts to rebuild black churches|last=Blau|first=Max|date=July 10, 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nAt least eighteen candidates and prospective candidates for the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election]] expressed reactions through various media and addresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/u-presidential-candidates-reaction-south-carolina-church-shootings-123405886.html|title=U.S. presidential candidates react to South Carolina church shootings|agency=Reuters|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> According to [[National Public Radio|NPR]], Democratic and Republican candidates found different ways to address the incident, with Democrats seeing race and gun control as central issues, while Republicans pointing to mental illness and referring to it as tragic but random act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Predictably, Democrats, Republicans Don't Agree on Charleston Causes, Solutions|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/06/19/415747034/predictably-democrats-republicans-dont-agree-on-charleston-causes-solutions|publisher=NPR|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|first=Don|last=Gonyea|first2=Domenico|last2=Montanaro}}</ref> Most Republican candidates eventually acknowledged that race was a motivating factor for the shooting. According to the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', the shooting became a precarious subject for Republican presidential contenders, in particular in regard of the racial motivations behind it, as South Carolina holds primaries and the state's political importance have resulted in some candidates \"skirting around the clear racial motivations behind the attack\".<ref>{{cite web|title=How presidential candidates are responding to Charleston, S.C., shooting|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/USA-Update/2015/0622/How-presidential-candidates-are-responding-to-Charleston-S.C.-shooting|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015|first=Henry|last=Gass}}</ref>\n\nThe night following the attack, [[Jon Stewart]] delivered a monologue on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' discussing the tragic nature of the news, condemning the attacks as well as the media's response to it.   Stewart argued that in response to [[Islamic terrorism]], politicians declare they will do \"whatever we can\" to make America safe, even justifying [[Torture and the United States#Torture, interrogation and prisons in the War on Terror|torture]], but respond to this mass shooting with \"what are you gonna do, crazy is as crazy does\".<ref name=\"RollingStone-JonStewart-2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/watch-jon-stewarts-heartbreaking-charleston-shooting-monologue-20150619|title=Watch Jon Stewart's Heartbreaking Charleston Shooting Monologue|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Daniel|last=Kreps}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], whose website Roof cited as a source for his radicalization, issued a statement on its website \"unequivocally condemn[ing]\" the attack, but that Roof has some \"legitimate grievances\" against black people. An additional statement from the group's president, Earl Holt III, disavowed responsibility for the crime and said the group's website \"accurately and honestly report[s] black-on-white violent crime\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/ccc-dylann-roof-legitimate-grievances|work=Talking Points Memo|last=Thompson|first=Catherine|title=Group That May Have Influenced Charleston Killer: He Had Some 'Legitimate Grievances'|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an online forum, Charles Cotton, a lawyer in [[Houston]] and a national board member of the [[National Rifle Association]], placed blame for the shooting on Pinckney for not allowing the churchgoers to hold [[concealed carry]] weapons inside the church. In 2011, Pinckney had voted against legislation that would allow concealed handguns to be carried into public places. Cotton also criticized the effectiveness of gun-free zones, stating, \"If we look at mass shootings that occur, most happen in gun-free zones.\" Cotton's comment has since been deleted from the online forum.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lisa Maria|last=Garza|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nra-executive-suggests-slain-charleston-pastor-blame-gun-043458974.html|title=NRA executive suggests slain Charleston pastor to blame for gun deaths|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"TimesPicayune-AP-NRABlamesPinckney-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Associated Press|title=Charleston shooting the fault of slain pastor Clementa Pinckney, NRA board member writes|url=http://www.nola.com/crime/index.ssf/2015/06/charleston_shooting_the_fault.html|accessdate=June 21, 2015|work=[[The Times-Picayune]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the shooting, [[Rhodesians Worldwide]], an online magazine catering to the Rhodesian expatriate community, issued a brief statement condemning Roof's actions in response to his use of the [[Flag of Rhodesia|Rhodesian flag]]. It said 80% of the [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] were black and that the [[Rhodesian Bush War]] was a struggle against [[communism]] rather than a racial conflict.<ref name=\"RhodesiansWorldwide-Condemning-2015\">{{cite web|title=Rhodesians Worldwide homepage|url=http://rhodesians-worldwide.com/|work=Rhodesians Worldwide|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Richardson]], the owner of the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[Carolina Panthers]], donated $100,000 to the Mother Emanuel Hope Fund set up by Mayor Riley, specifically calling for $10,000 to each of the families of the nine victims to cover their funeral expenses, and the remaining $10,000 to be delivered to the Emanuel AME Church itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000498123/article/panthers-owner-donates-100000-to-charleston-victims|title=Panthers owner donates $100,000 to Charleston victims|publisher=National Football League|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcnc.com/story/sports/nfl/panthers/2015/06/20/panthers-make-generous-donation-for-church-shooting-victims/29031349/|title=Panthers make generous donation for church shooting victims|publisher=WCNC.com|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621211649/http://www.wcnc.com/story/sports/nfl/panthers/2015/06/20/panthers-make-generous-donation-for-church-shooting-victims/29031349/|archive-date=June 21, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nArtist [[Carrie Mae Weems]] has created a theater piece in response to the murders, called ''Grace Notes''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/this-artist-is-taking-on-americas-history-of-violence|title=This artist is taking on America\u2019s history of violence|last=Brown|first=Jeffrey|date=January 8, 2018|website=PBS NewsHour|access-date=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCivil rights advocates said the Charleston attack not only fit the dictionary definition of terrorism but reflected a history of attempts by the [[Ku Klux Klan]] and other white supremacist groups to terrorize African-Americans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-shooting-terrorism-or-hate-crime.html |title=Many Ask, Why Not Call Church Shooting Terrorism |work=New York Times|date=18 June 2015|accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged retaliatory attack===\n{{main|Burnette Chapel shooting}}\n\nAccording to the State of Tennessee, a 2017 church shooting that killed a woman and wounded seven others was retaliation for the Charleston shooting. The suspect, who is black, reportedly said that he wanted to \"kill 10 white people\" and referenced Roof and the [[Pan-African flag]] in a note he left in his car.<ref>https://jg-tc.com/news/national/state-suspect-aimed-to-kill-at-least-white-churchgoers/article_7313a262-6692-5f9b-be25-448bdae251b8.html</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-nashville-church-shooter-motive-20190521-ub3jfebrujifbdpvfcp46bbhh5m.html|title=Nashville-area shooter wanted to kill 10 white congregants to avenge Charleston church victims|last=Ganz|first=Jami|work=New York Daily News|access-date=June 16, 2019|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/antioch-church-shooting-more-testimony-expected-on-day-2-of-trial|title=Gunman's note: \"Dylann Roof is less than nothing\", says shooting was \"vengeance\" for Charleston|last=Bowles|first=Laken|work=News Channel 5 (Nashville)|access-date=June 14, 2019|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\n\n===Confederate flag===\n{{main|Modern display of the Confederate flag#Reactions to 2015 Charleston church shooting}}\n[[File:Battle flag of the Confederate States of America.svg|thumb|upright=0.7|The battle flag of the [[Confederate States of America]].]]\n\nOn June 18, 2015, the day after the shooting, many flags, including those at the [[South Carolina State House]], were flown at [[half-staff]]. The [[Confederate battle flag]] flying over the South Carolina Confederate Monument<ref>{{cite web|title=South Carolina Confederate Monument|url=http://www.hmdb.org/Marker.asp?Marker=17048|publisher=The Historical Marker Database|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> near the state house was not lowered, as South Carolina law prohibited alteration of the flag without the consent of two-thirds of the state legislature.<ref name=\"wp0619\">{{cite news|last1=Moyer|first1=Justin Wm.|title=Why South Carolina's Confederate flag isn't at half-staff after church shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/06/19/why-south-carolinas-confederate-flag-isnt-at-half-mast-after-church-shooting/|accessdate=June 19, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> Also, the flagpole lacked a pulley system, meaning the flag could not be flown at half-staff, only removed.<ref name=\"wp0619\"/>\n\n====Flag removal from statehouse grounds====\n[[File:South Carolina State House.JPG|thumb|right|[[South Carolina State House]] with the Confederate Monument in front, flag at rest|alt=View of the South Carolina State House with the Confederate Monument in front]]\n\nCalls to remove the Confederate flag from statehouse grounds, as well as debates over the context of its symbolic nature, were renewed after the attack<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/06/19/dylann-roof-charleston-police-charged-with-murder-black-church/28975573/|title=Dylann Roof charged with 9 counts of murder in Charleston attack|work=USA Today|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|first=Yamiche|last=Alcindor|first2=Doug|last2=Stanglin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/20/us/charleston-shooting-reignites-debate-about-confederate-flag.html|title=Charleston Shooting Reignites Debate About Confederate Flag|work=The New York Times|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|first=Katie|last=Rogers}}</ref> by several prominent figures, including President [[Barack Obama]], [[Mitt Romney]], and [[Jeb Bush]].<ref name=\"NYT.Flag\">{{cite web|title=Mitt Romney, Jeb Bush and Ted Cruz Weigh In on Confederate Flag at South Carolina Capitol|url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/06/20/mitt-romney-calls-for-removal-of-confederate-flag-at-south-carolina-capitol/|work=The New York Times|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015|first=Michael|last=Barbaro}}</ref> On June 20, 2015 several thousand people gathered in front of the South Carolina State House in protest. An online petition at [[MoveOn.org]] encouraging the flag's removal had received over 370,000 signatures by that time.<ref name=FlagProtest>{{cite news|last1=Macpherson|first1=Robert|title=Protesters target Confederate flag after Charleston killings|url=https://news.yahoo.com/protesters-target-confederate-flag-charleston-killings-015001853.html|accessdate=June 21, 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt a statehouse press conference on June 22, Governor [[Nikki Haley]], flanked by elected officials of both parties, including U.S. Republican senators [[Lindsey Graham]] and [[Tim Scott]], and former Republican Governor [[Mark Sanford]], called for the flag to be removed by the state legislature, saying that while the flag was \"an integral part of our past, it does not represent the future\" of South Carolina.<ref name=Niquette22June>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-06-22/south-carolina-officials-call-for-confederate-flag-to-come-down|title=South Carolina Governor Backs Removal of Confederate Flag|first=Mark|last=Niquette|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=Bloomberg News}}</ref> Eulogizing the Rev. Clementa Pinckney on June 26, 2015, before 5,000 congregants at the [[College of Charleston]], President [[Barack Obama]] acknowledged that the shooting had catalyzed a broad movement, backed by Republicans and Democrats, to remove the flag from official public display. \"Blinded by hatred, [the gunman] failed to comprehend what Reverend Pinckney so well understood: the power of God's grace,\" Obama said. \"By taking down that flag we express God's grace. But I don't think God wants us to stop there.\"<ref name=Sack26June>{{cite news|first1=Kevin|last1=Sack|first2=Lizette|last2=Alvarez|work=The New York Times|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/27/us/thousands-gather-for-funeral-of-clementa-pinckney-in-charleston.html|title=President Obama Eulogizes Charleston Pastor as One Who Understood Grace}}</ref><ref name=Hathaway26June>{{cite news|url=http://gawker.com/obama-leads-mourners-in-amazing-grace-at-pinckney-fun-1714240326 |title=In Breathtaking Moment, Obama Leads Charleston Mourners in 'Amazing Grace' |first=Jay |last=Hathaway |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=June 26, 2015 |work=Gawker |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627094419/http://gawker.com/obama-leads-mourners-in-amazing-grace-at-pinckney-fun-1714240326 |archivedate=June 27, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2015, the [[South Carolina Senate]] voted to remove the Confederate flag from display outside the South Carolina State House. Following 13 hours of debate, the vote in the House to remove it was passed by a two-thirds majority (94\u201320) on July 9. Governor Nikki Haley signed the bill on July 9.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/07/09/south-carolina-rep-jenny-horne-on-her-historic-and-surprisingly-personal-speech-it-needed-to-be-done/?hpid=z2 ''Washington Post'', Jenny Horne: How a descendant of the president of the Confederacy helped vanquish his flag] accessdate=2015-07-09</ref>  On July 10, the Confederate flag was taken down for the last time; it will be stored until it can later be shown in a museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/confederate-flag-fans-critics-gather-s-statehouse-article-1.2287700|title=Confederate flag fans, critics gather at S.C. statehouse|work=The New York Daily News|date=July 10, 2015|accessdate=July 10, 2015|first=Meg|last=Wagner|first2=Corky|last2=Siemaszko}}</ref>\n\n====Retailers end sales of the flag====\n\nOn June 23, 2015, retailers [[Wal-Mart]], [[Amazon.com]], [[Sears Holding Corporation]] (which owns [[Sears]] and [[Kmart]]), and [[eBay]] all announced plans to stop selling merchandise with the Confederate flag.<ref>{{cite web|first=MJ|last=Lee|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/22/politics/confederate-flag-walmart-south-carolina/|title=Walmart, Amazon.com, Sears, eBay to stop selling Confederate flag merchandise|publisher=CNN|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Similarly, [[Warner Bros.]] announced they were halting production of \"[[General Lee (car)|General Lee]]\" car toys, which prominently feature a Confederate flag on the roof.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rich|first1=McCormik|title=Warner Bros. scraps Dukes of Hazzard car toys over Confederate flag controversy|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/6/23/8836571/dukes-of-hazzard-car-toys-confederate-flag|work=The Verge|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> Many major flag manufacturers also decided to stop profiting from the flag.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-shooting-south-carolina-flag-fact-idUSKBN0P421P20150624|title=At rural South Carolina flag factory, sadness and pride|date=June 24, 2015|first=Edward|last=McAllister|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3932924/flag-manufacturer-confederate/|title=Prominent Flag Manufacturer Will Stop Producing Confederate Flags|date=June 23, 2015|first=Katy|last=Osborn|work=Time|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chapa|first1=Sergio|title=Dixie Flag will no longer sell confederate flags|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/news/2015/06/23/dixie-flag-will-no-longer-sell-the-confederate.html|work=San Antonio Business Journal|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Removal of monuments and memorials related to the Confederacy===\n{{see also|Removal of Confederate monuments and memorials}}\n\nThe city of [[New Orleans]] has announced plans to remove four memorials related to the Confederacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/vigil-vs-removal-of-statue-of-confederate-president-jefferson-davis-in-new-orleans/|title=New Orleans tears down Confederate monument|publisher=}}</ref> Two of them, the [[Battle of Liberty Place Monument]] and the [[Jefferson Davis Monument]], have been removed as of May 11, 2017.\n\n===Other===\nIn addition to the controversy regarding the Confederate flag's modern display, there have been considerations by institutions across the U.S. to remove the names of historic Confederate figures from schools, colleges, and streets. Campaigns to change the names were started in several cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2015/07/institutions_reconsider_confed.html|title=Institutions reconsider Confederate memorials after Charleston, S.C., church shooting|work=Mass Live|date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=July 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a national survey conducted in 2015, 57% of Americans opined that the Confederate flag represented Southern pride rather than racism. A previous poll in 2000 had a nearly identical result of 59%. However, poll results from only citizens living in the South yielded different results: 75% of whites described the flag as a symbol of pride, while 75% of blacks said the flag represented racism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/02/politics/confederate-flag-poll-racism-southern-pride/|title=Poll: Majority sees Confederate flag as Southern pride symbol, not racist|publisher=CNN|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Earl Holt political donations===\n\nEarl Holt, the leader of the [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], whose website Roof credited in his manifesto for shaping his views, gave more than $74,000<ref name=Swaine22June>{{cite news|title=Four Republican hopefuls return money after 'Dylann Roof manifesto's revelation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/22/scott-walker-republican-dylann-roof-manifesto|first1=Jon|last1=Swaine|first2=Jessica|last2=Glenza|work=The Guardian|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates and committees in recent years, including campaign donations to 2016 presidential candidates [[Ted Cruz]], [[Rick Santorum]], and [[Rand Paul]], who have all condemned Roof's racially based motives.<ref name=Alexander22June>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/republicans/11690736/Republican-presidential-candidates-received-donations-from-man-who-inspired-Charleston-shooter.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|first=Harriet|last=Alexander|title=Republican candidates accepted donations from man whose organisation inspired Dylann Roof}}</ref><ref name=Lichtblau22June>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/22/us/campaign-donations-linked-to-white-supremacist.html|title=White Supremacist Donated to 2016 G.O.P. Campaigns|date=June 22, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 22, 2015|first=Eric|last=Lichtblau}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-holt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/21/dylann-roof-manifesto-charlston-shootings-republicans|title=Leader of group cited in 'Dylann Roof manifesto' donated to top Republicans|work=The Guardian|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> Following the shooting, and after a journalist contacted the campaigns with details about the donor's background, a spokesman for the [[Ted Cruz 2016 presidential campaign|Ted Cruz campaign]] said he would return an $8,500 donation to Holt;<ref name=\"guardian-holt\"/> the campaign later said it would be donating $11,000 to the Mother Emanuel Hope Fund, to assist the victims' families.<ref name=Swaine22June/> The Rand Paul campaign said Holt's $2,250 donation would be given to the Fund,<ref name=Lichtblau22June/> and Rick Santorum said his $1,500 donation from Holt would be donated to the same charity.<ref name=Thompson22June>{{ cite news|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/rick-santorum-earl-holt-ccc|title=Santorum To Give Away Money Donated To Him By White Supremacist|first=Catherine|last=Thompson|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=Talking Points Memo}}</ref> Twelve other Republican office-holders also announced they would be returning or donating Holt's contributions.<ref name=Swaine22June/>\n\n===\"Terrorism\" terminology===\n{{See also|Definitions of terrorism}}\n\nWhile some media professionals, politicians and law enforcement officials referred to the attack as [[Homegrown terrorism|domestic terrorism]], others did not. This renewed a debate about the proper terminology to use when describing the shooting and other attacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/charleston-shooting-renews-debate-over-labelling-incidents-as-terrorism/article25045158/|title=Questions surround reluctance to label Charleston shooting as 'terrorism'|first=Affan|last=Chowdhry|work=The Globe and Mail|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, professor and [[terrorism]] expert Brian Phillips offered his definition of terrorism and said, the shooting was \"clearly a terrorist act\". He based this conclusion on a racist political motivation that \"seems likely\" and his \"intimidation of a wider audience\" criterion was met when \"...{{nbsp}}the shooter reportedly left one person alive to spread the message\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/monkey-cage/wp/2015/06/18/was-what-happened-in-charleston-terrorism/|title=Was what happened in Charleston terrorism?|first=Brian J.|last=Phillips|work=The Washington Post|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> An article by CNN National Security Analyst [[Peter Bergen]] and David Sterman on June 19 says, \"By any reasonable standard, this is terrorism, which is generally defined as an act of violence against civilians by individuals or organizations for political purposes. ... [D]eadly acts of terrorism by virulent racists and anti-government extremists have been more common in the United States than deadly acts of jihadist terrorism since [[September 11 attacks|9/11]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/opinions/bergen-charleston-attack-terrorism/index.html|title=Call it terrorism in Charleston|first=Peter|last=Bergen|first2=David|last2=Sterman|publisher=CNN|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome publications and their analyses of the event said these naming discrepancies reflect either forms of denial or outright [[racism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/06/18/was-the-charleston-massacre-an-act-of-terrorism/|title=Was the Charleston Massacre an Act of Terrorism?|first=Elias|last=Groll|work=Foreign Policy|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/06/29/terrorism-in-charleston|title=Terrorism in Charleston|first=Jelani|last=Cobb|work=The New Yorker|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/hate-crime-or-terrorism-debate-grows-about-terminology|title=Civil-rights experts have one word for church attack: It was terrorism|first=Rick|last=Gladstone|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> The journalist [[Glenn Greenwald]] wrote that {{quote|Almost immediately, news reports indicated there was 'no sign of terrorism'{{snd}}by which they meant: {{em|it does not appear that the shooter is Muslim}} ... other than the perpetrator\u2019s non-Muslim identity, the Charleston attack from the start had the indicia of what is commonly understood to be 'terrorism'. (emphasis in original)<ref>{{cite web |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |title=Refusal to Call Charleston Shootings 'Terrorism' Again Shows It\u2019s a Meaningless Propaganda Term |url=https://theintercept.com/2015/06/19/refusal-call-charleston-shootings-terrorism-shows-meaningless-propaganda-term/ |website=The Intercept |date=June 19, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nSpeaking on June 19 at a press conference in [[Baltimore]], [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI Director]] [[James Comey]] said, while his agency was investigating the shooting as a \"hate crime\", he did not consider it an \"act of terrorism\", citing the lack of political motivation for the suspect's actions.<ref name=Comey>{{cite web|url=http://www.13wham.com/news/features/nation-news/stories/fbi-director-charleston-shooting-not-terrorism-3408.shtml|title=FBI Director: Charleston shooting not terrorism|publisher=WHAM-TV|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150628135934/http://13wham.com/news/features/nation-news/stories/fbi-director-charleston-shooting-not-terrorism-3408.shtml|archivedate=June 28, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/06/22/white-house-won-t-back-fbi-chief-on-charleston-terror.html|title=White House Won't Back FBI Chief on Charleston 'Terror'|work=The Daily Beast|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015|first=Shane|last=Harris}}</ref> He said, \"Terrorism is act of violence done or threatened in order to try to influence a public body or citizenry, so it's more of a political act, and again, based on what I know, I don't see this as a political act. Doesn't make it any less horrific, but terrorism has a definition under federal law.\"<ref name=Comey/>\n\nHeidi Beirich, who leads the Intelligence Project of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), pointed to the discovery of a website attributed to Roof, which featured a manifesto and sixty photos as an example of why federal agents \"don't have themselves together on this issue\". The website began circulating on the Internet on June 20. Beirich said, \"The way they found the website was that someone ran a domain tool reverse search on this guy's name... It wasn't rocket science, but where were the feds?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/25/dylann-roof-domestic-extremists-terrorism-law-enforcement|title=Beyond Dylann Roof: inside the hunt for domestic extremists in the digital age|work=The Guardian|date=June 25, 2015|accessdate=July 4, 2015|first=Andrew|last=Gumbel}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, FBI spokesman Paul Bresson left open the possibility of terrorism charges, saying, \"Any eventual federal charges will be determined by the facts at the conclusion of the investigation, and are not influenced by how the investigation is initially opened.\" Ultimately, it is up to [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] prosecutors to decide what federal charges to bring. A spokesperson for Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] said the Department of Justice was investigating the shooting as both \"a hate crime and as an act of domestic terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/fbi-terrorism-charges-not-ruled-out-charleston-shooting|publisher=MSNBC|title=FBI: Terrorism charges not ruled out in Charleston shooting|last=Melber|first=Ari|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Imitators and subculture===\nThe infamy of Roof and the shooting has inspired imitators to plot similar attacks. Benjamin Thomas Samuel McDowell was arrested for unlawful firearm possession; he had been planning to shoot up the Temple Emanu-El synagogue in [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]], while Elizabeth Lecron and Vincent Armstrong were arrested for plotting to use explosives for \"upscale mass murder\"{{Clarification needed|reason=|date=July 2019}} in [[Toledo, Ohio]], having previously corresponded with Roof himself.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/06/us/south-carolina-arrest-benjamin-mcdowell-dylann-roof.html|title=Man in South Carolina Wanted to Copy Dylann Roof, Officials Say|last=Bidgood|first=Jess|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 22, 2019|date=February 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ndoh/pr/toledo-couple-indicted-conspiracy-use-explosives-and-firearms-kill-and-injure-others|title=Toledo couple indicted for conspiracy to use explosives and firearms to kill and injure others|work=United States Department of Justice|access-date=February 21, 2019|date=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heavy.com/news/2018/12/elizabeth-lecron|title=Elizabeth LeCron: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Santiago|first=Elyn|work=Heavy.com|access-date=June 16, 2019|date=December 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/monroe-area-man-with-arsenal-fantasized-about-killing-jews|title=Man with arsenal allegedly fantasized about killing Jews|last=Hutton|first=Caleb|work=HeraldNet.com|access-date=June 16, 2019|date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA violent [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] subculture has also emerged, known as the \"Bowl Gang\" or \"Bowl Patrol\", glorifying Roof and other far-right mass murderers.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Zack|last1=Beauchamp|accessdate=2019-08-17|title=An online subculture celebrating the Charleston church shooter appears to be inspiring copycat plots|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/2/7/18215634/dylann-roof-charleston-church-shooter-bowl-gang|date=7 February 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Paul|last1=Blumenthal|first2=Jessica|last2=Schulberg|first3=Luke|last3=O'Brien|accessdate=2019-08-17|title=Mass Shooters Have Been Exploiting The Internet For Years. New Zealand Took It To A New Level.|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/new-zealand-shooting-columbine-breivik-rodgers-roof-bowers_n_5c8c4b79e4b0d7f6b0f38e58|date=16 March 2019|website=HuffPost}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-08-17|title=Hardcore White Supremacists Elevate Dylann Roof to Cult Hero Status|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/hardcore-white-supremacists-elevate-dylann-roof-to-cult-hero-status|website=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Post\u2013civil rights era in African-American history|Post-civil rights era African-American history]]\n* [[Jeffersontown Kroger shooting]]\n* [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150620134455/http://lastrhodesian.com/ The Last Rhodesian] via [[Archive.org]] \u2013 Dylann Roof website\n* {{cite web|title=South Carolina State Senate Debate on the Confederate Flag|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?326742-1/south-carolina-state-senate-debate-confederate-flag|publisher=[[C-SPAN]]|date=June 23, 2015}}\n* [http://www.aaihs.org/resources/charlestonsyllabus/ #Charlestonsyllabus, a list of academic sources related to the shooting]\n* [http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1907500-un-ano-de-la-masacre-de-charleston-el-debate-que-no-fue Marcelo Pisarro, \"Un a\u00f1o de la masacre de Charleston: el debate que no fue\", La Naci\u00f3n, June 12, 2016.] (Spanish)\n{{Charleston, South Carolina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charleston, South Carolina shooting}}\n[[Category:2015 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:2015 in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:2015 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American history in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2015]]\n[[Category:Charleston church shooting| ]]\n[[Category:Crimes in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Massacres of Christians]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:History of Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:June 2015 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2015]]\n[[Category:Massacres in religious buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder trials]]\n[[Category:Murdered African-American people]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Civil Rights Era African-American history]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against African Americans]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in the United States in 2015]]\n[[Category:White supremacy in the United States]]\n[[Category:White nationalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Attacks on African-American churches]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n", "name_user": "TheFrenchTickler1031", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charleston_church_shooting"}
{"title_page": "Masters of the Universe (book)", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title      = \n| name              = Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics\n| image             = Masters of the Universe, Daniel Stedman Jones cover.png\n| image_size        = \n| border            = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| author            = Daniel Stedman Jones\n| audio_read_by     = \n| title_orig        = \n| orig_lang_code    = \n| title_working     = \n| translator        = \n| illustrator       = \n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = \n| language          = English\n| series            = \n| release_number    = \n| subject           = [[Neoliberalism]]\n| genre             = \n| set_in            = \n| publisher         = [[Princeton University Press]]\n| publisher2        = \n| pub_date          = 2012\n| english_pub_date  = \n| published         = \n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = 418\n| awards            = \n| isbn              = 978-0-691-15157-1\n| isbn_note         = \n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource        = \n| notes             = \n| exclude_cover     = \n| website           = \n}}\n\n'''''Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics''''' is a 2012 book by [[barrister]] Daniel Stedman Jones, in which the author traces the intellectual development and political rise of [[neoliberalism]] in the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. Originally a PhD thesis, the author adapted it into a book.<ref name=\"Financial-Times\">{{cite news |last1=Ben-Ami |first1=Daniel |title=Free market defined |url=https://www.ft.com/content/519636d2-4298-11e2-a3d2-00144feabdc0 |accessdate=30 July 2019 |publisher=Financial Times |date=13 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Prospect\">{{cite news |last1=Burns |first1=Jennifer |title=The Measure of All Things |url=https://prospect.org/article/measure-all-things |accessdate=3 August 2019 |publisher=The American Prospect |date=3 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Jones, neoliberalism began after the [[Great Depression]] as a movement of intellectuals committed to protecting [[liberalism|liberal]] values of [[individual liberty]] and [[limited government]], which they believed were threatened in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and the [[United States]] by expanding government. They aimed to construct a distinctly new liberalism (hence \"neoliberalism\") by charting a middle way between the [[laissez-faire]] economics of the pre-[[Great Depression|Depression]] era and the \"[[collectivism]]\" of [[New Deal]] liberalism and British [[social democracy]]. He argues that between the 1950s and 1970s this commitment evolved into one of greater conviction in the superiority of the [[free market]], such that by the 1980s neoliberal policy proposals centered almost entirely around [[market liberalization]]. Modern neoliberalism, according to Jones, is associated with [[economic liberalism]], [[monetarism]], and a staunch support of [[free market]] [[capitalism]], and advocates political policies of [[deregulation]], [[privatization]], and other market-based reforms.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|1}}\n\nJones structures the book around what he argues are the three phases of the history of neoliberalism. In the first, lasting from roughly 1920 until 1950, he details how early European neoliberal thinkers like [[Friedrich Hayek]], [[Ludwig von Mises]], and [[Karl Popper]], motivated by expanding government and later the rise of totalitarian regimes in Europe during [[World War II]], developed critiques of \"[[collectivism]]\", which to them included British [[social democracy]] and American [[New Deal]] liberalism. Particularly influential during this time was the formation of the [[Mont Pelerin Society]], which brought together intellectuals committed to the defense of [[liberalism]] and [[individualism]]. In the second phase, lasting from roughly 1950 until 1980, the locus of neoliberal thought moved to the [[United States]], where academics like [[Milton Friedman]] and [[George Stigler]] built upon the earlier neoliberal foundation by developing new academic and political arguments and introducing a range of neoliberal policy prescriptions. It was during this time that Jones contends neoliberal thought evolved from its more moderate early stance into a \"faith\" in the power and efficiency of markets. Jones argues that during this period a transatlantic network of intellectuals, businessmen, journalists, and [[think tanks]] arose to promote neoliberal ideology, slowly moving neoliberalism out of the political fringes and into the mainstream. The third phase, taking place after 1980, was the period of neoliberal political prominence. After a decade of [[stagflation]] in the United States and the United Kingdom, the neoliberal alternative to the [[Keynesian]] consensus that had dominated politics was adopted by politicians, finding particular influence with US president [[Ronald Reagan]] and British prime minister [[Margaret Thatcher]]. This era, Jones notes, was characterized by sweeping [[deregulation]], [[market liberalization]], and [[tax cut|tax reductions]].\n\n==Structure==\nThe book is divided into an introduction, seven chapters, and a conclusion.<ref name =\"Masters\">{{cite book|url=http://press.princeton.edu/titles/9827.html|title=Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics|last=Stedman Jones|first=Daniel|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0691151571|ref=harv}}</ref> \n* The introduction summarizes the history of [[neoliberalism]] and lays out the structure of the book. \n* Chapter one (\"The Postwar Settlement\") provides context for the rise of neoliberalism by briefly describing the development of [[embedded liberalism]] and [[Keynesianism]] after the [[Great Depression]]. \n* Chapter two (\"The 1940s: The Emergence of the Neoliberal Critique\") discusses the critiques of [[social democracy]] by the early neoliberals [[Karl Popper]], [[Ludwig von Mises]], and [[Friedrich Hayek]], and outlines the birth of the [[Mont Pelerin Society]].\n* Chapter three (\"The Rising Tide: Neoliberal Ideas in the Postwar Period) discusses the two [[Chicago school of economics|Chicago School]]s, the relation of [[Adam Smith]] to neoliberalism, the early ideas of [[Milton Friedman]], the [[ordoliberal]]s in [[West Germany]], and the economic theories of [[regulatory capture]], [[public choice]], and [[rational choice theory]]. \n* Chapter four (\"A Transatlantic Nework: Think Tanks and the Ideological Entrepreneurs\") discusses [[fusionism]] in the [[United States]], [[conservatism]] in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] during the 1950s, the growth of neoliberal organizations and [[think tanks]] from the 1950s through the 1970s, and the spread of neoliberal thought to journalists and politicians. \n* Chapter five (\"Keynesianism and the Emergence of Monetarism, 1945\u201371) discusses [[Keynesianism]], American economic policy in the 1960s, and the development of [[monetarism]] by Milton Friedman. \n* Chapter six (\"Economic Strategy: The Neoliberal Breakthrough, 1971-84\") discusses the [[stagflation]] of the 1970s in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]] and how it set the stage for the political rise of [[monetarism]], which ushered in further neoliberal reforms; it continues with a description of the neoliberal policies of British prime ministers [[James Callaghan]] and [[Margaret Thatcher]], [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Denis Healey]], US presidents [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Ronald Reagan]], and [[Chair of the Federal Reserve]] [[Paul Volcker]]. \n* Chapter seven (\"Neoliberalism Applied? The Transformation of Affordable Housing and Urban Policy in the United States and Britain, 1945\u20132000\") considers the effects of neoliberal policies on housing and [[urban policy]] in the United States and the United Kingdom.\n* The conclusion (\"The Legacy of Transatlantic Neoliberalism: Faith-Based Policy\") discusses the lasting effects of neoliberalism and lays out the author's belief in the need to return \"reason-based policymaking\" to political and economic debates.\n\n==Summary==\n{{Quote box|quote = \"Neoliberalism was a radical form of [[individualism]] that was first generated before World War II in reaction to [[Social liberalism|New Liberalism]], [[Progressivism]], the [[New Deal]], and the onset of [[Nazi]] and [[communist]] [[totalitarianism]]. Together, these strands were called '[[collectivism]]' by neoliberals.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|329}}|align = right |width = 20%}}\n\nThe author divides the history of neoliberalism into three phases.\n\nIn the first phase, lasting from 1920 to 1950, Jones contends that the crises of the [[Great Depression]] and [[Second World War]] produced two competing economic ideologies: [[Keynesianism]] and [[neoliberalism]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|22}} Keynesianism, developed by economist [[John Maynard Keynes]] and motivated by the widespread [[unemployment]] during the Great Depression, viewed government intervention in the economy as a means to alleviate [[economic downturn]]s and achieve [[full employment]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|24}} Neoliberalism, promoted by economists like [[Friedrich Hayek]], [[Milton Friedman]], and [[Ludwig von Mises]] and arising out of fears of [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]] regimes like the [[Nazi]]s, [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Soviet communists]], and [[Italian fascism|Italian fascists]], viewed increasing government intervention as a threat to [[economic freedom|economic]] and [[political freedom]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|22}} Early neoliberal thought, according to Jones, focused on defending [[liberalism]] and critiquing all forms of [[collectivism]], and in particular on critiquing [[New Deal]] liberalism and British [[social democracy]], which they believed posed a \"grave threat to the continued existence of Western civilization\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|23,136}}\n\nIn the second phase, lasting from 1950 to 1980, Jones notes that Keynesianism dominated political policy while neoliberal thought was mostly confined to universities and [[think tanks]]. However, it was during this time that neoliberal thought was refined and spread, creating a transatlantic network of intellectuals, businessmen, journalists, university departments and [[think tank]]s promoting neoliberal ideas.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|134}} The locus of neoliberal thought shifted from Europe to the United States, with the American intellectuals [[Milton Friedman]] and [[George Stigler]], as well as the larger [[Chicago school of economics]] they were a part of, becoming increasingly influential.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|85}} Neoliberal thought evolved: whereas the neoliberalism that had emerged during the [[interwar period|interwar years]] had been a \"nuanced response\" to war, depression and totalitarian regimes, late-twentieth-century neoliberalism became dominated by [[market liberalization]] and [[globalization]], and galvanized around a defense of the superiority of [[free market]]s to government [[Planned economy|economic planning]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|4\u20135}}\n\nThe third phase, lasting from 1980 onward (the book was released in 2012), is the period of neoliberal political hegemony. Jones suggests that the high [[inflation]] and low [[economic growth]] in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]] during the 1970s chipped away at the Keynesian political consensus, which seemed unable to address the decade's [[stagflation]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|215}} Jones argues that the transatlantic neoliberal network provided a compelling alternative economic ideology\u2014one that conveniently included [[monetarism]], an economic theory dealing with inflation.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|216}} Jones asserts that this led to the widespread political acceptance of neoliberal policies in the 1980s, which brought with it a greater acceptance of neoliberal ideology.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|270}} Jones maintains that, contrary to the opinion of some observers, the adoption of neoliberal policies was not an inevitability; they were not necessarily the \"right\" policies for the challenges of the era, but instead found political power through an \"unpredictable, patchy\" process that had \"luck and historical contingency\" as central players.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|333}} The left-leaning [[Carter administration]] and [[Callaghan government]] were the first to implement particular neoliberal policies,<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|269}} but neoliberalism would find its greatest impact with US president [[Ronald Reagan]] and British prime minister [[Margaret Thatcher]], who would each successfully advance agendas of [[deregulation]], [[tax cut]]s, and [[market liberalization]]. Jones argues that while these incremental policy changes did not require a wholesale acceptance of neoliberal philosophy, by the late 1980s that is exactly what had happened. Neoliberal ideas on the superiority of the market and [[individual liberty]] became widely accepted by politicians and academics, and Jones contends that this \"boundless belief in markets and deregulation\" ultimately led to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]].<ref name=\"Masters\"/>{{rp|6}}\n\n===First phase: Early history (1920\u20131950)===\nAccording to Jones, neoliberalism traces its earliest beginnings to the establishment of the [[Colloque Walter Lippmann]] in 1938. The [[Great Depression]] left the reputation of [[economic liberalism]] in tatters, and the scholars at the society sought to \"reconstruct a theory of liberalism\" because they believed that \"[[classical liberalism]] was under assault\". They called this reconstruction \"neoliberalism\" to signify that they were not simply accepting [[laissez-faire]] economics but were developing a new vision of economic liberalism. Ultimately, however, the ideas promoted at the colloquium did not take political hold, and at the outset of [[World War II]] the colloquium was largely forgotten.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\nThe destruction wrought by [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]] regimes during World War II would, however, energize a number of liberal thinkers in their opposition to [[collectivism]]. From this fear of collectivism emerged the early influential neoliberal texts critiquing [[social democracy]], and led to the formation of a new neoliberal organization by many of the same individuals present at the Colloque Walter Lippman: the [[Mont Pelerin Society]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|30\u201331}}\n\n====Mont Pelerin Society====\n[[File:Hoff i Mont Pelerin society.png|thumb|upright=1.15|[[Trygve J. B. Hoff]], editor of [[Farmand]], (left) and Austrian economist [[Ludwig von Mises]] (middle) at the Mont Pelerin Society in 1947]]\nJones outlines how, after the catastrophes of [[World War II]], [[Friedrich Hayek]] convened a group of intellectuals to combat the trend of increasing government intervention in the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]] and \"develop an organizational and intellectual strategy\" to \"defend the core tenets of...the freedom of the individual.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|30}} This group called itself the [[Mont Pelerin Society]], after the venue of its first meeting in Vevey, Switzerland.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ebenstein|first1=Alan|title=Friedrich Hayek: A Biography|date=2014|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781466886766|page=146}}</ref> The society set out to develop a neoliberal alternative to, on the one hand, the [[laissez-faire]] economic consensus that had collapsed with the [[Great Depression]] and, on the other, [[New Deal]] liberalism and British [[social democracy]], collectivist trends which they believed posed a threat to [[individual freedom]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|33}} A distinct neoliberal worldview, Jones contends, emerged \"on the foundations of the critique of New Deal liberalism and social democracy\" developed by the intellectuals of the Society.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|85}}\n\nJones finds three Mont Pelerin individuals particularly influential: [[Karl Popper]], [[Ludwig von Mises]], and [[Friedrich Hayek]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|33}} Popper, in his book ''[[The Open Society and its Enemies]]'', criticized thinkers from [[Plato]] to [[Karl Marx]] for valuing the collective over the individual and derided teleological [[historicism]] (a theory which holds that history unfolds inexorably according to universal laws) as a threat to [[individualism]]\u2014which he believed underpins [[Western civilization]]\u2014because it reduces the individual to \"a cog in the machine\" of history and empowers governments to engage in the sorts of \"Utopian engineering\" that has motivated communists, socialists, and [[Nazis]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|37\u201349}} Mises, in his book ''[[Bureaucracy (book)|Bureaucracy]]'', argued the superiority of the private market motivated by [[profit (economics)|profit]] over the bureaucratic management inherent in government.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|49\u201357}} Hayek, in his book ''[[The Road to Serfdom]]'', argued central planning was impossible because no individual or group could ever possess the requisite knowledge to direct the economic activity of millions of people.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|57\u201373}}\n\nThe early Mont Pelerin Society, Jones notes, had little effect on political policy. Instead, it acted as \"a siren call, a warning about the tragic possibilities of moving in the direction\" of greater collectivist government intervention \"which Western politics, economy, and society seemed to be moving.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|84}} Importantly, Jones argues it helped to \"create a transatlantic neoliberal network that would...combat the [[New Deal]] and social-democratic political establishments in Britain and the United States\", \"combat the forces of [[collectivism]]\", and refine neoliberal thought into a workable set of policies.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|32}}\n\n===Second phase: Emergence of a transatlantic neoliberal network (1950\u20131980)===\nJones outlines how a transatlantic network of neoliberal intellectuals, businessmen, journalists, university departments, and think tanks arose between 1950 and 1980 and, building on the foundations of the critiques of [[New Deal]] liberalism and [[social democracy]] of the early neoliberals, refined and popularized neoliberal ideas to the point that \"they eventually seemed the natural alternative to liberal or [[social democracy|social democratic]] policies\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|153}} This network would serve \"almost like a kind of Neoliberal International\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|218}} that would be highly influential in the later adoption of neoliberal policies by the governments of the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|134}} During this time, the locus of neoliberal thought shifted from Europe to America, with the American economist [[Milton Friedman]] becoming its most influential proponent\u2014its \"beating heart\", as Jones describes it.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|135}} Neoliberalism, according to Jones, evolved from an attempt to find a middle way between [[laissez-faire]] capitalism and collectivism into a \"faith in free markets\", often articulating \"individual liberty in apocalyptic terms as a struggle between free societies and [[communist]] [[totalitarianism]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|345,116}} Neoliberals of the era emphasized the need to recover \"lost truths\" from [[classical liberalism]], including the value of [[individual liberty]], the [[invisible hand]] of the free market, and the virtues of [[limited government]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|101}} By the 1960s, Jones contends, neoliberal thought had established a \"distinct and coherent identity\" centered around \"individual liberty, free markets, spontaneous order, the price mechanism, competition, consumerism, deregulation, and rational self-interest.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|132}} Additionally, during this period a body of policy prescriptions was injected into neoliberalism.\n\nJones points to an early essay by [[Milton Friedman]] entitled [https://miltonfriedman.hoover.org/objects/57816/neoliberalism-and-its-prospects?ctx=b8c0f32e-f5a4-4e53-ba3d-cf017b993579&idx=0 \"Neoliberalism and its Prospects\"] as a \"bridge\" between the first phase of neoliberal thought\u2014dominated by European conerns\u2014and the second phase, centered in the United States and concerned more with economic freedom and the superiority of markets.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|6}} Jones considers the essay a \"useful marker of the moment when neoliberalism became a self-conscious political and economic concept in the United States\", as it was one of the first instances in which an American writer claimed the neoliberal moniker.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|96}} In the essay Friedman makes a quintessentially first-phase argument for a \"new faith\" between [[collectivism]], which he believed leads to an over-mighty state, and [[laissez-faire]] economics, which he believed fostered the development of over-mighty individuals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Friedman |first1=Milton |title=Neo-Liberalism and its Prospects |url=https://miltonfriedman.hoover.org/objects/57816/neoliberalism-and-its-prospects?ctx=b8c0f32e-f5a4-4e53-ba3d-cf017b993579&idx=0 |accessdate=25 July 2019 |publisher=Farmand |date=17 February 1951}}</ref><ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|96}} However, the essay marked a \"symbolic cutting off point\" in neoliberal thought, signifying the point in time when neoliberalism began to shift away from the early \"middle way\" arguments to a more strident belief in free markets. Friedman himself advocated a level of government intervention in the essay which he would never again publicly support.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|97}}\n\n====Academic thought====\nAccording to Jones: \"After 1945, a distinct neoliberal worldview was built on the foundations of the critique of [[New Deal]] liberalism and [[social democracy]] synthesized in the writings of [[Ludwig von Mises]], [[Friedrich Hayek]], and [[Karl Popper]]...Its main tenets\u2014philosophical, political, and economic\u2014were worked out in detail by scholars such as [[Milton Friedman]], [[George Stigler]], [[Gary Becker]], [[James Buchanan]], and [[Gordon Tullock]], as well as Hayek and Mises.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|85}}\n\nJones asserts that the [[Chicago school of economics]], of which Friedman and Stigler were a part, was \"perhaps the most influential group in terms of the development of transatlantic neoliberal politics\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|89}} In the 1950s, 1960s, and 1970s Chicago economists published influential works arguing for [[free market]] policies and extending free market analyses into new regions (e.g. law and regulation). They painted a hostile portrait of [[trade unions]] and presented [[monopoly|monopolies]] as mostly benign.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|92\u201393}}\n\nThe theories of [[regulatory capture]], [[public choice theory]], and [[rational choice theory]] all became influential to neoliberal thought, according to Jones, because they connected the market to politics and the public sector, and helped the neoliberal view of free markets seep into mainstream public and political consciousness.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|126\u2013133}} The economist George Stigler argued that government regulatory bodies often become captured by private industry, so that these bodies act in the interests of private corporations rather than in the public's interest\u2014a notion known as \"regulatory capture\". James Buchanan and Gordon Tullock, considered the \"fathers of public choice theory\", emphasized the imperfections of political institutions and constitutional mechanisms, and argued voters have a tendency to vote their own interest rather than in the public interest.\n\n====Milton Friedman and monetarism====\n[[File:Portrait of Milton Friedman.jpg|thumb|[[Milton Friedman]]]]\n[[Milton Friedman]] became a leading figure of neoliberal thought and a prominent public intellectual in the 1950s. An American, Friedman was less influenced by the effects of [[World War II]] than by the subsequent [[Cold War]] between the [[United States]] and the [[Soviet Union]]. Jones argues that for neoliberals \"the Cold War necessitated the unambiguous advocacy of the superiority of the market\", and Friedman framed the \"war of ideas\" between [[socialism]] and free-market [[capitalism]] as a \"life-or-death struggle.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|101,120}}\n\nJones argues that \"Friedman's significant contribution to neoliberal thought was his connection of [[economic freedom]] with [[political freedom]]\", which he made in his popular book ''[[Capitalism and Freedom]]'' (which Jones describes as the \"American ''[[Road to Serfdom]]''\").<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|116}} Friedman argued that free markets and liberal democracy are inseparable, that the market guarantees basic political freedoms by ensuring that alternatives are always available (e.g. alternative employment options or alternative goods), guarantees equality by separating divorcing economic activities from reasons unrelated to an individual's [[productivity]], and protects dissent by separating economic power (i.e. the ability to make money) from political power (in other words, politicians cannot deprive an individual of employment if they express political dissent).<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|117,121}} Friedman consistently pointed out his view that \"increases in economic freedom have gone hand in hand with increases in political and civil freedom and have led to increased prosperity; competitive capitalism and freedom have become inseparable\", and pointed to countries like [[China]] under [[Deng Xiaoping]] and [[Chile]] to justify this.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|121}}\n\nJones notes that Friedman was a harsh critic of government intervention in the economy. A key point of ''[[Capitalism and Freedom]]'', according to Jones, was outlining government failure, including in the areas of railroad regulation, [[labor law]], [[monetary policy|monetary]] reform, agriculture, [[public housing]], [[social security]] legislation, [[foreign aid]], [[urban redevelopment]], and [[income tax]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|118}} In ''[[A Monetary History of the United States]]'', Friedman blamed the [[Great Depression]] on overly tight monetary policy by the [[Federal Reserve]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|202}} Friedman linked [[New Deal]] liberalism with [[socialism]] and [[communism]], while he considered his own ideas as a part of the [[classical liberalism|classical liberal]] family.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|119}}\n\nFriedman's development of the [[macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] theory [[monetarism]] was particularly influential to neoliberalism. Jones argues that the [[Keynesian]] consensus that had dominated political thought in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]] for decades had prioritized low [[unemployment]] over [[inflation]]. In contrast, by the 1950s neoliberal thinkers began to emphasize inflation.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|193}} Friedman ultimately developed [[monetarism]], a [[macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] theory dealing with [[inflation]] and the [[supply of money]] that suggested that the Keynesian view that government can achieve [[full employment]] at the cost of limited inflation was incorrect and would lead to higher inflation in the [[Long run and short run|long run]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|207}} Friedman argued that governments and central banks, rather than focusing on employment, should focus on ensuring a constant and predictable level of [[monetary inflation|monetary growth]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|207}} Jones describes monetarism as \"the most consistent, systematic, and significant alternative economic strategy to Keynesian demand management and fine-tuning\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|201}} This, according to Jones, primed neoliberal theory for political acceptance in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]], who would experience persistent [[stagflation]] during the 1970s. Jones sums it up as such: \"Friedman's monetarist analysis and market solutions grabbed people's attention as a ready-made and plausible alternative strategy [to Keynesianism] when the economy began to unravel [in the 1970s] under the weight of stagflation\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|212}}\n\n====Think tanks====\nIn Britain and the United States, the neoliberal right built a \"dazzling array of think tanks\", which became the preferred vehicle of neoliberal thinkers.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|336}} Notable among these, according to Jones, were the [[American Enterprise Institute]], the [[Foundation for Economic Education]], the [[Institute of Economic Affairs]], the [[Heritage Foundation]], the [[Cato Institute]], the [[Adam Smith Institute]], and a group of think tanks emanating out of the [[Atlas Network|Atlas Foundation]], including the [[Fraser Institute]], the Fisher Institute, and the [[Manhattan Institute]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|134}} These think tanks brought politicians and businesspeople into contact with neoliberal ideas and thinkers and raised the public profile of free-market policies. In particular, the Heritage Foundation had a significant influence on US president [[Ronald Reagan]]\u2014claiming on its website that nearly two-thirds of the proposals they suggested to him in their policy guide ''[[Mandate for Leadership]]'' were implemented<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blasko |first1=Andrew |title=REAGAN AND HERITAGE: A Unique Partnership |url=https://www.heritage.org/conservatism/commentary/reagan-and-heritage-unique-partnership |website=The Heritage Foundation |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\u2014while the Adam Smith Institute had appreciable sway with the [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher government]]. Jones notes that many of these institutes were funded by wealthy businessmen, such as [[Charles Koch]] and [[Joseph Coors]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|163\u2013164}}\n\n====Relation to conservatism====\nFree market economics has been associated with the [[political right]], but Jones emphasizes that it is \"but one branch\" of it.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|138}} In the United States, he argues that the right had a number of often-competing interests (principally [[Traditionalist conservatism|traditionalism]], [[anticommunism]], and [[neoliberalism]]), but the \"distinctive feature of the conservative revival in the 1950s and 1960s was the ability of its disparate elements to unite under the banners of [[anticommunism]] and [[states' rights]]\"\u2014a union that became known as \"[[fusionism]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|140}} This union, which Jones largely credits [[William F. Buckley Jr.]] for achieving, led to the growth of a conservative establishment that would, after decades of decline, rival its liberal opponents. This \"pave[d] the way for the later electoral successes of Ronald Reagan,\" which would usher in neoliberal policies.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|146}}\n\n===Third phase: Policy implementation (1980 onward)===\n{{Quote box|quote = \"The demise of the postwar economic settlement had been hastened by a series of catastrophic events: the [[Vietnam War]], the first [[1973 oil crisis|oil shock of 1973]], and the near collapse of [[industrial relations]] in Britain. The Keynes-inspired policies that governments had relied on to deliver a golden age of prosperity and rising incomes for a generation after 1945 seemed exhausted. The collapse of the [[Bretton Woods system|Bretton Woods international monetary system]] in 1971 indicated the end of the experiment with [[fixed exchange rates]]. The assumption that there was a relatively simple and manipulable trade-off between [[inflation]] and [[employment]], the famous [[Phillips Curve]]...proved to be a dangerous illusion...In both Britain and the United States, the appearance of [[stagflation]]...meant that governments felt forced to change course.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|1\u20132}}|align = right |width = 20%}}\nJones notes that there were two major issues facing the United States and the United Kingdom at the end of the 1960s: the instability of the [[Bretton Woods system|Bretton Woods international monetary system]] and high [[inflation]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|219\u2013220}} As Jones describes it: \"the late 1960s and early 1970s brought a succession of economic shocks that undermined the postwar international monetary system and pushed the world economy into stormy waters. The final stage in the shift in economic strategy in Britain and the United States, the reason neoliberal ideas found a receptive audience, was the force of these events.\" The proposed neoliberal solutions of [[monetarism]], [[deregulation]], and [[trade union]] reform, as well as the wealth of neoliberal arguments against the prevailing Keynesian demand management, provided a \"powerfully compelling logic\", and neoliberal policies were soon adopted by British and American politicians.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|15}} Yet these economic solutions acted as mere \"Trojan horses for a more polemical neoliberal faith in free markets\", which would come to dominate politics in the United States and the United Kingdom.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|13}}\n[[Image:US Historical Inflation.svg|thumb|Rate of inflation in the United States (1914-2009)|left]]\n\nNeoliberal policies, according to Jones, were first introduced in the United States by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] president [[Jimmy Carter]] and in the United Kingdom by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] prime minister [[James Callaghan]]. However, their approaches were examples of \"governments of the left who accept[ed] the logic of the technical insights of [[Milton Friedman|Friedman]] and [[George Stigler|Stigler]] in terms of macroeconomic strategy or deregulation without also importing their neoliberal philosophies\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|253}} It would be their successors, [[Ronald Reagan]] in the United States and [[Margaret Thatcher]] in the United Kingdom, who Jones argues embodied the neoliberal belief in the \"supremacy of the free market\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|268}} They would also have the greatest impact on neoliberal policy implementation, successfully advancing agendas of deregulation, lower taxes, and market liberalization.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|270}} He emphasizes the importance of the transatlantic neoliberal network on Reagan and Thatcher, noting that \"many of their most important advisers, government colleagues, and supporters were drawn from the transatlantic neoliberal network\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|268}}\n\n====Jimmy Carter and Paul Volcker====\nJones argues that the implementation of neoliberal policy in the United States began with US president [[Jimmy Carter]], who Jones notes had been strongly influenced by neoliberal economist [[George Stigler]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|249}} During the [[presidency of Jimmy Carter|Carter presidency]] (1977\u20131981) the airline, trucking, and financial industries were deregulated.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|249}}\n\nJones suggests that \"perhaps the single most important economic policy decision made by Carter was his appointment of [[Paul Volcker]] in August 1979 to replace [[G. William Miller|[George William] Miller]] as [[chairman of the Federal Reserve]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|250}} Volcker aggressively and successfully targeted [[inflation]] by raising interest rates,<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Neill |first1=William L. |title=The Jimmy Carter Administration |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/United-States/The-Gerald-R-Ford-administration#ref613295 |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> bringing inflation down from a high point of nearly 15% in 1980 to 3%.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|252}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Inflation, consumer prices (annual %) |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/FP.CPI.TOTL.ZG?end=2018&locations=US&start=1960 |website=World Bank |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Ronald Reagan====\n[[File:Official Portrait of President Reagan 1981.jpg|thumb|Ronald Reagan presidential portrait]]\nIn 1981, [[Ronald Reagan]] became [[president of the United States]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronald Reagan |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/presidents/ronald-reagan/ |website=The White House |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref> Jones argues that the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] \"followed neoliberal principles influenced particularly by the ideas of [[Friedrich Hayek]], [[Milton Friedman]], [[George Stigler]], and [[Pat Buchanan]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}} This can be seen in the four policy proposals Jones argues Reagan prioritized:<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}} \n# Increased [[deregulation]] and [[market liberalization]]\n# Tighter control of the [[money supply]]\n# [[Tax cuts]]\n# Cuts to [[public spending]]\n\nThe administration lifted economic controls on oil, busted the [[Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization (1968)|air traffic controller's union]] and fired all the striking workers (in the United States most air traffic controllers are employed by the federal government<ref>{{cite web |title=Occupational Outlook Handbook, Air Traffic Controllers |url=https://www.bls.gov/ooh/transportation-and-material-moving/air-traffic-controllers.htm#tab-3 |website=Bureau of Labor Statistics, U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>), and implemented [[Reagan tax cuts|significant tax cuts]], including reducing the top marginal tax rate from 70% to 28%.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}}<ref>{{cite act |date=22 October 1986 |legislature=United States Congress |title=Title I\u2014Individual Income Tax Provisions |url=http://legisworks.org/sal/100/stats/STATUTE-100-Pg2096.pdf |language=}}</ref> Jones argues that Reagan's tax cuts were motivated by arguments including the philosophy of [[limited government]] promoted by Friedman and other neoliberals; the idea developed by economist [[Arthur Laffer]] that [[tax revenue]] would increase as [[tax rates]] dropped because, as Jones summarized Laffer's argument, \"more people would pay taxes and fewer would attempt tax avoidance\"; and the belief that lower taxes lead to increased investment by the wealthy, which boosts [[economic growth]] and thereby benefits all members of society (a belief that would become known as [[trickle-down economics]]).<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}}\n\n====Margaret Thatcher====\n[[Margaret Thatcher]] became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] in 1979,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Hugo |title=Margaret Thatcher |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Margaret-Thatcher#ref214939 |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref> ushering in a broad range of [[Supply-side economics|supply-side]] reforms and [[monetarism|monetarist]] macroeconomic policies.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}} Jones contends that \"the key early battle for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government had been driving through a tough slew of measures to bring the deficit under control and create the conditions for economic recovery in the famous [[1981 United Kingdom budget|budget of 1981]].\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|260\u2013261}} The government combined budget cuts with a \"reorientation of the tax system to provide greater incentives for entrepreneurship.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|261}}\n\nMonetarist policy had first been introduced by the [[Labour government, 1974\u20131979|Callaghan's Labour government]], which had introduced monetary targets and cash limits.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|242}} Monetarist policy was continued under the Thatcher government. Jones places \"the major differences, and the real departure in economic terms, between the Callaghan government and the Conservatives lay in their radicalization of microeconomic policy through various market-based supply-side reforms and their importation of market mechanisms into public service provision.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|262}}\n\n====Effects====\n{{Quote box|quote = \"Neoliberalism transformed British, American, and global politics. At the dawn of the twenty-first century, the triumph of the free market was almost universally accepted by mainstream politicians, public officials, and civil servants. More important, the distinctive neoliberal brand of free market individualism had prevailed over alternative forms of managed market-based capitalism.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|329}}|align = right |width = 20%}}\nJones believes that the \"neoliberal contribution to the political changes of the last third of the twentieth century in Britain and the United States have been massive\", and includes not only the considerable reforms that Reagan and Thatcher implemented but also the effects neoliberalism had on introducing \"a new economic policy framework...[that] governed the policies and ambitions of [[Bill Clinton]], [[Tony Blair]], [[Gordon Brown]], and [[Barack Obama]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|271}} Neoliberalism resulted in a \"broad breakdown of the characteristic mid-twentieth century belief in the efficacy and moral superiority of government and collective action\" in favor of a belief in the efficacy of markets.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|335}} Additionally, he notes that neoliberalism was extended into international development and trade through the [[structural adjustment]] policies of the [[International Monetary Fund]], the [[World Bank]], and the [[World Trade Organization]], which were dominated by neoliberal economists in the late 20th century.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|332}} He argues that this ultimately had mixed effects:\n<blockquote>\n\"Some of the most powerful insights of [neoliberal] thinkers did help to address pressing social and economic issues by increasing homeownership or stabilizing persistently high [[inflation]]. But such successes were not so numerous as to make the effect of transatlantic neoliberal politics anything better than ambivalent...neoliberal policies tended to affect the most vulnerable members of society in the harshest ways.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|338}}\n\nDuring the last two decades of the [20th] century, [[economic inequality|inequality]] (the gap between rich and poor), [[poverty]], and [[homelessness]] all increased. [[Unemployment]] seemingly disappeared as a major problem in the immediate postwar years but returned with a vengeance after the 1970s. Inflation...[was] cowed...by the uncompromising policies of [[central bankers]] and pliant politicians in the early 1980s. In Britain, unemployment and inflation returned during another deep [[recession]] by the time Thatcher was forced from office in October 1990.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|330}}\n</blockquote>\n\nFurthermore, Jones believes that \"the most important reason for the [[2008 financial crisis|[2008] financial crisis]] was the direct result of neoliberal policies\" of financial deregulation.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|340}} He argues the neoliberal \"faith in markets had become divorced from reality\", with crisis-level effects.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|330}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe book was a finalist for the Western Social Science Association's 2014 Presidents\u2019 Book Award and shortlisted for the 2012 [[Gladstone Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters of the Universe Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics |url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/9827.html |website=Princeton University Press |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref> It has received mixed reviews.\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' praised the book as a \"bold biography of a great idea\", describing it as a \"novel and comprehensive history of neoliberalism\" that, while \"a little thin on character sketches and economics\", is a \"strong work\" by a \"fair and nuanced writer\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Birth of Neoliberalism |url=https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2012/10/13/new-brooms |accessdate=24 July 2019 |publisher=The Economist |date=13 October 2012}}</ref> James McAuley, writing in the magazine [[Prospect (magazine)|''Prospect'']], claims that Jones \"has produced an ideal kind of intellectual history\u2014an investigation that shows that the reigning free market paradigm was not the inevitable end of progressive policy developments...it was instead a programme that was actively promoted by a network of intellectuals and institutions, and it depended on external political circumstances for its success.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=McAuley |first1=James |title=The shock of the neoliberal |url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/arts-and-books/neoliberalism-reagan-thatcher-hayek-friedman |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Prospect |date=30 January 2013}}</ref> [[Alejandro Chafuen]], former president of the [[Atlas Economic Research Foundation]] and member of the [[Mont Pelerin Society]], writes in ''[[Forbes]]'' that he appreciates that the author's \"lengthy exposition of the views shared by these outstanding economists (Friedman, Hayek, and Mises) might encourage many to pay attention to their works.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/realspin/2013/01/16/think-tanks-are-they-the-masters-of-the-universe/#413dc4c5264a|title=Think Tanks: Are They The Masters Of The Universe?|last1=Chafuen|first1=Alejandro|date=16 January 2013|accessdate=3 August 2019|publisher=Forbes}}</ref> Jennifer Burns, writing in ''[[The American Prospect]]'' states that \"Jones\u2019s provocative if disconcerting argument deserves wide consideration. So does ''Masters of the Universe'', which does much to help explain the aftermath of 2008 and the ways in which political responses that might have defined another era seem unthinkable in ours.\"<ref name=\"Prospect\"/> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called it \"a cerebral, pertinent exegesis on the thinking behind the rise of the New Right\", though notes it is \"too scholarly for most general readers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/daniel-stedman-jones/masters-universe/|title=Masters of the Universe|date=14 July 2012|accessdate=24 July 2019|publisher=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref> Glenn C. Altschuler, writing in the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', states that the author \"draws on extensive archival research and interviews with politicians, policy-makers and intellectuals to provide a lucid, richly detailed examination of the evolution of the free-market ideology since the end of World War II.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/book-reviews/2012/10/28/Masters-of-the-Universe-the-failures-of-conservative-economic-theory-and-the-practice-is-worse/stories/201210280215|title='Masters of the Universe': the failures of economic theory (and the practice is worse)|last1=Altshuler|first1=Glenn C.|date=27 October 2012|accessdate=3 August 2019|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette}}</ref>\n\nScott Sumner, writing in the magazine [[Reason (magazine)|''Reason'']], calls the book \"a balanced and informative study of neoliberal thinkers\", however he believes that Jones, in his criticism of neoliberalism as prone to [[market fundamentalism]], \"misses the bigger picture for three reasons: He underestimates the extent to which neoliberalism was built on impressive economic research, he overstates the extent to which neoliberalism became associated with modern conservatism, and he overstates the neoliberals' opposition to government\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sumner |first1=Scott |title=The Neoliberal Revolution |url=https://reason.com/2013/01/22/the-neoliberal-revolution/ |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Reason |date=February 2013}}</ref> Daniel Ben-Ami, writing in ''[[Financial Times]]'', praised the book as \"clearly written and relevant to a wide audience\", noting it \"incorporates a wealth of primary material\", although he states Jones \"fails to capture fully the failures or successes of neoliberal thought\".<ref name=\"Financial-Times\" /> Edward Nik-Khah, writing for the [[Economic History Association]], calls it an \"accessible introduction\" to the intellectual history of neoliberalism, criticizing it only for \"some of Jones\u2019s framing choices\" which \"get in the way of understanding [the] complex history [of neoliberalism].\"<ref name=\"Edward\">{{cite news |last1=Edward |first1=Nik-Khah |title=Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics |url=https://eh.net/book_reviews/masters-of-the-universe-hayek-friedman-and-the-birth-of-neoliberal-politics/ |accessdate=24 July 2019 |publisher=Economic History Association |date=November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Kelly (professor)|Paul Kelly]], writing for the ''[[London School of Economics]] Review of Books'', criticizes the book as being \"overambitious\", lamenting that \"the connections between the various [neoliberal] thinkers are ambiguous, fortuitous or at best under explained\" and stating that the book \"sadly fails to deliver on its promise\" of delivering \"an analysis and critique of the dominant language of political economy of the last four decades \u2013 neoliberalism\"; he also criticizes the book for \"assuming a polemical concept (neoliberalism) as an ideological unity\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Paul |title=Book Review: Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics |url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/politicsandpolicy/book-review-masters-of-the-universe-hayek-friedman-and-the-birth-of-neoliberal-politics/ |accessdate=30 July 2019 |publisher=London School of Economics Review of Books |date=4 November 2012}}</ref> [[Kenneth Minogue]], writing for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', claims that while the book \"has intelligent things to say\" its \"historical virtues are compromised by more adjectival attitudinizing than a chronicler of history should allow himself\"; for instance, \"free-market ideas are characterized as 'aggressive,' 'relentless' and 'uncritical,' culminating in the description of market enthusiasm as a 'holy grail' and the use of a variety of religious metaphors designed to suggest that it is irrational.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minogue |first1=Kenneth |title=The Death and Life of Liberal Economics |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443995604578002432460754000 |accessdate=24 July 2019 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=26 October 2012}}</ref> Greg Kaza, writing in the ''[[Quarterly Journal of Austrian Economics]]'' published by [[The Mises Institute]], criticized the book for neglecting to include information from the archives of [[Ludwig von Mises]] and for selective reporting on the 1960s-era U.S. civil rights movement.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kaza |first1=Greg |title=Review of Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics by Daniel Stedman Jones |journal=Quarterly Journal of Austrian Economics |date=2 February 2015 |volume=17 |issue=4 |pages=543\u2013549 |url=https://mises.org/library/review-masters-universe-hayek-friedman-and-birth-neoliberal-politics-daniel-stedman-jones |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe title has been criticized by Edward Nik-Khah, who notes that the book does not explicitly state who, exactly, the \"masters of the universe\" are.<ref name=\"Edward\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* For further analysis of the intellectual development of neoliberalism: {{cite book |last1=Burgin |first1=Angus |title=The Great Persuasion: Reinventing Free Markets since the Great Depression |date=2015 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0674033184}}\n* For a survey of early neoliberal thought by a number of academics: {{cite book |editor1-last=Mirowski |editor1-first=Philip |editor2-last=Plehwe |editor2-first=Dieter |title=The Road from Mont P\u00e8lerin: The Making of the Neoliberal Thought Collective |date=2009 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-03318-4}}\n* For a short summary of neoliberalism: {{cite book |last1=Steger |first1=Manfred B. |last2=Roy |first2=Ravi K. |title=Neoliberalism: A Very Short Introduction |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199560516}}\n* For a positive analysis of neoliberalism:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shenk |first1=Timothy |title=The Long Shadow of Mont Pelerin |url=https://www.dissentmagazine.org/article/the-long-shadow-of-mont-pelerin |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Dissent |date=Fall 2013}}</ref> Yergin, Daniel; Stanislaw, Joseph (1998). [[The Commanding Heights|''The Commanding Heights: The Battle for the World Economy'']]. Free Press. {{ISBN|978-0684835693}}.\n* For a [[Neo-Marxism|neo-Marxist]] critique and a description of the spread of neoliberalism:<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ritzer |first1=Georgy |title=A Brief History of Neoliberalism |journal=American Journal of Sociology |date=July 2007 |volume=113 |issue=1 |url=https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/520901?journalCode=ajs |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref> {{cite book |last1=Harvey |first1=David |title=A Brief History of Neoliberalism |date=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0199283279}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neoliberalism]]\n[[Category:2012 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books in political philosophy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title      = \n| name              = Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics\n| image             = Masters of the Universe, Daniel Stedman Jones cover.png\n| image_size        = \n| border            = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| author            = Daniel Stedman Jones\n| audio_read_by     = \n| title_orig        = \n| orig_lang_code    = \n| title_working     = \n| translator        = \n| illustrator       = \n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = \n| language          = English\n| series            = \n| release_number    = \n| subject           = [[Neoliberalism]]\n| genre             = \n| set_in            = \n| publisher         = [[Princeton University Press]]\n| publisher2        = \n| pub_date          = 2012\n| english_pub_date  = \n| published         = \n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = 418\n| awards            = \n| isbn              = 978-0-691-15157-1\n| isbn_note         = \n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource        = \n| notes             = \n| exclude_cover     = \n| website           = \n}}\n\n'''''Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics''''' is a 2012 book by [[barrister]] Daniel Stedman Jones, in which the author traces the intellectual development and political rise of [[neoliberalism]] in the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. Originally a PhD thesis, the author adapted it into a book.<ref name=\"Financial-Times\">{{cite news |last1=Ben-Ami |first1=Daniel |title=Free market defined |url=https://www.ft.com/content/519636d2-4298-11e2-a3d2-00144feabdc0 |accessdate=30 July 2019 |publisher=Financial Times |date=13 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Prospect\">{{cite news |last1=Burns |first1=Jennifer |title=The Measure of All Things |url=https://prospect.org/article/measure-all-things |accessdate=3 August 2019 |publisher=The American Prospect |date=3 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Jones, neoliberalism began after the [[Great Depression]] as a movement of intellectuals committed to protecting [[liberalism|liberal]] values of [[individual liberty]] and [[limited government]], which they believed were threatened in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and the [[United States]] by expanding government. They aimed to construct a distinctly new liberalism (hence \"neoliberalism\") by charting a middle way between the [[laissez-faire]] economics of the pre-[[Great Depression|Depression]] era and the \"[[collectivism]]\" of [[New Deal]] liberalism and British [[social democracy]]. He argues that between the 1950s and 1970s this commitment evolved into one of greater conviction in the superiority of the [[free market]], such that by the 1980s neoliberal policy proposals centered almost entirely around [[market liberalization]]. Modern neoliberalism, according to Jones, is associated with [[economic liberalism]], [[monetarism]], and a staunch support of [[free market]] [[capitalism]], and advocates political policies of [[deregulation]], [[privatization]], and other market-based reforms.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|1}}\n\nJones structures the book around what he argues are the three phases of the history of neoliberalism. In the first, lasting from roughly 1920 until 1950, he details how early European neoliberal thinkers like [[Friedrich Hayek]], [[Ludwig von Mises]], and [[Karl Popper]], motivated by expanding government and later the rise of totalitarian regimes in Europe during [[World War II]], developed critiques of \"[[collectivism]]\", which to them included British [[social democracy]] and American [[New Deal]] liberalism. Particularly influential during this time was the formation of the [[Mont Pelerin Society]], which brought together intellectuals committed to the defense of [[liberalism]] and [[individualism]]. In the second phase, lasting from roughly 1950 until 1980, the locus of neoliberal thought moved to the [[United States]], where academics like [[Milton Friedman]] and [[George Stigler]] built upon the earlier neoliberal foundation by developing new academic and political arguments and introducing a range of neoliberal policy prescriptions. It was during this time that Jones contends neoliberal thought evolved from its more moderate early stance into a \"faith\" in the power and efficiency of markets. Jones argues that during this period a transatlantic network of intellectuals, businessmen, journalists, and [[think tanks]] arose to promote neoliberal ideology, slowly moving neoliberalism out of the political fringes and into the mainstream. The third phase, taking place after 1980, was the period of neoliberal political prominence. After a decade of [[stagflation]] in the United States and the United Kingdom, the neoliberal alternative to the [[Keynesian]] consensus that had dominated politics was adopted by politicians, finding particular influence with US president [[Ronald Reagan]] and British prime minister [[Margaret Thatcher]]. This era, Jones notes, was characterized by sweeping [[deregulation]], [[market liberalization]], and [[tax cut|tax reductions]].\n\n==Structure==\nThe book is divided into an introduction, seven chapters, and a conclusion.<ref name =\"Masters\">{{cite book|url=http://press.princeton.edu/titles/9827.html|title=Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics|last=Stedman Jones|first=Daniel|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0691151571|ref=harv}}</ref> \n* The introduction summarizes the history of [[neoliberalism]] and lays out the structure of the book. \n* Chapter one (\"The Postwar Settlement\") provides context for the rise of neoliberalism by briefly describing the development of [[embedded liberalism]] and [[Keynesianism]] after the [[Great Depression]]. \n* Chapter two (\"The 1940s: The Emergence of the Neoliberal Critique\") discusses the critiques of [[social democracy]] by the early neoliberals [[Karl Popper]], [[Ludwig von Mises]], and [[Friedrich Hayek]], and outlines the birth of the [[Mont Pelerin Society]].\n* Chapter three (\"The Rising Tide: Neoliberal Ideas in the Postwar Period) discusses the two [[Chicago school of economics|Chicago School]]s, the relation of [[Adam Smith]] to neoliberalism, the early ideas of [[Milton Friedman]], the [[ordoliberal]]s in [[West Germany]], and the economic theories of [[regulatory capture]], [[public choice]], and [[rational choice theory]]. \n* Chapter four (\"A Transatlantic Nework: Think Tanks and the Ideological Entrepreneurs\") discusses [[fusionism]] in the [[United States]], [[conservatism]] in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] during the 1950s, the growth of neoliberal organizations and [[think tanks]] from the 1950s through the 1970s, and the spread of neoliberal thought to journalists and politicians. \n* Chapter five (\"Keynesianism and the Emergence of Monetarism, 1945\u201371) discusses [[Keynesianism]], American economic policy in the 1960s, and the development of [[monetarism]] by Milton Friedman. \n* Chapter six (\"Economic Strategy: The Neoliberal Breakthrough, 1971-84\") discusses the [[stagflation]] of the 1970s in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]] and how it set the stage for the political rise of [[monetarism]], which ushered in further neoliberal reforms; it continues with a description of the neoliberal policies of British prime ministers [[James Callaghan]] and [[Margaret Thatcher]], [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Denis Healey]], US presidents [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Ronald Reagan]], and [[Chair of the Federal Reserve]] [[Paul Volcker]]. \n* Chapter seven (\"Neoliberalism Applied? The Transformation of Affordable Housing and Urban Policy in the United States and Britain, 1945\u20132000\") considers the effects of neoliberal policies on housing and [[urban policy]] in the United States and the United Kingdom.\n* The conclusion (\"The Legacy of Transatlantic Neoliberalism: Faith-Based Policy\") discusses the lasting effects of neoliberalism and lays out the author's belief in the need to return \"reason-based policymaking\" to political and economic debates.\n\n==Summary==\n{{Quote box|quote = \"Neoliberalism was a radical form of [[individualism]] that was first generated before World War II in reaction to [[Social liberalism|New Liberalism]], [[Progressivism]], the [[New Deal]], and the onset of [[Nazi]] and [[communist]] [[totalitarianism]]. Together, these strands were called '[[collectivism]]' by neoliberals.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|329}}|align = right |width = 20%}}\n\nThe author divides the history of neoliberalism into three phases.\n\nIn the first phase, lasting from 1920 to 1950, Jones contends that the crises of the [[Great Depression]] and [[Second World War]] produced two competing economic ideologies: [[Keynesianism]] and [[neoliberalism]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|22}} Keynesianism, developed by economist [[John Maynard Keynes]] and motivated by the widespread [[unemployment]] during the Great Depression, viewed government intervention in the economy as a means to alleviate [[economic downturn]]s and achieve [[full employment]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|24}} Neoliberalism, promoted by economists like [[Friedrich Hayek]], [[Milton Friedman]], and [[Ludwig von Mises]] and arising out of fears of [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]] regimes like the [[Nazi]]s, [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Soviet communists]], and [[Italian fascism|Italian fascists]], viewed increasing government intervention as a threat to [[economic freedom|economic]] and [[political freedom]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|22}} Early neoliberal thought, according to Jones, focused on defending [[liberalism]] and critiquing all forms of [[collectivism]], and in particular on critiquing [[New Deal]] liberalism and British [[social democracy]], which they believed posed a \"grave threat to the continued existence of Western civilization\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|23,136}}\n\nIn the second phase, lasting from 1950 to 1980, Jones notes that Keynesianism dominated political policy while neoliberal thought was mostly confined to universities and [[think tanks]]. However, it was during this time that neoliberal thought was refined and spread, creating a transatlantic network of intellectuals, businessmen, journalists, university departments and [[think tank]]s promoting neoliberal ideas.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|134}} The locus of neoliberal thought shifted from Europe to the United States, with the American intellectuals [[Milton Friedman]] and [[George Stigler]], as well as the larger [[Chicago school of economics]] they were a part of, becoming increasingly influential.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|85}} Neoliberal thought evolved: whereas the neoliberalism that had emerged during the [[interwar period|interwar years]] had been a \"nuanced response\" to war, depression and totalitarian regimes, late-twentieth-century neoliberalism became dominated by [[market liberalization]] and [[globalization]], and galvanized around a defense of the superiority of [[free market]]s to government [[Planned economy|economic planning]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|4\u20135}}\n\nThe third phase, lasting from 1980 onward (the book was released in 2012), is the period of neoliberal political hegemony. Jones suggests that the high [[inflation]] and low [[economic growth]] in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]] during the 1970s chipped away at the Keynesian political consensus, which seemed unable to address the decade's [[stagflation]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|215}} Jones argues that the transatlantic neoliberal network provided a compelling alternative economic ideology\u2014one that conveniently included [[monetarism]], an economic theory dealing with inflation.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|216}} Jones asserts that this led to the widespread political acceptance of neoliberal policies in the 1980s, which brought with it a greater acceptance of neoliberal ideology.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|270}} Jones maintains that, contrary to the opinion of some observers, the adoption of neoliberal policies was not an inevitability; they were not necessarily the \"right\" policies for the challenges of the era, but instead found political power through an \"unpredictable, patchy\" process that had \"luck and historical contingency\" as central players.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|333}} The left-leaning [[Carter administration]] and [[Callaghan government]] were the first to implement particular neoliberal policies,<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|269}} but neoliberalism would find its greatest impact with US president [[Ronald Reagan]] and British prime minister [[Margaret Thatcher]], who would each successfully advance agendas of [[deregulation]], [[tax cut]]s, and [[market liberalization]]. Jones argues that while these incremental policy changes did not require a wholesale acceptance of neoliberal philosophy, by the late 1980s that is exactly what had happened. Neoliberal ideas on the superiority of the market and [[individual liberty]] became widely accepted by politicians and academics, and Jones contends that this \"boundless belief in markets and deregulation\" ultimately led to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]].<ref name=\"Masters\"/>{{rp|6}}\n\n===First phase: Early history (1920\u20131950)===\nAccording to Jones, neoliberalism traces its earliest beginnings to the establishment of the [[Colloque Walter Lippmann]] in 1938. The [[Great Depression]] left the reputation of [[economic liberalism]] in tatters, and the scholars at the society sought to \"reconstruct a theory of liberalism\" because they believed that \"[[classical liberalism]] was under assault\". They called this reconstruction \"neoliberalism\" to signify that they were not simply accepting [[laissez-faire]] economics but were developing a new vision of economic liberalism. Ultimately, however, the ideas promoted at the colloquium did not take political hold, and at the outset of [[World War II]] the colloquium was largely forgotten.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\nThe destruction wrought by [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]] regimes during World War II would, however, energize a number of liberal thinkers in their opposition to [[collectivism]]. From this fear of collectivism emerged the early influential neoliberal texts critiquing [[social democracy]], and led to the formation of a new neoliberal organization by many of the same individuals present at the Colloque Walter Lippman: the [[Mont Pelerin Society]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|30\u201331}}\n\n====Mont Pelerin Society====\n[[File:Hoff i Mont Pelerin society.png|thumb|upright=1.15|[[Trygve J. B. Hoff]], editor of [[Farmand]], (left) and Austrian economist [[Ludwig von Mises]] (middle) at the Mont Pelerin Society in 1947]]\nJones outlines how, after the catastrophes of [[World War II]], [[Friedrich Hayek]] convened a group of intellectuals to combat the trend of increasing government intervention in the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]] and \"develop an organizational and intellectual strategy\" to \"defend the core tenets of...the freedom of the individual.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|30}} This group called itself the [[Mont Pelerin Society]], after the venue of its first meeting in Vevey, Switzerland.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ebenstein|first1=Alan|title=Friedrich Hayek: A Biography|date=2014|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781466886766|page=146}}</ref> The society set out to develop a neoliberal alternative to, on the one hand, the [[laissez-faire]] economic consensus that had collapsed with the [[Great Depression]] and, on the other, [[New Deal]] liberalism and British [[social democracy]], collectivist trends which they believed posed a threat to [[individual freedom]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|33}} A distinct neoliberal worldview, Jones contends, emerged \"on the foundations of the critique of New Deal liberalism and social democracy\" developed by the intellectuals of the Society.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|85}}\n\nJones finds three Mont Pelerin individuals particularly influential: [[Karl Popper]], [[Ludwig von Mises]], and [[Friedrich Hayek]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|33}} Popper, in his book ''[[The Open Society and its Enemies]]'', criticized thinkers from [[Plato]] to [[Karl Marx]] for valuing the collective over the individual and derided teleological [[historicism]] (a theory which holds that history unfolds inexorably according to universal laws) as a threat to [[individualism]]\u2014which he believed underpins [[Western civilization]]\u2014because it reduces the individual to \"a cog in the machine\" of history and empowers governments to engage in the sorts of \"Utopian engineering\" that has motivated communists, socialists, and [[Nazis]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|37\u201349}} Mises, in his book ''[[Bureaucracy (book)|Bureaucracy]]'', argued the superiority of the private market motivated by [[profit (economics)|profit]] over the bureaucratic management inherent in government.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|49\u201357}} Hayek, in his book ''[[The Road to Serfdom]]'', argued central planning was impossible because no individual or group could ever possess the requisite knowledge to direct the economic activity of millions of people.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|57\u201373}}\n\nThe early Mont Pelerin Society, Jones notes, had little effect on political policy. Instead, it acted as \"a siren call, a warning about the tragic possibilities of moving in the direction\" of greater collectivist government intervention \"which Western politics, economy, and society seemed to be moving.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|84}} Importantly, Jones argues it helped to \"create a transatlantic neoliberal network that would...combat the [[New Deal]] and social-democratic political establishments in Britain and the United States\", \"combat the forces of [[collectivism]]\", and refine neoliberal thought into a workable set of policies.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|32}}\n\n===Second phase: Emergence of a transatlantic neoliberal network (1950\u20131980)===\nJones outlines how a transatlantic network of neoliberal intellectuals, businessmen, journalists, university departments, and think tanks arose between 1950 and 1980 and, building on the foundations of the critiques of [[New Deal]] liberalism and [[social democracy]] of the early neoliberals, refined and popularized neoliberal ideas to the point that \"they eventually seemed the natural alternative to liberal or [[social democracy|social democratic]] policies\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|153}} This network would serve \"almost like a kind of Neoliberal International\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|218}} that would be highly influential in the later adoption of neoliberal policies by the governments of the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|134}} During this time, the locus of neoliberal thought shifted from Europe to America, with the American economist [[Milton Friedman]] becoming its most influential proponent\u2014its \"beating heart\", as Jones describes it.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|135}} Neoliberalism, according to Jones, evolved from an attempt to find a middle way between [[laissez-faire]] capitalism and collectivism into a \"faith in free markets\", often articulating \"individual liberty in apocalyptic terms as a struggle between free societies and [[communist]] [[totalitarianism]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|345,116}} Neoliberals of the era emphasized the need to recover \"lost truths\" from [[classical liberalism]], including the value of [[individual liberty]], the [[invisible hand]] of the free market, and the virtues of [[limited government]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|101}} By the 1960s, Jones contends, neoliberal thought had established a \"distinct and coherent identity\" centered around \"individual liberty, free markets, spontaneous order, the price mechanism, competition, consumerism, deregulation, and rational self-interest.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|132}} Additionally, during this period a body of policy prescriptions was injected into neoliberalism.\n\nJones points to an early essay by [[Milton Friedman]] entitled [https://miltonfriedman.hoover.org/objects/57816/neoliberalism-and-its-prospects?ctx=b8c0f32e-f5a4-4e53-ba3d-cf017b993579&idx=0 \"Neoliberalism and its Prospects\"] as a \"bridge\" between the first phase of neoliberal thought\u2014dominated by European conerns\u2014and the second phase, centered in the United States and concerned more with economic freedom and the superiority of markets.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|6}} Jones considers the essay a \"useful marker of the moment when neoliberalism became a self-conscious political and economic concept in the United States\", as it was one of the first instances in which an American writer claimed the neoliberal moniker.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|96}} In the essay Friedman makes a quintessentially first-phase argument for a \"new faith\" between [[collectivism]], which he believed leads to an over-mighty state, and [[laissez-faire]] economics, which he believed fostered the development of over-mighty individuals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Friedman |first1=Milton |title=Neo-Liberalism and its Prospects |url=https://miltonfriedman.hoover.org/objects/57816/neoliberalism-and-its-prospects?ctx=b8c0f32e-f5a4-4e53-ba3d-cf017b993579&idx=0 |accessdate=25 July 2019 |publisher=Farmand |date=17 February 1951}}</ref><ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|96}} However, the essay marked a \"symbolic cutting off point\" in neoliberal thought, signifying the point in time when neoliberalism began to shift away from the early \"middle way\" arguments to a more strident belief in free markets. Friedman himself advocated a level of government intervention in the essay which he would never again publicly support.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|97}}\n\n====Academic thought====\nAccording to Jones: \"After 1945, a distinct neoliberal worldview was built on the foundations of the critique of [[New Deal]] liberalism and [[social democracy]] synthesized in the writings of [[Ludwig von Mises]], [[Friedrich Hayek]], and [[Karl Popper]]...Its main tenets\u2014philosophical, political, and economic\u2014were worked out in detail by scholars such as [[Milton Friedman]], [[George Stigler]], [[Gary Becker]], [[James Buchanan]], and [[Gordon Tullock]], as well as Hayek and Mises.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|85}}\n\nJones asserts that the [[Chicago school of economics]], of which Friedman and Stigler were a part, was \"perhaps the most influential group in terms of the development of transatlantic neoliberal politics\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|89}} In the 1950s, 1960s, and 1970s Chicago economists published influential works arguing for [[free market]] policies and extending free market analyses into new regions (e.g. law and regulation). They painted a hostile portrait of [[trade unions]] and presented [[monopoly|monopolies]] as mostly benign.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|92\u201393}}\n\nThe theories of [[regulatory capture]], [[public choice theory]], and [[rational choice theory]] all became influential to neoliberal thought, according to Jones, because they connected the market to politics and the public sector, and helped the neoliberal view of free markets seep into mainstream public and political consciousness.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|126\u2013133}} The economist George Stigler argued that government regulatory bodies often become captured by private industry, so that these bodies act in the interests of private corporations rather than in the public's interest\u2014a notion known as \"regulatory capture\". James Buchanan and Gordon Tullock, considered the \"fathers of public choice theory\", emphasized the imperfections of political institutions and constitutional mechanisms, and argued voters have a tendency to vote their own interest rather than in the public interest.\n\n====Milton Friedman and monetarism====\n[[File:Portrait of Milton Friedman.jpg|thumb|[[Milton Friedman]]]]\n[[Milton Friedman]] became a leading figure of neoliberal thought and a prominent public intellectual in the 1950s. An American, Friedman was less influenced by the effects of [[World War II]] than by the subsequent [[Cold War]] between the [[United States]] and the [[Soviet Union]]. Jones argues that for neoliberals \"the Cold War necessitated the unambiguous advocacy of the superiority of the market\", and Friedman framed the \"war of ideas\" between [[socialism]] and free-market [[capitalism]] as a \"life-or-death struggle.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|101,120}}\n\nJones argues that \"Friedman's significant contribution to neoliberal thought was his connection of [[economic freedom]] with [[political freedom]]\", which he made in his popular book ''[[Capitalism and Freedom]]'' (which Jones describes as the \"American ''[[Road to Serfdom]]''\").<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|116}} Friedman argued that free markets and liberal democracy are inseparable, that the market guarantees basic political freedoms by ensuring that alternatives are always available (e.g. alternative employment options or alternative goods), guarantees equality by separating divorcing economic activities from reasons unrelated to an individual's [[productivity]], and protects dissent by separating economic power (i.e. the ability to make money) from political power (in other words, politicians cannot deprive an individual of employment if they express political dissent).<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|117,121}} Friedman consistently pointed out his view that \"increases in economic freedom have gone hand in hand with increases in political and civil freedom and have led to increased prosperity; competitive capitalism and freedom have become inseparable\", and pointed to countries like [[China]] under [[Deng Xiaoping]] and [[Chile]] to justify this.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|121}}\n\nJones notes that Friedman was a harsh critic of government intervention in the economy. A key point of ''[[Capitalism and Freedom]]'', according to Jones, was outlining government failure, including in the areas of railroad regulation, [[labor law]], [[monetary policy|monetary]] reform, agriculture, [[public housing]], [[social security]] legislation, [[foreign aid]], [[urban redevelopment]], and [[income tax]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|118}} In ''[[A Monetary History of the United States]]'', Friedman blamed the [[Great Depression]] on overly tight monetary policy by the [[Federal Reserve]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|202}} Friedman linked [[New Deal]] liberalism with [[socialism]] and [[communism]], while he considered his own ideas as a part of the [[classical liberalism|classical liberal]] family.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|119}}\n\nFriedman's development of the [[macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] theory [[monetarism]] was particularly influential to neoliberalism. Jones argues that the [[Keynesian]] consensus that had dominated political thought in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]] for decades had prioritized low [[unemployment]] over [[inflation]]. In contrast, by the 1950s neoliberal thinkers began to emphasize inflation.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|193}} Friedman ultimately developed [[monetarism]], a [[macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] theory dealing with [[inflation]] and the [[supply of money]] that suggested that the Keynesian view that government can achieve [[full employment]] at the cost of limited inflation was incorrect and would lead to higher inflation in the [[Long run and short run|long run]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|207}} Friedman argued that governments and central banks, rather than focusing on employment, should focus on ensuring a constant and predictable level of [[monetary inflation|monetary growth]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|207}} Jones describes monetarism as \"the most consistent, systematic, and significant alternative economic strategy to Keynesian demand management and fine-tuning\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|201}} This, according to Jones, primed neoliberal theory for political acceptance in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]], who would experience persistent [[stagflation]] during the 1970s. Jones sums it up as such: \"Friedman's monetarist analysis and market solutions grabbed people's attention as a ready-made and plausible alternative strategy [to Keynesianism] when the economy began to unravel [in the 1970s] under the weight of stagflation\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|212}}\n\n====Think tanks====\nIn Britain and the United States, the neoliberal right built a \"dazzling array of think tanks\", which became the preferred vehicle of neoliberal thinkers.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|336}} Notable among these, according to Jones, were the [[American Enterprise Institute]], the [[Foundation for Economic Education]], the [[Institute of Economic Affairs]], the [[Heritage Foundation]], the [[Cato Institute]], the [[Adam Smith Institute]], and a group of think tanks emanating out of the [[Atlas Network|Atlas Foundation]], including the [[Fraser Institute]], the Fisher Institute, and the [[Manhattan Institute]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|134}} These think tanks brought politicians and businesspeople into contact with neoliberal ideas and thinkers and raised the public profile of free-market policies. In particular, the Heritage Foundation had a significant influence on US president [[Ronald Reagan]]\u2014claiming on its website that nearly two-thirds of the proposals they suggested to him in their policy guide ''[[Mandate for Leadership]]'' were implemented<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blasko |first1=Andrew |title=REAGAN AND HERITAGE: A Unique Partnership |url=https://www.heritage.org/conservatism/commentary/reagan-and-heritage-unique-partnership |website=The Heritage Foundation |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\u2014while the Adam Smith Institute had appreciable sway with the [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher government]]. Jones notes that many of these institutes were funded by wealthy businessmen, such as [[Charles Koch]] and [[Joseph Coors]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|163\u2013164}}\n\n====Relation to conservatism====\nFree market economics has been associated with the [[political right]], but Jones emphasizes that it is \"but one branch\" of it.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|138}} In the United States, he argues that the right had a number of often-competing interests (principally [[Traditionalist conservatism|traditionalism]], [[anticommunism]], and [[neoliberalism]]), but that the \"distinctive feature of the conservative revival in the 1950s and 1960s was the ability of its disparate elements to unite under the banners of [[anticommunism]] and [[states' rights]]\"\u2014a union that became known as \"[[fusionism]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|140}} This union, which Jones largely credits [[William F. Buckley Jr.]] for achieving, led to the growth of a conservative establishment that would, after decades of decline, rival its liberal opponents. This \"pave[d] the way for the later electoral successes of Ronald Reagan,\" which would usher in neoliberal policies.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|146}}\n\n===Third phase: Policy implementation (1980 onward)===\n{{Quote box|quote = \"The demise of the postwar economic settlement had been hastened by a series of catastrophic events: the [[Vietnam War]], the first [[1973 oil crisis|oil shock of 1973]], and the near collapse of [[industrial relations]] in Britain. The Keynes-inspired policies that governments had relied on to deliver a golden age of prosperity and rising incomes for a generation after 1945 seemed exhausted. The collapse of the [[Bretton Woods system|Bretton Woods international monetary system]] in 1971 indicated the end of the experiment with [[fixed exchange rates]]. The assumption that there was a relatively simple and manipulable trade-off between [[inflation]] and [[employment]], the famous [[Phillips Curve]]...proved to be a dangerous illusion...In both Britain and the United States, the appearance of [[stagflation]]...meant that governments felt forced to change course.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|1\u20132}}|align = right |width = 20%}}\nJones notes that there were two major issues facing the United States and the United Kingdom at the end of the 1960s: the instability of the [[Bretton Woods system|Bretton Woods international monetary system]] and high [[inflation]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|219\u2013220}} As Jones describes it: \"the late 1960s and early 1970s brought a succession of economic shocks that undermined the postwar international monetary system and pushed the world economy into stormy waters. The final stage in the shift in economic strategy in Britain and the United States, the reason neoliberal ideas found a receptive audience, was the force of these events.\" The proposed neoliberal solutions of [[monetarism]], [[deregulation]], and [[trade union]] reform, as well as the wealth of neoliberal arguments against the prevailing Keynesian demand management, provided a \"powerfully compelling logic\", and neoliberal policies were soon adopted by British and American politicians.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|15}} Yet these economic solutions acted as mere \"Trojan horses for a more polemical neoliberal faith in free markets\", which would come to dominate politics in the United States and the United Kingdom.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|13}}\n[[Image:US Historical Inflation.svg|thumb|Rate of inflation in the United States (1914-2009)|left]]\n\nNeoliberal policies, according to Jones, were first introduced in the United States by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] president [[Jimmy Carter]] and in the United Kingdom by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] prime minister [[James Callaghan]]. However, their approaches were examples of \"governments of the left who accept[ed] the logic of the technical insights of [[Milton Friedman|Friedman]] and [[George Stigler|Stigler]] in terms of macroeconomic strategy or deregulation without also importing their neoliberal philosophies\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|253}} It would be their successors, [[Ronald Reagan]] in the United States and [[Margaret Thatcher]] in the United Kingdom, who Jones argues embodied the neoliberal belief in the \"supremacy of the free market\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|268}} They would also have the greatest impact on neoliberal policy implementation, successfully advancing agendas of deregulation, lower taxes, and market liberalization.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|270}} He emphasizes the importance of the transatlantic neoliberal network on Reagan and Thatcher, noting that \"many of their most important advisers, government colleagues, and supporters were drawn from the transatlantic neoliberal network\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|268}}\n\n====Jimmy Carter and Paul Volcker====\nJones argues that the implementation of neoliberal policy in the United States began with US president [[Jimmy Carter]], who Jones notes had been strongly influenced by neoliberal economist [[George Stigler]].<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|249}} During the [[presidency of Jimmy Carter|Carter presidency]] (1977\u20131981) the airline, trucking, and financial industries were deregulated.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|249}}\n\nJones suggests that \"perhaps the single most important economic policy decision made by Carter was his appointment of [[Paul Volcker]] in August 1979 to replace [[G. William Miller|[George William] Miller]] as [[chairman of the Federal Reserve]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|250}} Volcker aggressively and successfully targeted [[inflation]] by raising interest rates,<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Neill |first1=William L. |title=The Jimmy Carter Administration |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/United-States/The-Gerald-R-Ford-administration#ref613295 |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> bringing inflation down from a high point of nearly 15% in 1980 to 3%.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|252}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Inflation, consumer prices (annual %) |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/FP.CPI.TOTL.ZG?end=2018&locations=US&start=1960 |website=World Bank |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Ronald Reagan====\n[[File:Official Portrait of President Reagan 1981.jpg|thumb|Ronald Reagan presidential portrait]]\nIn 1981, [[Ronald Reagan]] became [[president of the United States]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronald Reagan |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/presidents/ronald-reagan/ |website=The White House |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref> Jones argues that the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] \"followed neoliberal principles influenced particularly by the ideas of [[Friedrich Hayek]], [[Milton Friedman]], [[George Stigler]], and [[Pat Buchanan]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}} This can be seen in the four policy proposals Jones argues Reagan prioritized:<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}} \n# Increased [[deregulation]] and [[market liberalization]]\n# Tighter control of the [[money supply]]\n# [[Tax cuts]]\n# Cuts to [[public spending]]\n\nThe administration lifted economic controls on oil, busted the [[Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization (1968)|air traffic controller's union]] and fired all the striking workers (in the United States most air traffic controllers are employed by the federal government<ref>{{cite web |title=Occupational Outlook Handbook, Air Traffic Controllers |url=https://www.bls.gov/ooh/transportation-and-material-moving/air-traffic-controllers.htm#tab-3 |website=Bureau of Labor Statistics, U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>), and implemented [[Reagan tax cuts|significant tax cuts]], including reducing the top marginal tax rate from 70% to 28%.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}}<ref>{{cite act |date=22 October 1986 |legislature=United States Congress |title=Title I\u2014Individual Income Tax Provisions |url=http://legisworks.org/sal/100/stats/STATUTE-100-Pg2096.pdf |language=}}</ref> Jones argues that Reagan's tax cuts were motivated by arguments including the philosophy of [[limited government]] promoted by Friedman and other neoliberals; the idea developed by economist [[Arthur Laffer]] that [[tax revenue]] would increase as [[tax rates]] dropped because, as Jones summarized Laffer's argument, \"more people would pay taxes and fewer would attempt tax avoidance\"; and the belief that lower taxes lead to increased investment by the wealthy, which boosts [[economic growth]] and thereby benefits all members of society (a belief that would become known as [[trickle-down economics]]).<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}}\n\n====Margaret Thatcher====\n[[Margaret Thatcher]] became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] in 1979,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Hugo |title=Margaret Thatcher |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Margaret-Thatcher#ref214939 |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref> ushering in a broad range of [[Supply-side economics|supply-side]] reforms and [[monetarism|monetarist]] macroeconomic policies.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|263}} Jones contends that \"the key early battle for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government had been driving through a tough slew of measures to bring the deficit under control and create the conditions for economic recovery in the famous [[1981 United Kingdom budget|budget of 1981]].\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|260\u2013261}} The government combined budget cuts with a \"reorientation of the tax system to provide greater incentives for entrepreneurship.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|261}}\n\nMonetarist policy had first been introduced by the [[Labour government, 1974\u20131979|Callaghan's Labour government]], which had introduced monetary targets and cash limits.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|242}} Monetarist policy was continued under the Thatcher government. Jones places \"the major differences, and the real departure in economic terms, between the Callaghan government and the Conservatives lay in their radicalization of microeconomic policy through various market-based supply-side reforms and their importation of market mechanisms into public service provision.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|262}}\n\n====Effects====\n{{Quote box|quote = \"Neoliberalism transformed British, American, and global politics. At the dawn of the twenty-first century, the triumph of the free market was almost universally accepted by mainstream politicians, public officials, and civil servants. More important, the distinctive neoliberal brand of free market individualism had prevailed over alternative forms of managed market-based capitalism.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|329}}|align = right |width = 20%}}\nJones believes that the \"neoliberal contribution to the political changes of the last third of the twentieth century in Britain and the United States have been massive\", and includes not only the considerable reforms that Reagan and Thatcher implemented but also the effects neoliberalism had on introducing \"a new economic policy framework...[that] governed the policies and ambitions of [[Bill Clinton]], [[Tony Blair]], [[Gordon Brown]], and [[Barack Obama]]\".<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|271}} Neoliberalism resulted in a \"broad breakdown of the characteristic mid-twentieth century belief in the efficacy and moral superiority of government and collective action\" in favor of a belief in the efficacy of markets.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|335}} Additionally, he notes that neoliberalism was extended into international development and trade through the [[structural adjustment]] policies of the [[International Monetary Fund]], the [[World Bank]], and the [[World Trade Organization]], which were dominated by neoliberal economists in the late 20th century.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|332}} He argues that this ultimately had mixed effects:\n<blockquote>\n\"Some of the most powerful insights of [neoliberal] thinkers did help to address pressing social and economic issues by increasing homeownership or stabilizing persistently high [[inflation]]. But such successes were not so numerous as to make the effect of transatlantic neoliberal politics anything better than ambivalent...neoliberal policies tended to affect the most vulnerable members of society in the harshest ways.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|338}}\n\nDuring the last two decades of the [20th] century, [[economic inequality|inequality]] (the gap between rich and poor), [[poverty]], and [[homelessness]] all increased. [[Unemployment]] seemingly disappeared as a major problem in the immediate postwar years but returned with a vengeance after the 1970s. Inflation...[was] cowed...by the uncompromising policies of [[central bankers]] and pliant politicians in the early 1980s. In Britain, unemployment and inflation returned during another deep [[recession]] by the time Thatcher was forced from office in October 1990.\"<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|330}}\n</blockquote>\n\nFurthermore, Jones believes that \"the most important reason for the [[2008 financial crisis|[2008] financial crisis]] was the direct result of neoliberal policies\" of financial deregulation.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|340}} He argues the neoliberal \"faith in markets had become divorced from reality\", with crisis-level effects.<ref name =\"Masters\"/>{{rp|330}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe book was a finalist for the Western Social Science Association's 2014 Presidents\u2019 Book Award and shortlisted for the 2012 [[Gladstone Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters of the Universe Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics |url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/9827.html |website=Princeton University Press |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref> It has received mixed reviews.\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' praised the book as a \"bold biography of a great idea\", describing it as a \"novel and comprehensive history of neoliberalism\" that, while \"a little thin on character sketches and economics\", is a \"strong work\" by a \"fair and nuanced writer\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Birth of Neoliberalism |url=https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2012/10/13/new-brooms |accessdate=24 July 2019 |publisher=The Economist |date=13 October 2012}}</ref> James McAuley, writing in the magazine [[Prospect (magazine)|''Prospect'']], claims that Jones \"has produced an ideal kind of intellectual history\u2014an investigation that shows that the reigning free market paradigm was not the inevitable end of progressive policy developments...it was instead a programme that was actively promoted by a network of intellectuals and institutions, and it depended on external political circumstances for its success.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=McAuley |first1=James |title=The shock of the neoliberal |url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/arts-and-books/neoliberalism-reagan-thatcher-hayek-friedman |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Prospect |date=30 January 2013}}</ref> [[Alejandro Chafuen]], former president of the [[Atlas Economic Research Foundation]] and member of the [[Mont Pelerin Society]], writes in ''[[Forbes]]'' that he appreciates that the author's \"lengthy exposition of the views shared by these outstanding economists (Friedman, Hayek, and Mises) might encourage many to pay attention to their works.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/realspin/2013/01/16/think-tanks-are-they-the-masters-of-the-universe/#413dc4c5264a|title=Think Tanks: Are They The Masters Of The Universe?|last1=Chafuen|first1=Alejandro|date=16 January 2013|accessdate=3 August 2019|publisher=Forbes}}</ref> Jennifer Burns, writing in ''[[The American Prospect]]'' states that \"Jones\u2019s provocative if disconcerting argument deserves wide consideration. So does ''Masters of the Universe'', which does much to help explain the aftermath of 2008 and the ways in which political responses that might have defined another era seem unthinkable in ours.\"<ref name=\"Prospect\"/> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called it \"a cerebral, pertinent exegesis on the thinking behind the rise of the New Right\", though notes it is \"too scholarly for most general readers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/daniel-stedman-jones/masters-universe/|title=Masters of the Universe|date=14 July 2012|accessdate=24 July 2019|publisher=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref> Glenn C. Altschuler, writing in the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', states that the author \"draws on extensive archival research and interviews with politicians, policy-makers and intellectuals to provide a lucid, richly detailed examination of the evolution of the free-market ideology since the end of World War II.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/book-reviews/2012/10/28/Masters-of-the-Universe-the-failures-of-conservative-economic-theory-and-the-practice-is-worse/stories/201210280215|title='Masters of the Universe': the failures of economic theory (and the practice is worse)|last1=Altshuler|first1=Glenn C.|date=27 October 2012|accessdate=3 August 2019|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette}}</ref>\n\nScott Sumner, writing in the magazine [[Reason (magazine)|''Reason'']], calls the book \"a balanced and informative study of neoliberal thinkers\", however he believes that Jones, in his criticism of neoliberalism as prone to [[market fundamentalism]], \"misses the bigger picture for three reasons: He underestimates the extent to which neoliberalism was built on impressive economic research, he overstates the extent to which neoliberalism became associated with modern conservatism, and he overstates the neoliberals' opposition to government\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sumner |first1=Scott |title=The Neoliberal Revolution |url=https://reason.com/2013/01/22/the-neoliberal-revolution/ |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Reason |date=February 2013}}</ref> Daniel Ben-Ami, writing in ''[[Financial Times]]'', praised the book as \"clearly written and relevant to a wide audience\", noting it \"incorporates a wealth of primary material\", although he states Jones \"fails to capture fully the failures or successes of neoliberal thought\".<ref name=\"Financial-Times\" /> Edward Nik-Khah, writing for the [[Economic History Association]], calls it an \"accessible introduction\" to the intellectual history of neoliberalism, criticizing it only for \"some of Jones\u2019s framing choices\" which \"get in the way of understanding [the] complex history [of neoliberalism].\"<ref name=\"Edward\">{{cite news |last1=Edward |first1=Nik-Khah |title=Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics |url=https://eh.net/book_reviews/masters-of-the-universe-hayek-friedman-and-the-birth-of-neoliberal-politics/ |accessdate=24 July 2019 |publisher=Economic History Association |date=November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Kelly (professor)|Paul Kelly]], writing for the ''[[London School of Economics]] Review of Books'', criticizes the book as being \"overambitious\", lamenting that \"the connections between the various [neoliberal] thinkers are ambiguous, fortuitous or at best under explained\" and stating that the book \"sadly fails to deliver on its promise\" of delivering \"an analysis and critique of the dominant language of political economy of the last four decades \u2013 neoliberalism\"; he also criticizes the book for \"assuming a polemical concept (neoliberalism) as an ideological unity\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Paul |title=Book Review: Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics |url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/politicsandpolicy/book-review-masters-of-the-universe-hayek-friedman-and-the-birth-of-neoliberal-politics/ |accessdate=30 July 2019 |publisher=London School of Economics Review of Books |date=4 November 2012}}</ref> [[Kenneth Minogue]], writing for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', claims that while the book \"has intelligent things to say\" its \"historical virtues are compromised by more adjectival attitudinizing than a chronicler of history should allow himself\"; for instance, \"free-market ideas are characterized as 'aggressive,' 'relentless' and 'uncritical,' culminating in the description of market enthusiasm as a 'holy grail' and the use of a variety of religious metaphors designed to suggest that it is irrational.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minogue |first1=Kenneth |title=The Death and Life of Liberal Economics |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443995604578002432460754000 |accessdate=24 July 2019 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=26 October 2012}}</ref> Greg Kaza, writing in the ''[[Quarterly Journal of Austrian Economics]]'' published by [[The Mises Institute]], criticized the book for neglecting to include information from the archives of [[Ludwig von Mises]] and for selective reporting on the 1960s-era U.S. civil rights movement.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kaza |first1=Greg |title=Review of Masters of the Universe: Hayek, Friedman, and the Birth of Neoliberal Politics by Daniel Stedman Jones |journal=Quarterly Journal of Austrian Economics |date=2 February 2015 |volume=17 |issue=4 |pages=543\u2013549 |url=https://mises.org/library/review-masters-universe-hayek-friedman-and-birth-neoliberal-politics-daniel-stedman-jones |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe title has been criticized by Edward Nik-Khah, who notes that the book does not explicitly state who, exactly, the \"masters of the universe\" are.<ref name=\"Edward\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* For further analysis of the intellectual development of neoliberalism: {{cite book |last1=Burgin |first1=Angus |title=The Great Persuasion: Reinventing Free Markets since the Great Depression |date=2015 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0674033184}}\n* For a survey of early neoliberal thought by a number of academics: {{cite book |editor1-last=Mirowski |editor1-first=Philip |editor2-last=Plehwe |editor2-first=Dieter |title=The Road from Mont P\u00e8lerin: The Making of the Neoliberal Thought Collective |date=2009 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-03318-4}}\n* For a short summary of neoliberalism: {{cite book |last1=Steger |first1=Manfred B. |last2=Roy |first2=Ravi K. |title=Neoliberalism: A Very Short Introduction |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199560516}}\n* For a positive analysis of neoliberalism:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shenk |first1=Timothy |title=The Long Shadow of Mont Pelerin |url=https://www.dissentmagazine.org/article/the-long-shadow-of-mont-pelerin |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Dissent |date=Fall 2013}}</ref> Yergin, Daniel; Stanislaw, Joseph (1998). [[The Commanding Heights|''The Commanding Heights: The Battle for the World Economy'']]. Free Press. {{ISBN|978-0684835693}}.\n* For a [[Neo-Marxism|neo-Marxist]] critique and a description of the spread of neoliberalism:<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ritzer |first1=Georgy |title=A Brief History of Neoliberalism |journal=American Journal of Sociology |date=July 2007 |volume=113 |issue=1 |url=https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/520901?journalCode=ajs |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref> {{cite book |last1=Harvey |first1=David |title=A Brief History of Neoliberalism |date=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0199283279}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neoliberalism]]\n[[Category:2012 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books in political philosophy]]\n", "name_user": "Jaydavidmartin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelation to conservatism:removed erroneous \"that\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masters_of_the_Universe_(book)"}
{"title_page": "Audrey Le Morvan", "text_new": "{{short description|French para table tennis player}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Audrey Le Morvan\n| nickname = \n| image = Audrey_Le_Morvan_Slovenia_Open_2012_2.jpeg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Le Morvan in 2012\n| nationality = \n| sport = [[Para table tennis]]\n| disability = [[Amelia (birth defect)|Amelia]] of left arm\n| disability_class = C10\n| event = \n| club = \n| coach = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1987|10|05|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lannion]], [[France]]\n| hometown = [[Louannec]], France\n| residence = [[Nantes]], France\n| retired = 2013\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{FRA}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[para table tennis]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{FRA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004 Athens]]|[[Table tennis at the 2004 Summer Paralympics - Women's team - Class 6-10|Team C6-10]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Paralympics - Women's team - Class 6-10|Team C6-10]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Table Tennis Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2006 Montreux|Singles C10}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2006 Montreux|Teams C9-10}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[European Para Table Tennis Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|2007 Kranksja Gora|Singles C10}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2003 Zagreb|Teams C10}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2005 Jesolo|Singles C10}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2005 Jesolo|Teams C9-10}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2011 Split|Teams C9-10}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2013 Lignano|Teams C9-10}}\n}}\n\n'''Audrey Le Morvan''' (born 5 October 1987) is a former [[French people|French]] [[para table tennis]] player who competed in international level events. She participated in three [[Paralympic Games]] and was a double bronze medalist. She was born with a deformed left forearm. She has competed in team events with [[Claire Mairie]] and [[Thu Kamkasomphou]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.ipttc.org/en/profiles/517|title=Audrey Le Morvan - IPTTF Profile|last=|first=|date=12 March 2020|website=International Para Table Tennis Federation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://france-paralympique.fr/paralympiens/audrey-le-morvan/|title=Audrey Le Morvan - France Paralympique (in French)|last=|first=|date=12 March 2020|website=France Paralympique|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|audrey-le-morvan|Audrey le Morvan}}\n* {{CPSF profile|audrey-le-morvan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Le Morvan, Audrey}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lannion]]\n[[Category:Paralympic table tennis players of France]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French para table tennis player}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n| name = Audrey Le Morvan\n| nickname = \n| image = Audrey_Le_Morvan_Slovenia_Open_2012_2.jpeg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Le Morvan in 2012\n| nationality = \n| sport = [[Para table tennis]]\n|disability = [[Amelia (birth defect)|Amelia]] of left arm\n|disability_class = C10\n| event = \n| club = \n| coach = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1987|10|05|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lannion]], [[France]]\n| hometown = [[Louannec]], France\n| residence = [[Nantes]], France\n| retired= 2013\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{FRA}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Para table tennis]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{FRA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[